<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Likely to Impose Landing Ban on Yugoslav Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The 15-nation European Union (EU)
could start to impose a ban on all Yugoslav airlines in EU
airports within this month as a further reaction to the continuing
violence in Yugoslavia's province of Kosovo, the German government
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The landing ban would be a "clear signal" for Belgrade, German
government spokesman Otto Hauser said, adding the EU nations
reserved the right to impose other sanctions if Belgrade continued
to refuse to end the bloodshed in Kosovo and to allow the return
of refugees.
</P>
<P>
Hauser Wednesday also voiced doubt about the sincerity of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic who reportedly said Tuesday
that he was willing to grant Kosovo "a certain degree of
autonomy."
</P>
<P>
Milosevic should follow his words with deeds, Hauser said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe
told the German parliament Wednesday that the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) was due to decide next week under which
circumstances group troops would be sent to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He noted that NATO was considering for the moment only to
conduct air force operations against targets of Serbian security
forces in case of a military intervention.
</P>
<P>
"At issue is a concept for calculated actions with which the
NATO could, for example, react swiftly to severe human rights
violations and force the conflicting parties back to the
negotiating table, " Ruehe said.
</P>
<P>
The NATO ground troops would probably only be deployed to
monitor a peace or cease-fire agreement in Kosovo, Ruehe added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
