<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diana's Sons Plead for Mother to Rest in Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Princes William and Harry, sons
of late Princess Diana, appealed Wednesday to the British public
to let their mother rest in peace.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the two princes said constant reminders of her
death caused "nothing but pain to those she left behind."
</P>
<P>
They said they had been enormously comforted by public sympathy
since Diana's death a year ago, but they believed their mother
"would want people now to move on," according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued two days after the first anniversary
of the death of Diana, who was killed in a car accident in Paris
on August 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The princes marked the anniversary in a brief private church
service with other members of the royal family on holiday at the
rural Balmoral estate in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Although the royal remembrance was fairly low-key, thousands of
mourners still turned out at Diana's former Kensington Palace home
in London to lay flowers and light candles in her memory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
