<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Needs More International Aid: Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Hit severely by an
unexpected abnormal weather, the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) this year is facing a gloomy prospect in its
agricultural sector and needs more international aid, DPRK
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman for the Flood Damage Rehabilitation Committee and
director of the Agricultural Production Department of the
Agricultural Commission described the delivery of international
aid as "smooth."
</P>
<P>
They said in August alone, more than 100,000 tons of food and
other relief materials donated by the World Food Program, the
European Union and other international organizations and countries
arrived in DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by aid from the international community, they said,
the DPRK people are determined to solve the food problem by
themselves under any circumstances.
</P>
<P>
From the beginning of this year, the people have made
substantial preparations for farming with the general mobilization
of all, thus laid a foundation for increasing the grain output,
they said.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the officials said the freak weather hit the DPRK
in the latter half of the year caused serious damage to its
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
In July and August, east and west coastal areas including
Kangwon, south Phyongan and south Hwanghae provinces and Kaesong
suffered from cold weather, downpours and hails while Jagang and
Ryanggang provinces and other northern inland areas were hit by
off-season cold weather.
</P>
<P>
According to conservative data available as of late August,
Kangwon, north and south Hwanghae, north and south Hamgyong, north
and south Phyongan provinces, Kaesong and other affected areas
were losing lives, and 128,927 hectares of arable land were
covered by water or washed away and more than 10,000 houses were
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The officials said representatives of the U.N. Office for the
Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs, the World Food Program, the
United Nations Development Program and other international
organizations arrived in the DPRK several days ago to learn about
the damage on the spot.
</P>
<P>
The Korean people, who are suffering from the heavy damage
caused by natural disasters and shortage of food, are working hard
to solve the food problem and resume agricultural production at an
early date, the officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
