<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Duma Urges Yeltsin to Fire Central Bank Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The State Duma voted
overwhelmingly Wednesday to call on President Boris Yeltsin to
dismiss Central Bank governor Sergei Dubinin.
</P>
<P>
The demand was contained in a resolution passed 267-2 in the
lower house of parliament on the socio-economic and financial
situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Duma described the actions taken by the government and the
Central Bank to overcome the financial crisis as "unsatisfactory
and belated."
</P>
<P>
Dubinin, however, has reportedly told Duma deputies that he
does not intend to resign.
</P>
<P>
The Duma told the bank to propose candidates for the bank's
directors, and instructed the government, in drafting a program
for pulling the country out of the crisis, to be guided by the
relevant provisions in a statement made by the trilateral
commission representing the State Duma, the Federation Council and
the cabinet, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It urged the Central Bank to tighten control over the
activities of crediting institutions, take steps to protect
savings, restore the liquidity of commercial banks and enable the
banking system to function properly.
</P>
<P>
The Duma also instructed the government to hold urgent
consultations with Belarus and other member nations of the
Commonwealth of Independent States on coordinating efforts to
stabilize the national financial, crediting and monetary systems.
</P>
<P>
It called for the imposition of state monopoly on production
and sales of alcoholic products and a suspension of tenders and
auctions in sales of the stock of natural monopolies and
strategically important installations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
