<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Passes Law on Grain Storing and Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria has adopted a law on
grain storing and trading, an effort to keep the country fed on
all occasions, the Agrarian Finance Daily reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the new law, any individual or organization must
have the permit from the Agriculture Ministry to trade in
grains. Violators will be fined 3 million to 50 million lev (about
1,700 to 28,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
With the permit from the Agriculture Ministry, individuals or
organizations can also operate grain silos, after making an
initial investment of at least 100 million lev, or 57,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
All the silos are required to have a storing capacity of at
least 3,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The law also regulates that a system of strategic grain reserve
must be set up in case of major natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria suffered an acute grain shortage at the beginning of
1997 due to improper management and over-export and, as a result, had
to import large quantities from Poland.
</P>
<P>
This year, its wheat output is expected to reach 3.38 million
tons, about 200,000 to 500,000 tons of which can be exported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
