<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Sacked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim was dismissed from his
posts Wednesday without any reasons given.
</P>
<P>
His dismissal was announced in a short statement by the Prime
Minister's Department issued late Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Anwar was also removed from all other
positions held by him in his capacity as deputy prime minister
and finance minister.
</P>
<P>
The Yang di-Pertuan Agong (the Supreme Head of State or the
King) has been informed of Anwar's removal from the cabinet, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The letter of his sacking was believed to have been delivered
to Anwar at his house by a top government official at about 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
The statement did not give any reason for the dismissal of
Anwar. Anwar and Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad had reportedly
been at odds over monetary policies as the ringgit depreciated by
40 percent against the U.S. dollar since July last year following
the onset of the economic crisis that was sparked off by
speculative currency attacks.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir favored stimulating business with lower interest rates
while Anwar along with Bank Negara (State Bank), whose governor
and deputy governor resigned four days ago, had adhered to
International Monetary Fund style policies particularly in
maintaining tight monetary policies including high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's economy slipped into recession with gross domestic
product declining 2.8 percent and 6.8 percent in the first two
quarters of the year respectively.
</P>
<P>
Anwar's dismissal came a day after the government announced new
controls to protect the falling ringgit and to boost efforts to
revitalize the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Teams of police personnel were seen entering the Deputy Prime
Minister's Office in Jalan Dato Onn and the Treasury in the Jalan
Duta government complex in the evening.
</P>
<P>
Police were seen sealing off the road leading to Anwar's house
in Bukit Damansara and Federal Reserve Unit personnel were placed
on standby.
</P>
<P>
Anwar is also deputy president of the ruling United Malays
National Organization (UMNO). His fate as UMNO deputy president is
expected to be known when the party's supreme council is scheduled
to meet Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
No immediate comment could be obtained from Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad or Anwar.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, 51, was appointed deputy prime minister on December 1,
1993, succeeding Tun Ghafar Baba, and was declared on several
occasions as Mahathir's successor.
</P>
<P>
He was brought into the government by Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad in 1982 when he was initially made a deputy minister in
the Prime Minister's Department. He was later promoted to full
minister, moving from the portfolio of the then Culture, Youth and
Sports Ministry in June 1983, the Agriculture Ministry (July 1984)
and the Education Ministry (May 1986). He has been finance
minister since March 1991.
</P>
<P>
Besides his government and political posts, Anwar also held
several other posts. He was chairman of the Cabinet Committee on
Malpractices in the Government, deputy chairman of the National
Information Technology Council and deputy president of the
National Telecommunication Council. He was appointed earlier this
year deputy chairman of the National Economic Action Council.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was appointed chairman of the Development Council of the
World Bank/International Monetary Fund in April this year for a
two-year term.
</P>
<P>
Anwar is Member of Parliament for Permatang Pauh, a seat in
Pulau Pinang, a northern state in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, a graduate from the University of Malaya, received his
secondary education at the Malay College Kuala Kangsar, an elite
school reputed for producing many of the country's leaders in
government and business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Population to Grow in Next Decade, Expert Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Global population
growth is slowing, thanks to successful family planning programs,
but because of past high fertility, world population will continue
to grow by more than 80 million a year for at least the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
In mid-1999, the total world population will pass 6 million --
twice what it was in 1960.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made as Stan Bernstein, a senior research
advisor of the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA), briefed
reporters here Wednesday on "The State of World Population 1988"
report by the UNFPA.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled "The New Generations," was released
Wednesday by Nafis Sadik, the UNFPA's executive director, in
London. "This report focuses on two large generational groups --
younger and older, the relationship between them, and prospects
and challenges that they pose for future development," Bernstein
said.
</P>
<P>
More young people than ever are entering their childbearing
years. "Now there are over 1 billion people between the ages of 15
and 24," Bernstein said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the number and proportion of people over 65
are increasing at an unprecedented rate. The rapid growth of these
young and old "new generations" is challenging societies' ability
to provide education and health care for the young, and social,
medical and financial support for the elderly, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In some developing regions over the next two decades, young
people will swell the workforce compared to older and younger
dependents, the report said, adding that "this will create a
temporary opportunity to build human capital and spur long-term
development, before dependency levels go up against as populations
age."
</P>
<P>
Falling fertility and smaller families have prompted recent
well-publicized claims that the "population explosion" is over. On
the contrary, the UNFPA report said, adding that the world
population will continue to grow substantially for at least
another 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Declining fertility and mortality will produce a gradual
demographic shift towards an older population in all countries
over the next few decades, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Ageing populations will strain medical systems in many
developing countries which are still struggling to protect the
health of younger age groups, the report said. The burden of
disease will shift to older ages over the next several decades, it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Calls for Closer Military Ties With Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Indian Deputy
Chief of Staff M. R. Sharma called Wednesday for enhancing India's
military cooperation with Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Sharma, who arrived here earlier Wednesday, told a news
conference that the Indian armed forces have the capability to
train Kuwaiti troops.
</P>
<P>
"The two countries are very similar in the military equipment,
strategy as well as marine and air defense techniques," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharma said that he would discuss with Kuwaiti military
officials ways of promoting cooperation and exchanging information
between the two armies.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and India have expanded their political and economic
ties in recent years, but the military cooperation lacks
significant development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
