<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mixed Reactions on Malaysian Deputy PM's Dismissal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The dismissal of
Malaysia's Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Anwar
Ibrahim as announced by the Prime Minister's Department Wednesday
evening set off mixed reactions in the country.
</P>
<P>
Political party leaders such as United Malays National
Organization (UMNO) Secretary General Sabbaruddin Chik and Gerakan
(the People's Movement Party) President Lim Keng Yaik expressed
their shock over the announcement of Anwar's removal from the
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Chinese Association (MCA) President Ling Liong Sik
said his party respected Mahathir's decision.
</P>
<P>
They, all cabinet ministers, shared the view that it was Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad's "prerogative" to appoint or remove
ministers.
</P>
<P>
Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs Minister Megat Junid Megat
Ayob expressed his sadness over Anwar's sacking as he said he felt
sad because this is happening at a time when the country is facing
an economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Syed Hamid Albar said he believed the prime
minister had enough information to act against Anwar in the
national interest.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Action Party Secretary General Lim Kit Siang,
the opposition leader in Parliament, said in a statement that the
sacking had nullified whatever positive effects of the currency
control measure announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said it had also plunged Malaysia into an unprecedented
political crisis which would make economic turnaround and recovery
more distant and difficult.
</P>
<P>
Anwar's removal from the Cabinet was announced in a short
statement by the Prime Minister's Department issued late Wednesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
His dismissal was announced in a short statement by the Prime
Minister's Department issued late Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Anwar was also removed from all other
positions
held by him in his capacity as deputy prime minister and finance
minister.
</P>
