<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Rebound on US Sharemarket Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- An overnight rebound on Wall
Street lifted the Australian share market by more than two
percent, with the bourse recovering nearly all of its losses over
the past two days.
</P>
<P>
With buoyant Asian markets also lending support, the all
ordinaries index rose 57.8 points to 2516.0, as the Dow Jones
industrial average recorded its second biggest points gain ever
overnight.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. market added 288 points to 7827, a 3.8 percent gain,
after losing 512 points the day before.
</P>
<P>
The Australian federal government's announcements Wednesday on
forecasts for key economic indicators was also seen as positive.
</P>
<P>
On the Australian market, turnover was 284.46 million shares
traded at a value of 964.04 million Australian dollars (561.74
U.S. dollars), with rises outnumbering falls by 769 to 384.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index was up 91.5 points Wednesday to
4460.3.
</P>
<P>
The major banks all rose: National Australia Bank was up 41
cents to 22.06 Australian dollars, ANZ bank up 19 cents to 8.79
Australian dollars, Commonwealth Bank of Australia rose 60 cents
to 19.33 Australian dollars while Westpac bank closed 13.8 cents
higher at 9.438 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was up 32.6 points at 940.4.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP jumped 54.8 cents to 12.298 Australian
dollars, while fellow diversified resources concern Rio Tinto was
up 70.8 cents to 17.30 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index added 31.7 points to 878.8 as the bullion price
added 2.10 U.S. dollars per ounce to 279.80 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
