<HEADLINE> Namibian Troops to Continue Help Quell DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DURBAN (South Africa), September 2 (Xinhua) -- Namibian
President Sam Nujoma said here Wednesday that his country,
together with Zimbabwe and Angola, would not withdraw their
troops from the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) until they had
helped the Kinshasa government quell the rebel forces in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inaugural ceremony of the 12th summit of the
Non-Aligned Movement, Nujoma said the presence of Namibian,
Angola and Zimbabwean troops in the DRC was in line with
agreements of the Southern African Development Community.
</P>
<P>
The agreements compelled regional members to go to the rescue
of another member if requested. "We will leave only when the
(quell) job is done to the satisfaction of the government of the
Congo," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian president appealed NAM countries to reiterate the
principle of sovereignty, unity and territorial integrity of
states, and to oppose attempts to overthrow legitimate
governments by military force.
</P>
<P>
"We should not hesitate in condemning those that are found
guilty of such brutal acts," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
