<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Firmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar gained
more than half a U.S. cent Wednesday, buoyed by the release of
better than expected news on growth in the Australian economy.
</P>
<P>
The local dollar closed in Sydney at 58.27 U.S. cents from
57.65 U.S. cents Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics Wednesday said the gross
domestic product (GDP) grew by 3.9 percent during the past
financial year ending on June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The local unit jumped in early Wednesday afternoon trading from
58.26 U.S. cents to 58.43 U.S. cents after data showing that
economic growth had been solid in the financial year of 1997-1998
and Treasurer Peter Costello's announcement that the budget
forecast for growth for the financial year of 1998-1999 would be
revised to 2.75 percent from 3.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
Some dealers said the boost in the Australian dollar Wednesday
made up for last week's fall, but noted it is still undervalued.
</P>
<P>
The local currency was trading at 80.10 Japanese yen from 80.20
yen and 1.0186 German marks from 1.0103 marks. 
</P>
