<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, India to Hold Official Dialog on "Push-in" Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh and India will hold
an official dialogue next month to thrash out the "push-in" issue
that created border tensions between the two neighboring
countries, the Associated Press of Bangladesh (APB) reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
India's Home Affairs Secretary B.P. Singh will come to Dhaka
sometime in October on a visit and meet his Bangladeshi
counterpart Safiur Rahman, APB quoted a spokesman for the Ministry
of Foreign Affairs as saying.
</P>
<P>
Besides the "push-in" issue, the two officials are likely to
hold discussions on skirmishes between security forces and other
border-related issues, like smuggling, trespass and trafficking in
women and children.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the official said, the Indian home secretary was
supposed to arrive here this month, but his trip was deferred in
view of the devastating floods Bangladesh is now facing.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh formally requested India on August 25 to stop
pushing Bengali-speaking "Indian citizens" into Bangladesh in the
interest of the two countries, against the backdrop that India had
made a series of attempts to push what India called "illegal
Bangladeshi nationals" into the country.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad has reiterated
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina's assertion that "no Bangladeshi
nationals are staying illegally in India."
</P>
<P>
From mid-August on, the situation on the Bangladesh-India
border has become a bit tense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
