<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Gov't Indicts Benazir on Money Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss government has
indicted former Pakistani prime minister Benazir Bhutto on money
laundering and handed over incriminating evidence to Pakistani
authorities here Wednesday, a senior anti-corruption official
said.
</P>
<P>
Benazir and her husband Asif Ali Zardari stashed away an
estimated 500 million U.S. dollars in 30 Swiss banks, Chairman of
Pakistan's Ethesab Bureau (accountability cell) Saif -ur-Rehman
told a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
The original indictment order of Swiss Judge Daniel Devaud was
handed over by Swiss Charge D' Affairs to an additional secretary
of the Foreign Office here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This indictment order against Benazir Bhutto will be served on
her through the Chief Justice of Lahore High Court within a few
days because this court was hearing Bhutto's corruption cases.
</P>
<P>
Saif said he was "hopeful Benazir Bhutto and Asif Zardari are
awarded punishment within three to four months."
</P>
<P>
Despite request by Pakistan, the Swiss Government had refused
to make it a party to its investigation into the money laundering
case, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss Government, he said, initiated the probe on its own
after the Ehtesab Bureau provided photo copies of Swiss Banks
proving Bhutto's involvement in money laundering.
</P>
<P>
Under Swiss law, Bhutto will be given two options, either to
defend herself before a jury comprising a professional magistrate
and ten jurors drawn from amongst the population, or before a
Criminal court consisting of two judges.
</P>
<P>
The jury can give her as long as 10 years' imprisonment while
the two judges have the powers to hand her a maximum prison term
of 18 months if she is found guilty.
</P>
<P>
If Benazir refuses to receive the indictment order, the
Pakistani government will send it back to the Swiss government for
further legal proceedings.
</P>
<P>
If the Swiss court gives its decision against Benazir Bhutto
after hearing her, the Pakistani government will be obliged to
hand over her and her husband to Swiss authorities under an
existing extradition treaty between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Housing Market: Price Drop, But Not Recession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- House prices fell slightly in
August in Britain, but the drop does not signal the start of a
property recession, according to Halifax, UK's biggest mortgage
lender.
</P>
<P>
A survey by the bank showed that the average price of a home
has risen by 5.3 percent over the last year, but in August the
market went into reverse and prices dropped 0.1 percent compared
with July.
</P>
<P>
"This does not signal the start of a housing recession but does
continue to strengthen our belief that the market is only growing
at a moderate rate," the Halifax said.
</P>
<P>
The Halifax is standing by its earlier forecast that annual
house price inflation for the last three months of the year would
be around 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the bank dismissed a suggestion from London
financial City analysts that house prices were "coming off the
boil."
</P>
<P>
"The fact is that house prices have only been on the boil in
London where City analysts live, throughout the rest of the
country it has been much more moderate.
</P>
<P>
"The market is performing just as we expected and there are
upturn and downturns but not the boom and bust that we've seen in
the past," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier survey, however, Britain's housing
market appeared to be cooling, as house prices were falling for
the first time in 20 months.
</P>
<P>
Figures published by the Nationwide Building Society showed
that the annual rate of price rises was at its lowest since April
1997.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide Divisional Manager David Parry said, "Although one
month's figures should not be seen in isolation, persistently high
interest rates and weakening consumer confidence mean that house
prices are likely to be somewhat less robust in the coming
months."
</P>
<P>
"It is now clear that the house price inflation peaked towards
the end of 1997 and has been on a modest downward trend ever
since," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
