<HEADLINE> Greece Indirectly Urges U.S. to Make Known Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Greece Wednesday indirectly
urged the United States to make known its position towards the
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that it was unclear whether the U.S. had any
foreknowledge of a proposal by Turkey and northern Cyprus
regarding the establishment of a confederation on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Those who, without making known what they wanted, simply
undertook initiatives for the resolution of the Cyprus problem,
did not respect the countries taking part in this process and
turned their backs on reality and the decisions of the U.N.
Security Council, he said, adding that these things did not
correspond.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that the framework and basis on which
the Cyprus issue must be resolved were the resolutions passed by
the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Greece has flatly rejected the idea of establishing a
confederation on the divided republic, saying that such a move was
unacceptable because it was a clear attempt by the Turkish side to
succeed in having northern Cyprus recognized and to undermine
Cyprus' attempt accession to the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
