<HEADLINE> Russian Ruble Drops to 12.8 to U.S. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The official exchanged rate of
the ruble set by the Central Bank for Thursday dived to 12.8198
rubles to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The new rate, announced Wednesday by the bank's public
relations department, represents a 17.8 percent fall on the
proceeding day's figure and way below the bottom rate of 9.5
rubles to the dollar set by the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Boris Fyodorov, deputy prime minister and head of the State Tax
Service, said the currency corridor policy pursued by the central
bank has failed.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference Wednesday that the currency corridor
"gave the go-ahead to speculations" on the financial market.
</P>
<P>
"Now the Central Bank must announce a floating exchange rate
and allow it to slowly move to the actual level," the Interfax
news agency quoted Fyodorov as saying.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the State Duma, or lower house of
parliament, has asked President Boris Yeltsin to fire Central Bank
Governor Sergei Dubinin.
</P>
<P>
The demand was contained in a resolution passed 267-2 in the
lower house of parliament on the socio-economic and financial
situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Duma described the actions taken by the government and the
Central Bank to overcome the financial crisis as "unsatisfactory
and belated."
</P>
<P>
Dubinin, however, has reportedly told Duma deputies that he
does not intend to resign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
