<HEADLINE> Lebanese Prime Minister to Visit Egypt Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri is due in Cairo next week to discuss with Egyptian leaders
the bilateral ties and the stalled Middle East peace process,
Lebanon's National News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Lebanese Ambassador in Cairo Hasham Damqia
as saying that Hariri will co-chair with his Egyptian counterpart
Kamal El-Ganzouri the third session of the Lebanese-Egyptian Joint
Council next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The session, which will last for two days, will focus on
cooperation agreements on the establishment of free trade zone,
holding of goods exhibitions in both countries and promotion of
trade, Damqia said.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries stood at 74 million U.S.
dollars in 1997, as Egypt has been registering trade surplus in
the past years.
</P>
<P>
Damqia said that during his stay in Cairo, Hariri will also
hold talks with Egyptian leaders on the stalled Middle East peace
process and the Israeli occupation of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up an 1,200-square-kilometer self-declared security
zone in south Lebanon in 1985 to allegedly protect its northern
areas from cross-border attacks by Lebanese Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between Israel and its two neighbors Syria and
Lebanon have been in a standstill since early 1996 due to the
dispute over the future of the Golan Heights which Israel
captured from Syria in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon, backed by its closest ally Syria, has rejected an
Israeli offer to withdraw from south Lebanon under a condition
that the Lebanese government prevents the Muslim guerrillas from
attacking its northern towns after its troop pullout. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
