<HEADLINE> Blair: Omagh Bombers Fail in Derailing Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair said Wednesday the Omagh bombers had failed in their attempt
to derail the peace process in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before a debate in parliament on the new measures
designed to eradicate those still committed to terrorism, Blair
said the bombers had failed "because violence and terror represent
the past in Northern Ireland and democracy and peace represent the
future."
</P>
<P>
Blair also announced the intent to legislate on "long-held
plans to make it a criminal offense of conspiracy to commit
offenses outside the UK."
</P>
<P>
Blair said such legislation was necessary to prevent worldwide
terrorism such as recent attacks in Africa.
</P>
<P>
He pointedly referred to the bombing of the American embassies
in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Conservative party leader William Hague promised
that his party would support the government's anti-terrorist
legislation but voiced concern that powers of internment had been
removed from the statute book.
</P>
<P>
Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown also pledged support but
complained that measures which had "nothing to do with Northern
Ireland" were included in the bill.
</P>
<P>
The emergency session coincided with a debate to introduce
similar laws in the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern promised to "crush and
dismantle" anyone determined to continue with terrorist
activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
