<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Members Losing Millions for Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Member states of the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) are losing
millions of U.S. Dollars in terms of export revenue as the crisis
in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) continues.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from the Lusaka-based COMESA
secretariat, the DRC's total imports from other COMESA members
were estimated to rise to about 150 million U.S. Dollars by the
end of this year but with the on-going war, this would not be
realized.
</P>
<P>
The report shows that the DRC has been growing as a steady
trading partner for the 21-member regional grouping since 1996
when its total exports to that country grew from 85 million U.S.
Dollars in 1995 to about 100 million Dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The former Zaire which joined COMESA last year has also been
Zambia's largest market for non-traditional exports. The report
shows that Zambian companies which were exporting to the DRC are
now stuck with their products due to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
COMESA, with the aim to achieve a free market by the year 2000,
is also losing out in terms of investment that is on hold as the
DRC has a number of investment opportunities in its mines as well
as hydro electric power, the report says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Duma Says Economic Crisis Threatens National Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Russian lower house of
parliament said Wednesday that the economic crisis is threatening
the country's security.
</P>
<P>
In a statement passed unanimously, the State Duma said the
situation "poses a serious threat to the security of the Russian
Federation as a sovereign state and requires a change in the
economic policy."
</P>
<P>
"The August collapse of the financial system resulted from the
accumulation of the state debt, the outflow of capitals from the
country, instability, and lack of confidence in power," the
Itar-Tass news agency quoted the statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
The statement was prepared by a trilateral commission grouping
members of the Duma, and the Federation Council, or upper house of
parliament, and the government.
</P>
<P>
It called for decisive and well-considered measures to prevent
the crisis from deteriorating and consolidation of all branches of
power and political movements to face the "nation-wide task."
</P>
<P>
The statement urged the government and the Central Bank to take
all necessary steps to ensure the safety of the deposits of
individuals with commercial banks, to restore their liquidity, and
to avoid the crashing of the system of settlements.
</P>
<P>
Despite all the pleas and statements, Russia's economic woes
worsened Wednesday, as the Central Bank set Thursday's official
exchange rate at 12.8198 rubles to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The new rate represents a 17.8 percent fall on the proceeding
day's figure and way below the bottom rate of 9.5 rubles to the
dollar set by the Central Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
