<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Welcomes Rwanda's Genocide Judgement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Wednesday welcomed the first-ever judgement on the
crime of genocide by an international court.
</P>
<P>
The International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda Wednesday found
its first defendant Jean Paul Akayeau, a former Hutu mayor of Taba
commune, guilty of nine counts including genocide, crimes against
humanity and violations of the Geneva Convention.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued through his spokesman's office, Annan
said this is a landmark decision in the history of international
criminal law, and it brings to life, for the first time, the
ideals of the Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the
Crime of Genocide adopted 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said the judgement is a testament to the
collective determination to confront the heinous crime of genocide
and a defining example of the ability of the United Nations to
establish an effective international legal order and the rule of
law.
</P>
<P>
Annan expressed the hope that this judgement will contribute to
the long-term process of national reconciliation in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda was created by
the United Nations Security Council in November 1994. During the
year, at least 500,000 people, primarily Tutsis and moderate
Hutus, were brutally massacred. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
