<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-NATO Chief Tried for Alleged Bribery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Ex-NATO Secretary-General
Willy Claes went on trial Wednesday in a multi-million franc
bribery case that was dubbed by Belgians as "the trial of the
century."
</P>
<P>
The trial was held at Belgium's highest court.
</P>
<P>
Claes, Belgian economy minister at the time of the alleged
"gift money" given to his Socialist Party in the late 1980s, is
one of the 12 former Belgian politicians and businessmen accused
of corruption in the Agusta/Dassault case.
</P>
<P>
Claes was forced to resign from the top NATO post in October
1995 when allegations rose that the economy minister, who also
served as foreign minister and was responsible for comparing rival
bids from helicopter manufacturers, received bribery.
</P>
<P>
The trial will investigate cash gifts allegedly given by the
Italian company Agusta and the French company Dassault in the late
1980s after they won multi-million franc contracts to supply
Belgium with 46 A-106 helicopters and to refit the electronic
systems in the country's F-16 fighter planes.
</P>
<P>
The death of Socialist Party politician Andre Cools in 1991 led
to the discovery of irregularities in party funds that in turn led
to a report alleging that the granting of the 1988 contract to
Agusta was tainted with illegal acts and suggesting technical
evaluations of the rival bids were handled by Belgian cabinet
members to make Agusta's bid more favorable.
</P>
<P>
The Agusta probe then led up to allegations over Dassault.
</P>
<P>
All the 12 accused, including ex-Belgian Defense Minister Guy
Coeme and former Socialist Party Chairman Guy Spitaels, have
denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
One key defendant, former Agusta President Raffaelo Teti, died
from a heart attack 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
The trial is expected to last well into December and if found
guilty, the accused could face five years in jail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
