<HEADLINE> NATO Offers Help to Fight Kosovar Winter Harshness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization offered Wednesday to use its resources to help
thousands of Kosovar refugees to fight against coming winter
harshness.
</P>
<P>
NATO ambassadors discussed the Kosovo situation and an
official, who declined to be named, told the press after the
discussion that the ambassadors had agreed to offer NATO transport
and other help to the United Nations refugee agency UNHCR if
called upon.
</P>
<P>
NATO ambassadors expressed great concerns about the predicament
of the Kosovar refugees who number by tens of thousands and are
camped in makeshift shelters in Kosovo's forests and mountains.
</P>
<P>
The Western military alliance, that has been preparing for a
military intervention in the Yugoslav province, continued to call
for a negotiated political solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The same official said that the planning for NATO intervention
in Kosovo would be completed in the next few days to provide the
governments of NATO member states with a full range of options
should they decide to enforce a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
European Union foreign ministers are slated to meet later this
week at Salzburg of Austria in their first formal meeting after
the summer break.
</P>
<P>
NATO, with its air-lift capability, has served international
and European Union aid operations. It ferried humanitarian
supplies to Estonia in 1991 and to Albania earlier this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
