<HEADLINE> U.S. Mediates for Cease-Fire in DRC: Zimbabwean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
been trying to mediate between Zimbabwe and the forces fighting
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted Zimbabwean paper
The Herald as saying Wednesday that U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright had instructed U.S. diplomats in Harare to
press for safe passage for anti-Kabila troops trapped in western
DRC.
</P>
<P>
The region was captured by Angolan, Zimbabwean and Namibian
forces backing Kabila in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Quoting unidentified government sources, the paper said the
U.S. has been asked by Uganda and Rwanda to intervene
diplomatically because their troops were trapped in western DRC.
</P>
<P>
It was almost certain that the information was from Zimbabwe's
senior government officials, and has been published by The Herald
on the instructions of the government, SAPA quoted Western
diplomatic sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said U.S. ambassador Tom MacDonald, acting on
Albright's instructions, had been busy advocating proposals for
"some kind of cease-fire and standstill arrangement for the
allied (Angolan, Namibian and Zimbabwean) forces".
</P>
<P>
It said Zimbabwean Defense Force commander, General Vitalis
Zvinavashe, is now in Luanda to discuss the U.S. proposals with
Angolan military authorities.
</P>
<P>
Namibian President Sam Nujoma said Wednesday that Namibian,
Angolan and Zimbabwean troops would not leave the DRC until the
rebellion had been quelled.
</P>
<P>
He told the Non-Aligned Movement summit that the presence
of the troops was in line with agreements of the Southern
African Development Community. 
</P>
