<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Praises World Population Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia described on
Wednesday the significance of the state of world population
report-1998 to the country as "very great indeed".
</P>
<P>
In a statement made at the launching of the state of the world
population report-1998 here, Negussie Teferra, head of Ethiopia's
national office of population said the report concentrates on the
part to be played by the new generations in the attainment of
sustainable development and on issues particularly related to
reproductive health and rights.
</P>
<P>
The state of world population report-1998, published by the
United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA), was officially launched
worldwide on Wednesday under the theme "The New Generations".
</P>
<P>
According to the report, among the 5.9 billion population in
the world today, there are about 1.05 billion young people
between the age of 15 and 24. The proportion of adolescent
population is reported to be 34 percent for less developed
countries, 19 percent for more developed and 43 percent for least
developed.
</P>
<P>
Negussie pointed out that as Ethiopia is in the very last
category, the significance of the report to Ethiopia is very
great indeed.
</P>
<P>
He said young people have special needs for health care and
education including the very important area of sexual and
reproduc- tive health both to fulfill their individual potential
and to make the maximum possible contribution to development.
</P>
<P>
He outlined focus areas of support for adolescents in
Ethiopia's fourth country program which included, among others,
establishing youth friendly reproductive health and family
planning service delivery centers and providing counseling
services specifically suitable for adolescents.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the elderly people in Ethiopia, Negussie said
although there are a variety of welfare institutions in Ethiopia
catering to the needs of the elderly, the services they render
leaves much to be desired.
</P>
<P>
The government alone can not handle all kinds of welfare
requirements geared to elderly people, he said, and called on
non-governmental organizations and members of the community at
large to pull their efforts together to save the elderly from
facing diverse problems in their old age while at the same time
designing viable programs of a lasting nature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
