<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Russian Parties to Work Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
urged here Wednesday leaders of Russia's political parties and
movements to work together in the face of economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
He told the officials that Washington will render support if
the parties find a way to work together on overcoming the crisis
and the democratic basis is preserved in Russia, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the remarks during a meeting at the U.S.
ambassador's residence with representatives of major Russian
political parties and movements as well as regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the absence of such a system of relations would
plunge Russia into a situation whereby investors would flee under
the rules of global economic operation.
</P>
<P>
Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov described his meeting with
Clinton as useful, noting Clinton's summit Wednesday might be the
final meeting with President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Clinton "seemed to be very surprised when I told him that Mr.
Yeltsin did not work with parliament at all," Zyuganov said.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party is the largest opposition faction in the
State Duma, or lower house of parliament, occupying 133 of the 450
seats.
</P>
<P>
The Duma Monday overwhelmingly rejected Yeltsin's choice of
prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
Grigory Yavlinsky, leader of the Yabloko movement, said
Clinton's visit to Moscow "in the context of the very fierce
economic and political crisis in Russia is a good sign."
</P>
<P>
He told Clinton that support should be given to the democratic
course in general, not to individual personalities," Interfax
reported.
</P>
<P>
Other participants at the meeting included Krasnoyarsk
territory Governor Alexander Lebed, Tatarstan President Mintimer
Shaimiyev, Our Home Is Russia faction leader Alexander Shokhin and
Duma International Affairs Committee Chairman Vladimir Lukin and
Defense Committee Chairman Roman Popkovich.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is scheduled to leave here Thursday for Ireland and the
British province of Northern Ireland. 
</P>
