<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus, Greece Urged to Reconsider Denktash's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkey on Wednesday urged
Cyprus and Greece to reconsider the proposal put forward by
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash for creating a confederation
in the divided Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a weekly press conference here, Turkish Foreign
Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan said that if the proposal was
wasted, the tension in Cyprus might escalate to a level which
would lead to a permanent division of the island.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Denktash proposed that a bi-communal confederation
"equal states " of Turkish and Greek Cypriots be established to
settle the long-running Cyprus crisis.
</P>
<P>
But Cyprus and its closest ally Greece have categorically
rejected Denktash's proposal.
</P>
<P>
"Those who do not bother to consider Denktash's proposal
carefully may regret in the future. I hope that Greece and
Greek Cypriots will sooner or later understand the merits of
Denktash's' proposal," Utkan said.
</P>
<P>
Describing the proposal as not being tactical, he said it was
"a scheme which has the biggest chance of being realized since it
is based on political realities in Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' President Glafkos Clerides, who was in Durban of South
Africa for the Non-Aligned Movement summit, said Monday that
Denktash's proposal contradicts the spirit of the United Nations
resolutions for the settlement of Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Greece, which supports the Greek Cypriot-controlled Cypriot
government, has also dismissed the Turkish Cypriot proposal as
"unacceptable".
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third after an abortive
coup by some Greek Cypriot military officers attempting to seek
union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
To contend with the internationally acknowledged Republic of
Cyprus dominated by Greek Cypriots in the south, Turkish Cypriots
declared in 1983 the breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern
Cyprus" in the north, which was only recognized by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The peace negotiations between the Greek and Turkish
communities broke down last summer when Denktash walked out to
protest against the European Union's decision to start accession
talks with the Cypriot government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
