<HEADLINE> Military MP Opposes Cease-Fire Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A member of parliament from
the Uganda People's Defense Forces (UPDF) has said no cease-fire
with the rebels should be passed by the country's legislature.
</P>
<P>
Major Noble Mayambo made the remarks Wednesday afternoon when
contributing to a cease-fire motion moved by a member of
parliament (MP) for Samia Bugwe North Aggrey Awori, Radio Uganda
reported.
</P>
<P>
Noble said that the UPDF has a historical and constitutional
mission to protect the lives and properties of the people and to
safeguard the territorial integrity of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the parliament never to seek a resolution that
will allow gunmen to unseat a popularly-elected government and
rule the country.
</P>
<P>
The government army is fighting a principled war and should be
supported and applauded for their contribution to the national
security.
</P>
<P>
He urged the MPs to build strong foundations to guarantee
peace and ensure constitutional rule in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire motion was tabled Tuesday seeking to persuade
the Ugandan government and the rebels to declare a cease-fire so
as to initiate peace talks. 
