<HEADLINE> Drug Smuggling Bid Foiled in Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabian anti-drug
authorities have foiled an attempt to smuggle large quantity of
drugs into the kingdom, the Saudi Press Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mujab Bin Mohammad Al-Qahtani, an official of the southern
Najran Administrative District, was quoted as saying that security
patrols seized 651,000 drug tablets near the border with Yemen.
</P>
<P>
Al-Qahtani said the smugglers tried to get rid of the tablets
when they were being chased by the patrols.
</P>
<P>
He did not elaborate on the time when the drugs were
confiscated and their source.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Saudi anti-narcotics authorities, aided by
Pakistani security forces, also aborted a bid to smuggle 200
kilograms of hashish to the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Like other oil-rich Gulf countries, Saudi Arabia has become one
of the major targets of drug traffickers in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf kingdom, which adopts a strict policy against
narcotics, imposes capital punishment against drug traffickers and
dealers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
