<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Central Bank Lets Ruble Free Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 2 (Xinhua) -- As the ruble shed nearly 18
percent in a single day Wednesday, the Russian Central Bank
formally admitted that it has given up maintaining the exchange
corridor of the national currency.
</P>
<P>
In a press release circulated Wednesday, the Central Bank said
it had to give up efforts to maintain an upper limit on the
ruble's official exchange rate, 9.5 rubles to the dollar, Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, the Central bank sold more than 9
billion U.S. dollars from its currency reserves in July and August
to support the ruble, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The period following the August 17 announcement of new limits
for the currency corridor was extremely complicated and the
situation developed according to the worst scenario imaginable,"
the press release said.
</P>
<P>
To restore the normal functioning of the currency market, an
electronic fixing system will start working on the Moscow
Interbank Currency Exchange (MICEX) Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, Central Bank Deputy Chairman Denis Kiselyov
praised the floating exchange rate, created through the electronic
fixing system, as the optimum foreign exchange policy in today's
Russia.
</P>
<P>
He said that back on August 17, the decision to set the
exchange band at 6.0 to 9.5 rubles to the dollar was taken with
the hope that "if events took a normal course, the rate could be
held within the established parameters without any intervention
(by the government)."
</P>
<P>
"What is happening now in economics and politics can in no way
be called a normal course of events, and we are facing a choice:
either to spend our foreign exchange reserves to keep the rate
within the limits of the corridor, or to leave the rate floating
the way it is and save the reserves for emergency measures,"
Kiselyov told the local Ekho Moskvy radio station.
</P>
<P>
However, he said it was impossible under the present
circumstances to foresee how far the ruble will fall and how high
inflation will rise.
</P>
<P>
The official exchange rate for Thursday set by the Central Bank
Wednesday was 12.8198 rubles to the dollar, a 17.8 percent fall on
the proceeding's figure.
</P>
<P>
Kiselyov said the inflation rate "depends on how many rubles
will have to be thrown in the economy and on how many rubles will
need to be issued to support lending organizations and Russia's
Sberbank to enable them to pay off deposits.
</P>
<P>
Sberbank is Russia's largest savings bank.
</P>
<P>
"And that depends on how soon it will be possible to stabilize
the situation in the country as a whole and on fiscal matters --
on how taxes will be connected," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
