Assembly and congratulate the citizens of Northern Ireland for
this hard-won peace that is yours," she said in a speech given to
400 women and some prominent politicians who were once arch foes.
</P>
<P>
She said that she and President Clinton would travel to Omagh
to "pay tribute to those who were murdered by the enemies of
peace."
</P>
<P>
"They were mostly women and children, they were Catholic and
Protestant, unionists and nationalist," said the U.S. first lady.
</P>
<P>
"The terrorists targeted the people of Northern Ireland and in
response it was the people, all the people, who bravely stood side
by side to say `hatred and violence will no longer have a place
here, we have chosen ballots not bombs, democracy not
division... we will only move forward.' And as you do, please know
that America will stand with you," she said.
</P>
<P>
"All of you are now the architects of a new environment. You
are ultimately those who will determine whether the children of
Northern Ireland can play like children should -- without respect
to religion or politics, without stereotyping or name-calling,
without fear of violence," she added. 
</P>
