<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Court Finds Former Rwandan Mayor Guilty of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The International
Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR), in the first-ever judgement
by an international court for the crime of genocide, Wednesday
found Jean-Paul Akayesu, a former Rwandan mayor, guilty of
genocide and crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, Akayesu was found guilty of direct and public
incitement to commit genocide, and crimes against humanity
(extermination, murder, torture, rape, and other inhumane acts),
according to an ICTR statement reaching here.
</P>
<P>
In finding Akayesu guilty on nine counts in his indictment,
the court, based in northern Tanzanian town of Arusha, firmly
established the individual responsibility of the accused for the
crimes.
</P>
<P>
In its judgement, three judges of the Trial Chamber 1
unanimously found Akayesu, former mayor of Taba in central
Rwanda, guilty of nine out of the 15 counts on which he was
charged, and not guilty of six counts in his indictment.
</P>
<P>
The 45-year-old former Rwandan official, however, had pleaded
not guilty to all 15 counts.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR was created by the United Nations Security Council in
November of 1994 after one of the intense periods of mass
exterminations in human history.
</P>
<P>
At least 500,000 people, primarily Tutsis and moderate Hutus,
were brutally massacred in just three months in the middle of
that year.
</P>
<P>
The chamber stated that "there was an intention to wipe out
the Tutsi group in its entirety, since even newborn babies were
not spared."
</P>
<P>
At least 2,000 Tutsis were killed in Taba between April 7 and
the end of June in 1994 while Akayesu held office as mayor.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the accused stopped trying to maintain law
and order and was subsequently present during the killings and
sometimes gave orders himself for bodily or mental harm to be
caused to certain Tutsis, and endorsed and even ordered the
killing of several Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
It said Akayesu also incited genocide by leading and
addressing a public gathering on April 19, 1994, during which he
urged the population to unite to kill the Tutsis in general.
</P>
<P>
The statement further said numerous women seeking refuge at
the Taba communal office from the massacres were systematically
raped and regularly subjected to multiple acts of sexual violence
by the armed local militia.
</P>
<P>
Prior to becoming the mayor of Taba commune, Akayesu was a
school teacher and school inspector. He entered politics and the
Mouvement Democratique Republican (MDR) in 1991 and became
Chairman of the local wing of the MDR in Taba.
</P>
<P>
In April of 1993, he was elected mayor of Taba and held that
position until June of 1994 when he fled Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Akayesu was arrested in Zambia in October of 1995, indicted by
the ICTR in February of 1996, and transferred three months later
from Zambia to Arusha, where he was detained at the tribunal's
detention facility. His trial began in January last year.
</P>
<P>
In a separate case, which is more significant, the ICTR will
pronounce the first ever sentence for genocide.
</P>
<P>
Jean Kambanda, who was Rwandan Prime Minister during the
genocide, has pleaded guilty and will be sentenced on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR is the first international body charged specifically
with prosecuting crimes of genocide. The maximum sentence the
tribunal can impose is life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal has in its custody a total of 26 indicted
Rwandans and five suspects. All the 31 come from what Tribunal
Registrar Agwu Okali calls "the commanding heights" of Rwanda's
governing elite during the time the genocide took place.
</P>
<P>
They were arrested by countries across Africa and Europe and
delivered to the tribunal in Arusha.
</P>
<P>
In addition, another accused, Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, a
Pastor, is being held in Texas in the United States.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. federal judge ordered his deportation to Arusha on
August 5 but he has one month in which to appeal.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal's next major challenge will be to find countries
which will accept for incarceration those found guilty.
</P>
<P>
Norway and Denmark have definitively indicated their
willingness to take some of those convicted, and a number of
African states and others have opened negotiations with tribunal
officials as well.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal prefers that as many of the convicted as possible
be convicted within Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
