<HEADLINE> People in Central Uganda Warned of Bombs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A regional police commander
in Uganda Wednesday urged local people to be more vigilant and
suspicious of any wrong elements.
</P>
<P>
Bakesiima Chrisostom, the central region police commander,
made the call Wednesday morning when addressing a bomb scare
awareness meeting in Mubende district, some 100 kilometers west
of capital Kampala.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by representatives of the business
community, heads of government departments and security
personnel.
</P>
<P>
Chrisostom warned local people against the habit of picking
and storing nice-looking objects that may turn out to be bombs,
adding that thorough checks shall be done on people entering
taxis, hotels, churches, petrol stations, banks and other public
places.
</P>
<P>
People were encouraged to be effective and to report any
suspicious situations to the police.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen were advised to install security lights to guide
security personnel on night duty.
</P>
<P>
Ever since August 25 when a total of 30 people were killed in
three bus explosions, police have used various means of media to
educate people on self-protection in emergencies.
</P>
<P>
Leaflets have also been distributed to enhance people's safety
awareness.
</P>
<P>
Security personnel are dispatched to check passengers' parcels
at bus stations.
</P>
<P>
Though several arrests have been made, there is still no
official report on who is responsible for the terrific blasts.
</P>
</TEXT>
