<HEADLINE> Clinton Pledges to Advance Israeli-Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
pledged on Wednesday to make efforts to advance the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, which have been stalled for 18
months, Israeli Prime Minister's Office said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued here by the office said Clinton made the
promise in a phone conversation with Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu from Moscow, where he was holding a summit with his
Russian counterpart Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he would work together with Netanyahu to advance
the peace process after he returns to Washington.
</P>
<P>
He added that he intended to speed up the peace talks between
Israel and Palestinians, which is stuck on the dispute over
Israel's second troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has since earlier this year urging Israel to hand over
13.1 percent of West Bank in exchange for the fulfillment of the
Palestinian commitments to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
While the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) has already
accepted the U.S. initiative, Israel has so far refused to
publicly endorsed it on security grounds.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu has repeatedly said in recent speeches that he is
ready to carry out the 13.1 percent withdrawal if the Palestinian
side accepts some conditions set by Israel.
</P>
<P>
One of the conditions is believed to be the demand for turning
3 percent of the proposed territories be designated as a nature
reserve, over which Israel would have overall security control and
the Palestinians are not allowed to build.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Moscow also said that Clinton also made a phone
call to PNA President Yasser Arafat, who is attending the
Non-Aligned Movement summit in South Africa, to discuss the latest
developments in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's phone calls were regarded as a way to register his
disappointment with the prolonged deadlock in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
