<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All Regions Register Record Flows of FDI in 1997: UNCTAD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- World foreign direct investment
(FDI) flows continued to expand in 1997 and are expected to grow
further in 1998, said the United Nations Conference on Trade and
Development (UNCTAD) in a report released here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, FDI outflows reached 424 billion U.S. dollars while
FDI inflows amounted to 400 billion dollars, up 27.1 percent and
18.6 percent compared with 333 billion in 1995 and 338 billion in
1996 respectively.
</P>
<P>
"It should be noted that as recorded in 1997, world FDI did not
decline in the wake of the East Asian financial crisis," said the
UNCTAD.
</P>
<P>
It attributed the continued expansion of global FDI mainly to
the growth of large-scale cross-border mergers and acquisitions
(M&AMP;As) among developed countries. Cross-border M&AMP;As involving more
than 1 billion dollars announced in 1997 amounted to 161 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Despite divergent economic performance of individual
countries, FDI reached record levels in all major country
groupings in 1997," said the UNCTAD. "Developing countries as a
group account for more than one third of world FDI flows."
</P>
<P>
Inflows to developing countries rose at a slower rate than to
the developed ones, but were still up by a significant 15 percent
to reach 149 billion dollars while outflows were up 24 percent to
61 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Developed countries invested 359 billion dollars globally in
1997, up by 27 percent over 1996, and attracted 233 billion
dollars, 19 percent higher than 1996.
</P>
<P>
Dramatic increases were registered in central and eastern
Europe, although still at relatively small levels, said the
UNCTAD. FDI inflows to the region increased by 44 percent to 19
billion dollars and outflows more than tripled to 3 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The rapid growth of FDI is clearly contributing to the
increasing internationalization and integration of economies, with
firms producing more and more outside their home country," said
the UNCTAD.
</P>
<P>
"Seven percent of global GDP is now generated by production of
foreign affiliates of transnational corporations," it said. "If
parent firms were included the proportion would be much higher."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania's Economy Declined in The First Seven Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The latest data of National
Statistics Commission confirmed the decline of Romania's economic
activity, especially industrial activity.
</P>
<P>
The data show a new regression of industrial production which
decreased 6.2 percent in July compared to June, and the decrease
in the first seven months of the year reached 18.6 percent,
compared to the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
This situation may be explained by a diminished activity in all
industrial branches, mainly, in the mining, the electric and
thermal power where the production declined by 24.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of the foreign trade is also worrisome, with a
deficit of balance amounting to 1335.7 million U.S. dollars during
the first half of this year as against 1073.5 million scored
during the same period of the previous year. The exports amounted
to 4094.7 million dollars, a 1.3 percent decrease compared to the
same period of the previous year, while the imports totalling
5430.4 million dollars which represents a rise by 4.0 percent as
against the first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Still, there are a few positive items from this data about a
small increase of economic investments by 0.8 percent in real
terms. The level of investments increased especially in the
manufacturing industry, the electric and thermal power industry,
agriculture and the tertiary sector.
</P>
<P>
The investments volume in the joint sector grew more than four
times, and by 6.4 percent those in the private one, detrimental to
those of the public sector which fell by 15.8 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
