<HEADLINE> Sudanese Envoy Asks U.S. Lawmakers to Probe Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese Ambassador to
Washington said on Wednesday that he would ask U.S. Congressional
leaders to make an investigation into the Sudanese pharmaceutical
factory blasted by cruise missiles on Aug. 20 by the Clinton
administration, alleging that it was producing chemical weapons
agents.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference, Mahdi ibrahim Mohamad, who
insisted the factory produced only medicines and other goods, also
said that he would seek from the Congress reparations for victims
of the U.S. bombings.
</P>
<P>
He described as "unbelievable" and "disgraceful" the U.S.
bombing of the factory, which, he insisted produced only medicines
and other goods.
</P>
<P>
To believe the U.S. allegations that the factory produced
chemical weapons agents "is to strain credibility beyond its
limits," he said. He called the U.S. bombing a "Wild West shoot
first and ask questions later" type operation.
</P>
<P>
Some of lawmakers have expressed support for the
administration's action, but Republican Senator Robert Bennett
said he believed that the case for bombing the factory was weaker
than the one for the simultaneous attack on the suspected
"terrorist-related" base in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Mohamad, who has served here for two years, was away from
Washington when the attack on the factory took place. Shortly
thereafter the Sudanese government announced it was withdrawing
its diplomats from Washington, Mohamad said he is now implementing
that decision.
</P>
<P>
"It is our hope that this interruption will be temporary," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
