<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aideed's Visit to Ethiopia Good for Somali Peace: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The recent visit by
Hussein Aideed, leader of the Somali National Movement, to
Ethiopia is a good sign for the Somali peace, a report reaching
here quoted Ali Mahdi, co-chairman of the Somali National
Salvation Council, as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mahdi said that Aideed's trip to Addis Ababa will help bring
about peace in the state of African Horn, said the report.
</P>
<P>
He said that he and Aideed share the same views and are
working hard "to bring together all the Somali people and
establish a national government."
</P>
<P>
"I trust him (Aideed) and he trusts me and I hope we can reach
the ultimate goal which is bringing Somalis together and hold
reconciliation conference," said Mahdi.
</P>
<P>
He said that the demobilization campaign taking place in
Mogadishu is "going well" and disclosed plans to encamp a total
of 9,000 people in 50 days.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the Somali people have accepted the process of
demobilization, Mahdi said, adding that "I think none will refuse
to come to camp."
</P>
<P>
Aideed last week paid his first ever official visit to
Ethiopia since he assumed the chairmanship of the movement in
1995.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, he held "serious talks" with Ethiopian Prime
Minister Meles Zenawi and Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin.
</P>
<P>
Before returning home, Aideed said that he has succeeded in
forging good relations with Ethiopia and its leadership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
