<HEADLINE> Mozambican PM Urges Police to Improve Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Prime Minister
Pascoal Mocumbi Wednesday urged all police in the country to
improve their skills, enhance efficiency and offer better
service.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican prime minister made the demand at a completion
ceremony of the police training course held in the Police
Training Center, 15 kilometers away from capital Maputo. Interior
Minister Almerinho Manheje, Minister of State Administration
Alfredo Gamito, Governor of Maputo Province Soares Nhaca and 580
trainees attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Mocumbi pointed out that no cases of unlawfulness or
negligence of law should be allowed in the police force, saying
that police should be modest, just, fair, prudent and selfless in
performing their duties.
</P>
<P>
Manheje also noted that the police on duty should wear badges
so that the people can easily identify and supervise them.
</P>
<P>
The interior minister added that the measure is designed to
build up an atmosphere of trust among the masses and increase
justice and transparency in police service.
</P>
<P>
The three-month training course was sponsored by the United
Nations Development Program and the Spanish Police, and Germany
provided some equipments for it.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan of the Mozambican government, a total
number of 4,000 policemen will attend the training course at the
center by April, 2000. The entire training plan is expected to
cost 12 million U.S. Dollars. 
</P>
