<HEADLINE> European Shares Rally but Close off Best Levels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- European shares staged a rally
but closed well off their best levels on Wednesday as worries
about Wall Street's ability to sustain yesterday's recovery and
fears about the Russian and Asian economies resurfaced.
</P>
<P>
The Dow's 288-point overnight rally triggered early strength in
London, with the FTSE 100 index up 172.5 at one time. But Wall
Street's inability to hold best levels at this afternoon's
opening, however, prompted caution, and the FTSE 100 closed 66.7
points up at 5235.8.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, share prices jumped 3.73 percent in the wake of a
good performance on Wall Street. The Dax index closed at 4,970.5
points, up from Tuesday's close of 4,791.81.
</P>
<P>
But traders said there was strong technical resistance at
around 5,000-5,010 on the Dax, and until the index managed to move
above that, the markets would remain volatile.
</P>
<P>
"We've reached a difficult stage. I can't say if this morning's
rise in share prices is just temporary or if the market is still
looking for a bottom," one dealer said.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French shares retreated from their early highs as
volume slowed in cautious trading, which saw the Cac-40 index peak
at 3,749.19. The Cac eventually closed up 83.4 points at 3729.7.
</P>
<P>
Bond markets in Europe were restrained and generally a touch
weaker after sharp falls in the previous session. The benchmark 30
year U.S. long bond was slightly lower at 102-11 and yielding 5.34
percent.
</P>
<P>
Prices eased a touch in light profit-taking following the
overnight rally in U.S. stocks, but could easily rally once more,
if global stocks slide again, traders said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
