<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Manufacturing Output Falls at Fastest Rate for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain's factory output is
falling at its fastest rate for at least six and half years,
according to a new survey.
</P>
<P>
Almost 40 per cent of manufacturers reduced their output over
the past month, according to the latest monthly analysis by the
Chartered Institute of Purchasing and Supply. Only a third as many
companies stepped up production.
</P>
<P>
The drop in production is considered in response to a further
weakening in domestic demand and export order books.
</P>
<P>
"Firms are responding by buying in fewer goods, running down
stocks and, worst of all, laying off staff," Peter Thomson, the
chartered institute's director-general, as quoted by the Financial
Times newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Export order books have been falling since May last year, in
the face of sterling's strength and escalation of the Asian
financial crisis. August's decline was the second largest recorded
since then. Domestic order books also weakened, but less than in
the previous month.
</P>
<P>
As production has fallen and pressure to cut costs intensified,
companies have generally reduced purchases and stocks of inputs.
Stocks of unsold goods remained stable as intentional destocking
was offset by unintentional stockbuilding because sales came in
below expectations. Manufacturers continue to shed jobs, but at a
slower rate than recently, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said the survey was unlikely to have much
impact on the interest rate deliberations of the Bank of England's
monetary policy committee, which has long expected a sharp
downturn in the manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
Recent stock market falls have also raised doubts about the
likely strength of domestic spending in coming months, according
to analysts. These concerns have been reflected in interest rate
futures markets, which are now pencilling in a half-point cut in
base rates by the end of the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
