<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Missile Defense Needs Huge Budgets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States faces
staggering costs in developing its missile defense system under
tight budgets in the coming years, a U.S. Air Force general said
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to have a huge, huge bill in the future for
missile defense," and tens of billions of dollars would be needed
to enable the United States to shoot down ballistic missiles in
flight, Lieutenant General Lester Lyles told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Lyles, head of the Ballistic Missile Defense Organization, said
that because of the high costs and technical troubles, the
Pentagon might have to stop testing its Theater High Altitude Air
Defense (THAAD) system.
</P>
<P>
The Lockheed Martin Corp. designed THAAD, which was designed to
destroy medium-range missiles, suffered five successive failures
in tests. But the program has already cost 3.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The United States is seeking a number of missile defense
options but has virtually no effective defense against medium- or
longer-range missiles.
</P>
<P>
Lyles said the U.S. military is operating within tight budgets
though Republicans in Congress are pressing the Pentagon and the
White House to move ahead with development of not only a "theater
missile defense" for troops and bases but also to build a more
costly U.S. national missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
Lyles, whose budget is 3.7 billion dollars this year, pointed
out that the costs of even short-range U.S. missile defenses were
growing rapidly. The cost of PAC-3 U.S. missiles designed to
destroy shorter-range attacking missiles had more than doubled
from original estimates of about 1 million dollars each.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Pentagon expects the results of studies
this month on whether to conduct a new test of the "THAAD" later
in the year.
</P>
<P>
If the test fail again, the military has to build a new THAAD
missile, that could delay the program for up to two years, the
general said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0068 </DOCNO>
