<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert Suggests Internet Technology for Science Museums in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- An Australian expert suggested
today that China use internet technology to develop science and
technology museums.
</P>
<P>
Brenton Honeyman, an expert with the National Science and
Technology Center of Australia, offered the suggestion at the '98
Beijing International Conference on Science and Technology
Center/Museums held today at the China Science and Technology
Museum in Beijing. He pointed out that an increasing number of
science centers around the world have introduced computers to
enable people of all ages to enjoy the fascinating world of
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
"Science centers are discovering that the Internet, the
Worldwide Web in particular, provides an excellent opportunity to
reach wide audiences and promote greater public contact,"
according to Honeyman.
</P>
<P>
He added that significant developments in browser software have
made it possible for web users to experience far greater levels of
"interactivity" than the passive scrolling which has dominated the
web in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Honeyman noted that China's population of 1.2 billion people
provides the nation's science centers and museums with the largest
potential audience in the world. However, he pointed to the fact
that most science museums have failed to give full play to
computers and noted the vast potential and prospects for their use.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Youwen, a senior engineer with the China Science and
Technology Museum, said that low rate of computer usage for
China's 285 science museums. He noted that most facilities simply
use computers to daily affairs.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from general problems such as the lack of funds, a
major factor hindering the introduction of computer applications
in science museums centers on the lack of suitable software,"
said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
He called on related departments to increase funding to
promote the development and use of advanced internet technology
and computer application systems.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference has attracted Chinese experts and a
large group of scholars from a dozen of countries and regions,
including the Untied States, France and the Philippines. The
participants will discuss the development of science centers, as
well as related education, exhibits design and applications of
modern technology.
</P>
<P>
The conference, carrying the theme "Providing Education and
Inculcation for the Public," is a major academic exchange activity
initiated by the World Science Center (WSC). The first
international conference was held in Finland in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
