<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Prepared to Give More Powers to Government: Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September (Xinhua) -- Speaker of the Russian State Duma
Gennady Seleznyov said on Thursday President Boris Yeltsin was
prepared to give more power to the government.
</P>
<P>
"As a gesture of good will and as the first step (toward a
compromise with the Duma) the president himself is ready to amend
the law on the government which would give the cabinet more
power," Seleznyov quoted Valentin Yumashev, chief of the Kremlin
administration, after their earlier meeting.
</P>
<P>
The change would enable the premier to have the right to choose
ministers and would give more space to the cabinet and soften
outside pressure upon it.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Seleznyov and Yumashev is considered part
of the compromise between the State Duma and the Kremlin over
Yeltsin's effort to nominate Viktor Chernomyrdin for
premiership.
</P>
<P>
The Duma vetoed him on Monday and has scheduled to take the
second vote on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Duma is seeking to limit Yeltsin's sweeping constitutional
power including the power of dissolving the parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
