<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 36 Bodies Recovered from Plane Crash off Canadian Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-six bodies have been
recovered from the crash of the Swissair jet off the coast of
Canada's Nova Scotia province, police said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
So far, the massive search-and-rescue effort has found no
survivors, Canadian police told a news briefing at Peggy's Cove,
Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Swissair confirmed that there were no survivors from
the crash. All 215 passengers and 14 crew aboard Flight 111 is
believed to have died.
</P>
<P>
The wide-bodied MD-11 jet crashed about 10:30 p.m. local time
(0130 GMT) Wednesday into the ocean 11 kilometers from Peggy's
Cove, a tiny fishing village on the south shore of Nova Scotia
province.
</P>
<P>
The three-engine plane, en route from New York to Geneva,
reported smoke in the cockpit after a normal takeoff from the JFK
international airport in New York.
</P>
<P>
The crew decided to turn back to Boston. After being told that
the Halifax airport was closer, the plane flew in the direction of
Halifax, but crashed into the Atlantic about 60 kilometers short
of its target.
</P>
<P>
Most of the passengers on board were thought to be Swiss, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Military aircraft, coast guard vessels and fishing boats
scoured the waters through the night.
</P>
<P>
Yet the inky and rough water made it difficult for rescuing
people to navigate through the debris field, which spread a couple
of kilometers across the sea.
</P>
<P>
As dawn broke on the southwest coast of Nova Scotia, a
shoreline search got under way.
</P>
<P>
"At this point, our main focus is on recovering the bodies,"
said Roy Bears of Canada's Transportation Safety Board, one of the
leading agencies in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
Divers will be used to try to recover flight recorders from the
plane, the reports said. Waters in the area are about 50 meters
deep.
</P>
<P>
Canadian police appealed to the public Thursday to turn in any
debris from the crash, which might wash up the shore.
</P>
<P>
The weather there was reported to be overcast, with a light
sprinkle of rain.
</P>
<P>
Boeing, the maker of the jet, was sending a team of people to
Nova Scotia to help in the investigation of the crash.
</P>
<P>
The United States also sent a team of investigators to the
crash site, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Limited Russian Impact on Enlargement: EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Russia's financial crisis
would have a limited impact on the process of the European Union's
enlargement, a senior European Commission official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hans van den Broek, European commissioner responsible for
external relations with Russia and central and eastern Europe,
told the press, "We would like to make it perfectly clear that on
the basis of our analysis this impact should be a limited one."
</P>
<P>
The economic fundamentals in the central and eastern European
countries applying for European Union membership were sound and
there was no reason for a loss of confidence among investors, he
added at a joint press conference held together with Commission
President Jacques Santer.
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek said that the central and eastern European
countries in accession talks had reoriented their trade away from
Russia toward member states of the European Union after the
disintegration of the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
The EU started accession talks with Hungary, Poland, the Czech
Republic, Slovenia, Estonia and Cyprus in late March this year.
Slovakia, Latvia, Lithuania, Bulgaria and Romania also aspire to
join the union.
</P>
<P>
The current financial crisis in Russia underlined the need for
the central and eastern European countries to forge ahead with
adopting the legislation and building up the institutions
necessary to allow them to cross the EU threshold, said van den
Broek.
</P>
<P>
The fact that they had moved along the road while Russia had
not could help explain why the central and eastern European
countries were not facing the kind of financial crisis Russia was
now suffering, he said.
</P>
<P>
"They are much less vulnerable because in the field of
legislation and institution-building they have made much more
progress than Russia," van den Broek said.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
European Union, made its first assessment of the Russian crisis
Thursday after the summer recess.
</P>
<P>
Commissioners agreed that the impact of the Russian financial
crisis would be limited on the economy of the union.
</P>
<P>
The EU's exports to Russia account for only 3.5 percent of the
union's total annual trade while its imports make up for 4 percent
of the total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
