<HEADLINE> EU Shows Concern Over DPRK Missile Testing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Union expressed
Thursday "grave concern" over the missile testing conducted by the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea on August 31.
</P>
<P>
The concern was expressed through a written statement by
Austria that is serving the rotating presidency of the 15-nation
union.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the union expressed its grave concern
at the test which undermines the efforts to enhance peace and
security on the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
It called upon the DPRK to refrain from any further testing and
to exercise utmost restraint in its missile development and export
activities.
</P>
<P>
The union, a significant contributor to humanitarian assistance
in the Asian country, said that the missile testing created
further tensions in a region that is already facing a precarious
security environment.
</P>
<P>
"We are deeply concerned that a country which for several years
has required and received from the international community
extensive humanitarian assistance chooses to put its own scarce
resources into developing an offensive weapons system," the
statement added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
