<HEADLINE> Myanmar: NLD Parliament Decision Threat to Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yangon, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government said
Thursday that the declaration of the National League for Democracy
(NLD) to convene a national parliament on their own will be a
threat to Myanmar's national security.
</P>
<P>
An official information sheet, available here Thursday evening,
said, "The government of Myanmar noted with concern the decision
by the NLD to convene a national parliament. Such an action by any
individual political party would be in contravention of Myanmar
law, and seems designed to derail the ongoing discussions between
the government and the NLD," it said.
</P>
<P>
"It would amount to the NLD making herself a parallel
government which no government in the world could accept if they
come across the same situation," it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The government warned that "In this scenario the government of
Myanmar will be left with no choice but to take necessary legal
action in safeguarding its national security."
</P>
<P>
The information sheet said the government believed that
"national unity, peace and stability are the most essential
elements the nation requires in order to develop economically and
politically."
</P>
<P>
On June 23, NLD leaders set a deadline for the ruling State
Peace and Development Council (SPDC) to meet their demand that the
parliament elected in the May 1990 multi-party general election be
convened for the first time within 60 days, but the government
made no response to the demand.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued by the NLD on August 21, the
NLD will convene a national parliament soon.
</P>
<P>
At the multi-party general election in May 1990, participated
by 93 political parties, the NLD won 396 out of 485 parliamentary
seats.
</P>
<P>
After the election and in January 1993, the Myanmar government
began to hold a national convention to lay down fundamental
principles for drawing up a new state constitution. However, all
the delegates of the representatives-elect of the NLD withdrew in
November 1995 from the convention, which has been in recess for
two and a half years since the last session ended in March 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
