<HEADLINE> Mongolia's Non-government Groups Meet On Poverty Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia's non-governmental
organizations and scientific institutes held a seminar Thursday to
facilitate the implementation of the country's aid-the-poor
program.
</P>
<P>
The seminar sought measures and ways to distribute relief loans
and worked out amendments to the program by drawing experience
from the past practice.
</P>
<P>
The Mongolian government began the national aid-the-poor
program in 1994. Since then, it has extended 2.2 billion tugrik
(2.59 million U.S. dollars) to help the poor families start
business or provide education to their children.
</P>
<P>
To aid the urban poor, the government initiated from the
beginning of this year a 7-year "green revolution" to encourage
city dwellers to plant potatoes and vegetables to increase market
supply and their income.
</P>
<P>
In the pastoral areas, it purchased animals for the poor
herdsmen on the condition that they would return the same number
of animals in five years and retain those produced in the period.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that more than 500,000 Mongolians, one quarter
of the whole population, are now living under the poverty line.
</P>
</TEXT>
