<HEADLINE> NAM Safeguards Developing Countries, Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DURBAN (South Africa), September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Non-Aligned
Movement (NAM) has become a force of vigor and vitality in the
past decades in safeguarding the rights and interests of the
developing countries, a senior Chinese official said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 12th NAM summit here, Tang Jiaxuan, head of the
Chinese delegation to the NAM summit and Foreign Minister, said
that the NAM which emerged on the international arena 37 years
ago, has developed steadily and grown in strength with its member
states expanding from 25 in 1961 to 113 at present.
</P>
<P>
He said that " the NAM has all along dedicated itself to
safeguarding the rights and interests of developing countries,
actively pushed for fair and reasonable solutions to
international issues and made fruitful efforts to promote peace
and development of mankind and raise the standing of developing
countries".
</P>
<P>
Tang expressed his confidence that the 12th NAM conference,
which is held at the turn of the century, will further enhance
the cohesion of the movement, strengthen the solidarity and
cooperation among developing countries and expand the common
understanding on the cross-century strategy so as to get the
movement ready to usher in the new century with a new outlook.
</P>
<P>
As a developing country and observer state of NAM, Tang said,
China has all along dedicated to safeguarding the legitimate
right and interests of developing countries, enhancing the
solidarity and cooperation with them to the benefit of common
development.
</P>
<P>
China will remain committed to a stronger long-term friendship
and cooperation with the non-aligned countries oriented toward the
21st century, said the Chinese minister.
</P>
<P>
Seven observer countries including China have attended the
12th NAM summit which is scheduled to conclude later Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
