<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Revive Dilapidated Power Stations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Government of
Nigeria is aimed at bringing all dilapidated power plants back to
their full utilization soon to improve power supply in the
country, a minister said.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Minister of power and Steel Alhaji Bello Suleiman
said that his government attached much priority to the power
plants' rehabilitation, adding that "we have a big plan to ensure
all the power plants are brought back to life", local press
reported Thursday,
</P>
<P>
Industry sources here estimated that the repair work to
improve public power supply may cost more than 650 million U.S.
Dollars as 49 out of 78 installed generating units in all the
power stations are believed to have broken down in the West
African country.
</P>
<P>
Public power supply is frequently interrupted in Lagos and
other cities because of the breakdown of power plants which is
due to lack of regular maintenance and mandatory overhaul.
</P>
<P>
Suleiman admitted that none of the power plants in the country
had undergone the mandatory turn-around maintenance since they
were commissioned.
</P>
<P>
The newly-appointed minister toured several power stations
this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
