<HEADLINE> Multi-Party Meeting Over DRC Crisis Expected Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DURBAN (South Africa), September 3 (Xinhua) -- A multi-party
meeting over the month-long crisis in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC) would be held within the week, Zimbabwean President
Robert Mugabe said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference, Mugabe, who is attending the
12th Non-Aligned Movement summit here, said the DRC government
headed by President Laurent Kabila and rebel forces in the
country had agreed to hold the meeting after Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In aition to representatives of the two warring sides, the
meeting would involve representatives from Uganda, Rwanda, member
states of the Southern African Development Community, the
Organization of African Unity and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the military involvement by Zimbabwe, Angola and
Namibia in the DRC, Mugabe defended his government's decision to
send troops to help the Kabila government quell rebels, saying if
they had not intervene, Kabila's legitimate government would have
fallen.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that military intervention was an action of
short time, saying there should be peaceful settlement of all
conflicts in the long run.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said Kabila had agreed to his proposal to hold general
elections in June next year so as to pave way for democracy and
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Kabila government was making a plan for the elections,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean president also denied reports that he had tense
relations with his South African counterpart Nelson Mandela, saying
that his personal ties with Mandela was "normal and good". 
</P>
</TEXT>
