<HEADLINE> Most Ancient Copper Works in Cyprus Excavated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The most ancient primary
copper smelting works ever found in Cyprus were brought to light
after nearly 10 years of excavations, an Italian archaeologist
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The excavations were carried out by an Italian archaeological
team, said Rosaria Belgiorno, an archaeologist of the Italian
Institute for Research.
</P>
<P>
She told reporters that the findings unearthed near Pyrgos
village, 20 kilometers east of the southern coastal town of
Limassol, are similar to those found in Sardenia (Italy) and
Spain, where copper was processed.
</P>
<P>
"Evidence of metallurgical activity has been found in an
Early-Middle Bronze Age settlement and this has given us the
clearest picture yet of the method used at the time of how people
processed copper," she said.
</P>
<P>
"The objects we have discovered, made of copper, ceramic and
stone, are an indication of the high living standards the local
community reached in the beginning of the Early Bronze Age in the
valley of the river near Pyrgos," she added.
</P>
<P>
She said that careful study of the findings will provide
information about the social structure in the beginning of the
Bronze Age and enable her team to get to know of the copper trade
at the time.
</P>
<P>
A two-day seminar on the Italian archaeology, archeometallurgy,
conservation and restoration will be held here Thursday, and the
findings of the Italian team will be on display at the
archaeological museum of Nicosia in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
