<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Conglomerates Unveil Merger Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 3 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's five largest
family-owned conglomerates Thursday unveiled a landmark agreement
to merge seven redundant and over-invested industries.
</P>
<P>
After three months of negotiations on merging their
subsidiaries, the five conglomerates -- Hyundai, Samsung, Daewoo,
LG and SK -- Thursday told a joint news conference that they will
set up joint firms or consortiums in seven sectors as part of
reform to boost competitiveness of their products.
</P>
<P>
The seven industries included petrochemicals, rolling-stock,
aerospace, power generator, ship engines and oil refining. Merger
in the auto industry will be made in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The deal of subsidiaries' merger came with an agreement on the
marriage of Hyundai Electronics Ind with LG Semicon to create a
single entity.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in the petrochemical sector, Samsung General
Chemical Co. and Hyundai Petrochemical Co., both located in Daesan
Industrial Complex in South Chungchong Province, will be merged
into a joint consortium to attract foreign capitals to further
reinforce their competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The proposed merger between petrochemical sectors of LG and SK
groups, located in Ulsan and Yeochon of South Cholla Province,
will be discussed soon.
</P>
<P>
In the aircraft industry, Samsung Aerospace Industries,
aerospace division of Daewoo Heavy Industries and Hyundai Space &AMP;
Aircraft Co., will form a single independent consortium before
inviting foreign investors to make equity participation.
</P>
<P>
The three rolling-stock makers -- Hyundai Precision &AMP; Ind. Co.,
Daewoo Heavy Industries and Hanjin Heavy Industries -- will become
a joint management company.
</P>
<P>
In the power-generation equipment industry, the relevant
divisions of Hyundai Heavy Industries and state-run Korea Heavy
Industries and Construction Co will be combined.
</P>
<P>
In the oil refining field, Hyundai Oil Co. will take over the
oil-refining business of Hanwha Energy Co.
</P>
<P>
In the auto industry, Hyundai, Daewoo and Samsung decided to
discuss their restructuring program after the fate of Kia Motors
Corp. is determined by an international bidding.
</P>
<P>
Calling for more support to help facilitate the seven-industry
restructuring schemes, the five conglomerates urged the government
and creditor banks to implement debt-to-equity swaps, drastic debt
write-offs, debt restructuring and tax reductions for the
concerned firms.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said the demanded financial supports,
estimated at 20 trillion won (about 16 billion U.S. dollars), are
too excessive. They believed that the five groups may renege on
their declared restructuring pledges if the government aids fall
short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that excessive debt-equity swaps and debt
write-offs could be seen by the United States and other World
Trade Organization countries as a kind of subsidy, touching off
severe trade conflicts.
</P>
<P>
South Korean conglomerates are blamed for devouring bank loans
and shirking responsibility for triggering the current financial
crisis with their high debts build-up and over expansion.
</P>
<P>
The subsidiaries of the nation's top 30 groups were laden with
a total debt of 28 billion U.S. dollars, which was 4.5 times more
than their capital at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Seoul signed an agreement late last year with the International
Monetary Fund for a bail-out loan of 58 billion U.S. dollars after
it was gripped by the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the country, once the 11th largest
economy in the world, has to restructure its economy and open its
markets this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
