<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Government Sets Out Proposals to Open Up TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) has put forward 35
proposals covering eight broad areas to liberalize television
broadcasting and program services.
</P>
<P>
These proposals were listed in a document "The 1998 Review of
Television Policy" released here Thursday afternoon for
one-month-long public consultation.
</P>
<P>
The eight areas range from network sharing, in-building
distribution systems, pay TV market, regulatory issues to
royalties and license fees, digital terrestrial television,
legislation and regulatory bodies.
</P>
<P>
Some of the major proposals include:
</P>
<P>
-- Allow Fixed Telecommunication Network Services (FTNS)
licensees to convey and provide television program services,
involving pay television and Video on Demand (VOD);
</P>
<P>
-- Lift the moratorium on pay TV and VOD program service
licenses and allow satellite broadcasters to offer pay television
services in Hong Kong;
</P>
<P>
-- Require Wharf Cable, the only cable television licensee in
Hong Kong, to open up its broadband network for use by other
television and telecommunications service providers;
</P>
<P>
-- Allow cable television networks to deliver
telecommunications services in addition to television services;
and
</P>
<P>
-- Prepare for the licensing of direct-to-home service using
the four Ku-band channels allocated to Hong Kong by the
International Telecommunication Union in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to K.C. Kwong, secretary for information technology
and broadcasting, these government proposals are designed to
"enable service providers to have fair and better access to all
the network facilities available in the market."
</P>
<P>
The government also proposed a series of measures to relieve
broadcasters of financial burdens and facilitate the introduction
of innovative services using new technologies.
</P>
<P>
These include relaxing the restrictions on ownership and
investment by licensees to enable diversification and
cross-fertilization of the telecommunications and broadcasting
markets, abolishing the charging of subscription royalties and
advertising royalties, and facilitating the development of digital
terrestrial television in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Kwong said, "Subject to policy decisions to be made by the end
of this year, we will immediately start work on the drafting of a
Broadcasting Bill with a view to introducing it into the
Legislative Council in 1999." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
