<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Launches Back Lanes Clean-Up Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's hygiene campaign
spread into its notorious back lanes Thursday as the Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government launched a clean-up
operation targeted at some 133 black spots throughout the "New
Territories."
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Regional Services Department (RSD), the
operation was kicked off simultaneously Thursday in the nine
districts in the "New Territories" and outlying islands.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the clean-up operations will improve the standard
of cleanliness of the back lanes and thus provide a better living
environment for people in these areas," Lo Yue-yee, acting
assistant director of regional services (environmental health
services), said when inspecting a clean-up site in Tsuen Wan
Market Street.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 people had been mobilized, including RSD
officers, staff and cleaners, who joined hands with staff from the
local hygiene contractors in the operation.
</P>
<P>
Many local shop and restaurant owners and residents have turned
back lanes into storehouses and dump sites. One-third of the 353
back lanes in Hong Kong had been blacklisted due to their poor
hygienic conditions.
</P>
<P>
Depositing waste at back lanes is an offense in Hong Kong and
the maximum penalty is a fine of 25,000 HK dollars (3,200 U.S.
dollars) and an imprisonment of six months. Charges were laid down
against 41,000 hygienic regulation offenders last year, which
represented an increase of 6 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The month-long back lanes clean-up operation is part of the SAR
government's three-year-long Healthy Living Into the 21st Century
Campaign, which started in July this year.
</P>
<P>
Lo said daily cleaning of public areas including back lanes
will be reinforced by weekly major clean-ups. Owners of private
back lanes will be asked to keep these areas clean, she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
