<HEADLINE> HK Open University to Start Web-Based Instruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Open University of Hong
Kong (OUHK) will implement full-scale web-based instruction in two
years' time, the university's newly-appointed director of
technology development, Leung Chun-ming, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said topping his agenda is to explore ways to enhance
distant education using advanced technology.
</P>
<P>
In web-based instruction, teaching activities will be conducted
on the worldwide web which integrates text, sound and images.
Students will be able to plan their studies at their own pace and
time.
</P>
<P>
To implement the plan, the OUHK will first convert materials of
more than 100 existing courses into on-line version. By applying
interactive multimedia technology, tutors and students will then
be able to interact on the web.
</P>
<P>
Web-based instruction is becoming popular in the United States
but has not yet been widely adopted in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
According to Leung, the OUHK also plans to adopt speech
recognition technology to upgrade language teaching at primary,
secondary and university levels.
</P>
<P>
The OUHK projects will be carried out with the support of the
10-million-HK-dollar (1.3 million U.S.) multimedia laboratory
sponsored by the Hong Kong Jockey Club Charities Trust. 
</P>
</TEXT>
