<HEADLINE> HKSAR Government's Proposals on Application of DTT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) has proposed the
establishment of a joint government-industry steering committee to
coordinate technical trials on the digital terrestrial television
(DTT).
</P>
<P>
This is one of the proposals set out in a government document
entitled "The 1998 Review of Television Policy" which was released
here Thursday afternoon for one-month-long public consultation.
</P>
<P>
The document said the government has a role to facilitate the
development of DTT in Hong Kong and to promote the diversity of
services ensuing from the application of this technology.
</P>
<P>
The successful introduction of DTT will depend very much on
when the prices of DTT products will come down to a level
attractive to consumers, it said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe therefore that a step-by-step approach is prudent.
We propose to invite interested parties to participate in the
trial but careful assessment of market and technical conditions
along the way is necessary before taking any major policy
decisions on implementation," the document added.
</P>
<P>
The government's proposals on the application of DTT also
include the commencing of the trials of DTT and high definition
television (HDTV) as soon as practicable with a view to
determining a DTT standard to be adopted in 2000.
</P>
<P>
DTT is developing fast around the world. The United States and
Britain are introducing digital television service this year while
Japan will launch the service in 1999 and Australia on January 1,
2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
