<HEADLINE> Ringgit Transactions to Be Closed Out in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore Foreign
Exchange Market Committee (SFEMC) has asked banks to settle
outstanding Malaysian ringgit transactions no later than September
9, 1998, according to its notes Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The point was made clear in the guidelines adopted by the SFEMC
at a meeting Wednesday following Malaysia's announcement on
Tuesday that all overseas trading of its currency and stocks is
banned.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines, generally agreed upon by market participants as
recommended practice for closing out ringgit transactions, also
require banks to close out ringgit-related transactions with
counterparties by netting all outstanding trades and settling the
difference in U.S dollars.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines also proposed that the representative rate
prevailing at 10:30 a.m. on September 1, 1998, be adopted as the
guideline for bilateral settlement since the freely traded market
for the ringgit came to a halt approximately at that time.
</P>
<P>
A spot U.S. dollar rate against the ringgit, a benchmark yield
curve, an option volatility structure and other technical matters
were also listed in an appendix to the guidelines.
</P>
<P>
The notes urged all affected parties to exert their best
efforts to reach an appropriate close-out arrangement and
preferably make the net payment on September 8.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
