<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Government Aims to Open Up Telecom Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) proposed here Thursday to
further liberalize the telecommunications market in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was set out in the 1998 Review of Fixed
Telecommunications, which was made public Thursday for one-month
public consultation.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press briefing Thursday afternoon, M. H. Au,
acting director-general of telecommunications of the SAR, said
competition in the local fixed telecommunications network service
(FTNS) market should be enhanced.
</P>
<P>
Two measures are being considered, Au said. One is to issue
more FTNS licenses to allow more new operators to enter the market
and the other is to ask existing new FTNS operators to continue
expansion of their networks.
</P>
<P>
Competition will be allowed in the external telecom services
market from January 1, 1999, and in the external telecom
facilities market from January 1, 2000, Au said.
</P>
<P>
The government proposed to start issuing licenses for external
telecom services before the end of 1998 and to let the market
determine the number of licenses.
</P>
<P>
For competition in external telecom facilities, which include
satellite telecommunications facilities, submarine or overland
cables and new technologies, the government plans to let the
market determine the number of licenses and technologies to be
deployed.
</P>
<P>
The government also considers taking effective measures to
ensure fair competition.
</P>
<P>
Au said that liberalizing the telecom market will consolidate
Hong Kong's position as the telecom hub in the Asia-Pacific region
and that high-quality, low-price services will enhance the
competitiveness of other sectors.
</P>
<P>
The further opening up of the market will reduce the cost of
telecom for business organizations and individual consumers and
facilitate the rollout of information infrastructure in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It will also attract investment and create job opportunities,
allow use of state-of-the-art technology and promote the image of
Hong Kong internationally, Au said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
