<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Rules Out Possibility of Holding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu on Thursday ruled out the possibility of
advancing the general elections which are scheduled in the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a meeting of the ruling Likud Party, Netanyahu
said he suported the view that the moves made by President Ezer
Weizman to hold early elections are against the law.
</P>
<P>
The hawkish National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon
strongly criticized Weizman for attempting to bring down a
democratically elected government, saying he was breaching
Israel's constitutional law.
</P>
<P>
The Likud meeting came after Weizman's meeting with the
opposition Labor Party leader Ehud Barak last week, during which
he publicly called for early elections.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in response to Weizman's remarks, the
Likud said the president was bringing disgrace to the presidency,
which is only a ceremonial post without executive power.
</P>
<P>
It said Weizman was proving to the public that he is more
worthy of the title of head of the left-wing opposition.
</P>
<P>
Although Weizman announced Wednesday that he planned to stop
discussing early elections, he defended his actions. "I'm doing
what I think I should do as a president when the state is in
crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
The outspoken president said the Netanyahu-led government has
ruined the peace process with the Palestinians, which have been
stalled for 18 months over the next Israeli troop redeployment in
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that unless the government is changed soon,
the situation could deteriorate into bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
Weizman and Netanyahu have long been at odds with each other
due to their differences over the handling of the peace process,
which has been stalled in all the tracks since the Likud
government came to power in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
