<HEADLINE> S. Korean Parliament Debates DPRK Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Lawmakers of the South Korean
National Assembly, or parliament, Thursday conducted hot debates
over the government's policy toward the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers from rival political parties showed their
difference on the government's decision to retain its "sunshine
policy" toward the DPRK despite its test-firing of a long-range
ballistic missile on Monday, which overflew Japan and fell into
the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers of the opposition Grand National Party appealed to
the government to develop long-range missiles to counter any
military threat from the DPRK, and criticized the government for
overlooking the DPRK's missile threat in the past in the belief
that it was directed at Japan and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The government, they said, should scrap its agreement with the
United States not to develop missiles with a range of more than
180 kilometers and join the Missile Technology Control Regime,
which permits the development of missiles with ranges of up to 300
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
However, they showed unanimity in strengthening cooperation
with the United States and Japan in defense against the DPRK's
missile threat.
</P>
<P>
Legislators from the ruling coalition of the National Congress
for New Politics and the United Liberal Democrats attributed
Pyongyang's missile test to the government's passive response to
its development of weapons of mass destruction in the past. They
urged the government to map out a plan to thwart that development.
</P>
<P>
The debates started after top government officials briefed the
lawmakers on the implications of the DPRK missile test at two
parliamentary panels -- the National Defense Committee and the
Foreign Affairs, Trade and Unification Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
