<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Expects U.S. Envoy Back to Middle East, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Israel is waiting for a
final decision by Washington on whether to send U.S. Middle East
envoy Dennis Ross back to the region to help the Israelis and the
Palestinians clinch a deal, Israel Radio reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials said that Ross may visit the region within a
few days -- possibly this weekend -- though his arrival could be
delayed if there are no specific commitments by the Palestinians
to advance the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
If the Ross mission takes place and succeeds, it could be
followed up by three-way talks in the U.S. between President Bill
Clinton, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat to finalize
several minor issues.
</P>
<P>
This could be a prelude to the signing of an agreement this
month on a 13 percent West Bank redeployment by Israel, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and Arafat are planning to visit New York around
September 23 to attend the session of the General Assembly of the
United Nations, reports said.
</P>
<P>
A possible Ross visit was discussed in a phone conversation
Wednesday night between Clinton and Netanyahu, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio cited officials in the Prime Minister's Office as
saying that the U.S. president, who phoned from Moscow after his
summit meeting with his Russian counterpart Boris Yeltsin,
promised that he would work together with Netanyahu to advance the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that Clinton also phoned Arafat, who was
attending a summit of the non-aligned countries in Durban, South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
A senior aide to the president said during both the
conversations with Netanyahu and Arafat, Clinton expressed his
disappointment that no agreement has been concluded over the
second Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the aide was quoted as saying that "we're closer
than we have ever been before," referring to Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations on the conditions for the Israeli redeployment.
</P>
<P>
There have been quiet meetings this week between Israel's
chief negotiator Yitzhak Molcho and Palestinian Legislative
Council Speaker Ahmed Queria (Abu Ala) in a bid to resolve the
differences blocking a West Bank pullback deal.
</P>
<P>
Previous reports said the two negotiators have drawn up a
draft agreement over the Israeli proposals that Israel pull back
its troops from 13 percent of the West Bank but 3 percent of the
land will be turned into a "nature reserve" where Israel will
maintain overriding security responsibility and the Palestinians
are not allowed to settle. 
</P>
