<HEADLINE> Air Canada Pilots Willing to Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Talks could soon resume between
Air Canada and its 2,100 striking pilots, the Financial Post
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Both sides indicated willingness Wednesday to restart
negotiations, which broke down late Tuesday after the pilots
refused Air Canada's wage offer.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Marc Belanger, head of the Air Canada Pilots Association
said the union was willing to return to the table soon.
</P>
<P>
Air Canada said it is anxious to negotiate, although it added
the onus is on the pilots.
</P>
<P>
But by late Wednesday, no dates were set for resuming the talks
and negotiators from both sides were exhausted after six days of
intense bargaining, including an 18-hour session Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The pilots, who say they are paid up to 30 percent less than
their U.S. counterparts, had lowered their wage increase demand to
12 percent over two years from an initial request of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Air Canada offered nine percent over two years. It had agreed
to stock options, pension and working condition improvement.
</P>
<P>
The strike has being causing inconvenience at airports across
the country since the carrier moves up to 60,000 people a
day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
