<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Crisis Has Limited Effect on EU: Santer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission
president said on Thursday that the current Russian financial
crisis has a limited direct effect on the economy of the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
Jacques Santer made the statement after his commission met for
the first time after the summer break to review the economic and
political development in Russia.
</P>
<P>
The commission president attributed the limited effect to the
limited trade between the 15-nation union and Russia.
</P>
<P>
EU exports to Russia account for 3.5 percent of the union's
total annual trade while its imports make up for 4 percent of the
total.
</P>
<P>
The potential effects through the banking sector are likely to
be manageable even though European banks are more exposed to
Russia than American banks, Santer said.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the European Union, made
its first assessment of the potential impact on the European
economy by Russia's deteriorating crisis on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The commissioners agreed that the crisis is most likely to have
severe negative consequences for the Russian economy and the
Russian people and that the main responsibility for ending the
crisis lies with the Russians themselves.
</P>
<P>
They warned that Russia risks reversing the progress it has
made over recent years toward establishing a market economy unless
the economic stabilization and reform program agreed with the
international financial institutions are fully and decisively
implemented.
</P>
<P>
Hans van den Broek, European commissioner responsible for
external relations with Russia and central and eastern Europe,
said that if a country like Russia ran into such a financial
crisis, there must be something politically wrong.
</P>
<P>
The commission appealed that it is vital for Russia to
establish a new government quickly and to put in place a credible
economic program to cooperate and render outside assistance
effective.
</P>
<P>
Santer told the press that the commission's efforts under
present circumstances will concentrate on using the maximum
flexibility within the commission's TACIS program to mobilize
expertise and should focus technical assistance in priority areas
such as public finances, finance sector restructuring and
institutional reform.
</P>
<P>
Between 1991 and 1997, the European Union has granted Russia
aid worth 1.6 billion ECU (1.76 billion U.S. dollars) through the
TACIS program that is designed to offer technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
The total yearly available funds under the TACIS program is 500
million ECU (550 million dollars) and a third of this fund usually
goes to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Russia has received 400 million ECU (440 million dollars) in
1998 already, according to commission sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The chairman of the Egyptian investment authority
Ibrahim Fawzi has announced the establishment of a river shipyard
in the governorate of Qena in the form of a full-fledged Egyptian
joint stock company for ship building and construction of metal
structures.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by Thursday's Arab daily "Al Hayat" as saying
that by establishing this company, Egypt would embark on ship
building for the first time in upper Egyptian governorates, within
the framework of a government plan to promote those areas and to
afford further job opportunities and overcome unemployment in
upper Egypt.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the investment cost of the company would
amount to 80 million Egyptian pounds (23.3 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- A Tunisian Ministry of Industry source has disclosed
that 60 new oil wells will be dug to make up for the registered
decline in the volume of domestic production due to the scarcity
of the reserves in the principal oil fields.
</P>
<P>
Quoting the source, "Al Hayat" reported Thursday that digging
the new wells will take five years, at the rate of 12 wells a year
and that Tunisian authorities plan to permit private sector
companies to take part in digging.
</P>
<P>
The Tunisian Minister of Industry Munsif Bin Abdulla expects an
annual average investment of 200 million dollars in petroleum and
natural gas exploration.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- A total of 1.2 million tonnes of wheat is lost in
Iran due to the lack of combines, Iranian Agriculture Minister
Issa Kalantari said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kalantari said in Hamadan, western province of Hamadan, that
the loss was estimated at 300 million U.S. dollars, the official
news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that the country needs 3,000 combines to meet the
demand, adding that the value of the lost wheat is that of 6,000
combines.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the country's harvest this year, the minister
said that Iran would enjoy a good one this year thanks to the mild
weather with more rain.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that the government has so far bought 6.56
million tonnes of wheat from farmers, showing an increase of about
54.8 percent from the figure of 4.236 million tonnes last year.
</P>
<P>
Iran's wheat consumption is reportedly 10 million tonnes
annually and 5 million tonnes of which were used to meet the
domestic demand last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
