<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Courage, Reconciliation for N. Irish Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Thursday said courage and reconciliation will be the watchwords
for Northern Ireland's hard road ahead.
</P>
<P>
In a keynote speech at Belfast's Waterfront Hall with the
attendance of 2,000 politicians and community leaders, Clinton
said, "Courage and reconciliation are the heart of your commitment
to peace."
</P>
<P>
"There will be a hard road ahead. The bombing at Omagh ... was
the opening shot of a vicious attack on peace," he added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived at Belfast from Moscow earlier in the day to
pay a one-day visit to Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
During his speech, the president urged the people of Northern
Ireland to continue on the path towards peace.
</P>
<P>
"As you work to change the shape and future of Northern Ireland
you can count on America."
</P>
<P>
But he warned the audience that the future is "up to you."
</P>
<P>
"Difficult, sometimes wrenching decisions lie ahead but they
must be made," said the president, urging people to "rise above
feuds, not fuel them".
</P>
<P>
"The spirit of reconciliation must be rooted in all you do," he
said, as must courage, which he added was the most important
quality required.
</P>
<P>
He also warned Northern Ireland that the outrage there may not
be the last bombing.
</P>
<P>
Drawing on conflicts around the world, he pointed out that
"people still hate each other."
</P>
<P>
"From here on in Northern Ireland you have said only one
dividing line matters. The line between those who embrace peace
and want to destroy it."
</P>
<P>
Before Clinton's speech, British Prime Minister Tony Blair
lauded praises on Clinton for the help he has given to the
Northern Ireland peace process, saying Clinton has done more to
the Northern Ireland peace process than all other U.S. leaders.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, the president held talks with the members of
the newly-established assembly of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's last visit to Britain was in 1995 which was said to
have given a substantial boost to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president will visit Omagh later in the day and lay a
wreath to the victims of a car bombing that killed 28 people. He
will visit the Irish Republic on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
