<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- David Trimble, first minister
designate of the Northern Irish assembly, on Thursday urged Irish
Republican Army (IRA) to scrap its arms in order to win
ministerial places for their Sinn Fein political allies in the
province's new government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Belfast's Waterfront Hall to welcome U.S. President
Bill Clinton, Trimble said Sinn Fein's readiness to cooperate with
international decommissioning commission was a welcome move, but
that did not go far enough.
</P>
<P>
"If the so-called war is really over, then there is no
justification for holding onto illegal weapons," said Trimble,
also leader of the Ulster Unionist Party, the main group
representing Northern Ireland's pro-British Protestant majority.
</P>
<P>
"Words alone cannot heal the mistrust but deeds will. People
want not just to hear of peace, they want to see it," Trimble
added.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA, declared to give up
violence for ever early this week and then appointed a senior
party figure to contact an international commission on guerrilla
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Trimble said that in line with the Northern Ireland peace
agreement reached last April, IRA must hand over its arms before
Sinn Fein can join the local government.
</P>
<P>
"As First Minister and leader of Northern Ireland, I can not
reconcile seeking positions in government with a failure to
discharge responsibilities under the agreement to dismantle their
terrorist organizations."
</P>
<P>
He also showed good signs of dealing with Sinn Fein which he
has refused to talk directly in the past.
</P>
<P>
"As First Minister I will speak to anyone who has the good of
Northern Ireland at heart. But no democrat can tolerate coercive
threats," he added. 
</P>
