<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Urges Aid to Education Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B. J.
Habibie Thursday urged local governments and businessmen to
provide financial aid to the education sector, saying the
deepening economic crisis has led to a drastic drop in the number
of children in school.
</P>
<P>
"In fiscal year 1996-97, the number of children going to school
reached 72.26 percent, but due to the crisis, this has gone down
to 54 percent, similar to the figure five years ago," the
president said in Semarang, Central Java, during a ceremony to
award scholarships to students.
</P>
<P>
The government has thus decided to provide scholarships to 4
million elementary and high school students and 500,000 college
students and allocate funds to support the operations of 130,000
schools across the country, reports reaching here quoted Habibie
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Besides providing scholarships, the government has also
abolished various levies usually collected by the School
Assistance Board, he said.
</P>
<P>
All these efforts, he added, are aimed at protecting the poor
as well as developing the country's human resources.
</P>
<P>
Habibie said the number of people living in poverty has soared
to 40 percent this year from 11 percent in 1997. Some 80 million
out of 202 million Indonesians are considered poor, he said.
</P>
<P>
In eradicating poverty, the government will introduce the right
technology, particularly to those who live in urban areas, he
said. 
</P>
