<HEADLINE> U.S. to Confiscate Part of Iranian Assets: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States is planning
to seize part of Iranian assets frozen in the U.S. to pay for
former American hostages in Lebanon, local daily Tehran Times
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Iranian presidency told the daily on
Wednesday that according to a recent court verdict, the U.S. is
planning to draw 65 million U.S. dollars out from the frozen
Iranian assets.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. federal judge ruled on August 28 that Iran must pay 65
million dollars in damages to three former hostages and their
families for Tehran's role in their abduction.
</P>
<P>
"If the U.S. does so, it will violate international law,"
warned the Iranian official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
He stated that only the International Court of Justice is
entitled to rule on the possible dispute between the two
countries and the American courts are only responsible for
settling litigation related to domestic issues inside the country
and not about foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, a group of people from western countries were
taken hostages in Lebanon. The hostages were freed in 1988 after
Tehran agreed to use its influence on the pro-Iran Lebanese groups.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Iranian Foreign Ministry Spokesman Mahmoud
Mohammadi also refuted the U.S. court rule, arguing that "how can
one judge of a country issue a verdict against a sovereign,
foreign government?"
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that the verdict against Tehran is in fact a
continuation of an anti-Iranian move "that is doomed to failure."
</P>
</TEXT>
