<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Index of Consumer Expectations Picks Up in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- China's Index of Consumer
Expectations (ICE) picked up 3.5 percentage points on a monthly
basis to 89.4 points in August, according to State Statistics
Bureau figures released today.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time a consumer index has ever been released
in China. Bureau spokesman Qiu Xiaohua said the bureau will
continue to release this information monthly to make it another
important indicator by which to judge the trend of China's
economic performance.
</P>
<P>
Consumer indexes, including ICE, Index of Consumer Sentiment
(ICS) and Index of Current Economic Conditions (ICC), are used
internationally as an indicator to analyze economic situations and
reflect consumers confidence.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the increased index figure indicates
that China's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in the third quarter
will be higher than it was in the first half year.
</P>
<P>
He added that the consumer index reversed its declining July
trend because China's economy continues to develop amid the Asia
financial crisis, market prices are steady or declining to some
extent, and the RMB exchange rate is stable.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, facing the biggest flood in a century, the
Chinese people have united with one heart and one mind to fight
against floods, increasing the cohesion of the Chinese nation.
</P>
<P>
China's Economic Monitoring and Analysis Center under the SSB
set up Surveys of Consumers system in December 1997 and took the
month's ICE as the base of 100 points. It used a random selection
method of 700 samples in each of six cities including Beijing,
Shanghai, Guangzhou, Chengdu, Wuhan and Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
The survey results for August show that about 41 percent of the
respondents believe that in the coming years China's overall
economy will be booming, though 12 percent think it will not be
good.
</P>
<P>
Also, 35 percent said they believe that in the next 12 months
their financial situation will be better than now, and 13 percent
think their situation will be worse.
</P>
<P>
In August, the ICS figure climbed two points to 88.6 and the
ICC remained at 87.3 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
