</P>
<P>
The competition features eight nations including world
champions France and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
FIFA said the Confederation's Cup and the thorny issue of
releasing players for the event was discussed at a meeting
between Blatter, British Minister of Sport Tony Banks and English
F.A. chief executive Graham Kelly on Wednesday in Zurich,
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Because of the timing clash with the league action in England,
Spain and Italy, Blatter said FIFA's executive will review
alternative dates for the competition or reduce the number of
days for which FIFA regulations stipulate players must be
released.
</P>
<P>
The issue will be further discussed at FIFA executive
committee meetings on September 24-25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
