<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: Israeli-Turkish Cooperation Boosts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu has said that the Israeli-Turkish cooperation
is aimed at ensuring peace and stability in the Middle East
region.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Turkey's Daily News newspaper
which was published Thursday, Netanyahu said that the countries
in the region need not worry about the close ties between Israel
and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"Our relationship with Turkey is not directed against any
country. It is directed to the benefit of the entire region,"
Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the world is becoming more unstable in the
absence of an East-West structure and the only sensible
arrangements and frameworks are regional security arrangements
that will try to induce stability where instability prevails.
</P>
<P>
"I think that is exactly the kind of relationship that Israel
has with Turkey," said the Israeli prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The rapidly growing Turco-Israeli military and defense
cooperation has drawn harsh criticism from the Muslim world and
Arab countries who fear it would change the region's balance of
power.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have signed a series of military and defense
accords which enable their air forces to train together and Israel
to help Turkey upgrade its aged fighters and tanks.
</P>
<P>
The naval forces of Israel, Turkey and the United States held
joint exercises in the international waters of the eastern
Mediterranean last January, prompting strong protests from Iran
and Arab nations.
</P>
<P>
"In any case we are not directing this (Israeli-Turkish
alliance) against any countries, but we are trying to create an
axis of stable and responsible countries," Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
"We sometimes see impoverished countries producing ballistic
missiles and atomic warheads and threatening everyone in
sight. This is becoming a very fluid and dangerous situation,"
Netanyahu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
