<HEADLINE> HK Gov't Proposes to Open up TV, Telecom Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government
announced here Thursday a package of proposals to liberalize the
television broadcasting and program services as well as to further
open up the telecommunications market in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The proposals are set out in two separate documents, the 1998
Review of Television Policy and the 1998 Review of Fixed
Telecommunications. Both review documents are intended for a
one-month public consultation, starting from Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Releasing details at a press conference, K. C. Kwong, secretary
for information technology and broadcasting of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR), said that the liberalization
of pay television broadcasting and program services would speed up
technology transfer, attract investment, stimulate the growth of
related industries, and create new employment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"All this will, in turn, enhance Hong Kong's position as a
leading broadcasting hub in the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
"And the further opening up of the telecommunications market,"
he continued, "will enhance the attractiveness of Hong Kong as a
place for investment in telecommunications, encourage competition
and innovation, and maintain Hong Kong's position as the
pre-eminent telecommunication center in Asia," Kwon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
