<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Gov't Appeals to Reduce Weight of School Bags </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Education
Department on Thursday called for actions from schools, teachers,
parents and publishers to reduce the weight of school bags.
</P>
<P>
Principal Education Officer (Curriculum Development Institute)
Lau Kwong-mo said that the department is very concerned about
overweight school bags, in particular their harmful effects on the
formation of spines on primary and junior secondary students.
</P>
<P>
Surveys by local social organizations have showed that school
bags are getting heavier and heavier these years and the society
is appealing for an easing of burden on the children.
</P>
<P>
"For years the department has recommended and encouraged
publishers to use thinner and lighter paper to print textbooks,
particularly those for primary schools. We have also suggested
publishers to print textbooks in loose-leaf form or in split
sections," Lau said, adding that publishers have taken measures
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
The officer noted that guidelines are issued every year to
schools on reducing the weight of school bags.
</P>
<P>
Schools are urged to regularly review their time-tables so that
students would not have to bring to school a large number of
textbooks, exercise books and heavy materials such as atlas,
drawing paper, or sportswear on a particular day, Lau said.
</P>
<P>
Schools are also advised to avoid using excessive supplementary
exercise books or workbooks, said Lau.
</P>
<P>
On the role of parents, he said, they should select light
school bags and stationery for their children, help them develop
the habit of packing school bags every day and bring only
necessary items according to the timetable.
</P>
<P>
"Parents should discourage their children from bringing
magazines, toys and other unnecessary items to school," Lau
suggested.
</P>
<P>
To reduce the weight of school bags, many primary schools were
furnished with lockers for students to keep books, dictionaries
and crayons.
</P>
<P>
Lau urged that schools encourage students to make full use of
these lockers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
