<HEADLINE> Shanghai Industrial Reports Rise in Half-year Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The company announced its interim results here, which showed
that profit attributable to shareholders totaled 622 million HK
dollars (80 million U. S. dollars) in the first six months of
1998, a sharp rise of 43 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Earnings per share grew by 28 percent to 74 cents (nine U.S.
cents), and the Board of directors decided to pay an interim
dividend of 11 cents (1.4 U.S. cents) per share.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure is the biggest profit contributor, accounting
for 54 percent of the company's total in the first half of this
year. Two purchased road projects in Shanghai, Inner Ring Road and
Yan'an Elevated Road, turned in steady cash revenues for the firm.
</P>
<P>
About one third of the company's profit comes from
manufacturing and sales of consumer products, including
cigarettes, printing goods, cosmetics, pharmaceuticals and diary
products.
</P>
<P>
Cai Laixing, Shanghai Industrial's chairman, told a press
conference Thursday that the Asia financial turmoil had slight
impact on the diversified businesses of the company, which went
public on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange in May, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Industrial now holds 3 billion HK dollars (380 million
U.S. dollars) in cash, outweighing its borrowing from banks, said
the chairman, who added that its total liability is less than 25
percent of its capital.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Despite the financial turmoil, we are confident about
the prospects for long-term economic growth in Hong Kong and the
Chinese mainland."
</P>
<P>
The company will continue to tap the potential of the existing
businesses and explore new investment opportunities, according to
Cai. 
</P>
