<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Voters Offered Three Tax Reform Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Eleven million Australian
voters have been offered three different tax reform plans in a
matter of 20 days by competing political parties.
</P>
<P>
The three tax plans were described as risky, lazy and easy,
respectively and Australian voters have until October 3 to decide
which tax plan is their favorite. Last week, Australian Prime
Minister John Howard set October 3 as the date for a federal
election.
</P>
<P>
The first tax reform plan, unveiled by the ruling Australian
Liberal Party and National Party on August 13, was described by
Australia watchers and even some within the two parties as a
courageous but risky one in an election period.
</P>
<P>
The ruling parties introduced their tax reform package,
including a 10-percent goods and services tax (GST), which was
generally welcomed by industrial and business circles and farmers.
</P>
<P>
However, a similar GST tax plan proposed in 1993 cost the
Australian Liberal Party so dearly that the party lost the 1993
federal election because many voters dumped the party as they
feared an introduction would increase the prices of goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 election campaign, Prime Minister John Howard, then
leader of the Liberal Party, promised voters that he would "never
ever" introduce a GST tax.
</P>
<P>
The "lazy" one was offered by the Australian Labor Party
several days after the release of the ruling parties' tax plan,
which rejects a GST tax, but offers more benefit to middle and
lower income earners.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Party's tax plan was rejected as a lazy one by
Federal Treasurer Peter Costello, who released the ruling parties'
tax package with the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Thursday afternoon, an "easy" tax reform plan was released by
Pauline Hanson, founder of racist One Nation Party, in her
hometown Ipswich in east Australia's Queesland state,
</P>
<P>
Under One Nation Party's plan, a flat two-percent income and
transaction tax is proposed, which Pauline Hanson said would leave
every Australian 17 percent better off.
</P>
<P>
Describing the plan as visionary, Hanson said the easy tax
system was fairer for all and would create jobs by lowering costs.
</P>
<P>
But the plan was immediately ridiculed by Treasurer Peter
Costello as economic madness, while the Australian Society of
Certified Practicing Accountants said it would lead to the
collapse of the Australian economy.
</P>
<P>
Under One Nation's plan, the two-percent tax would be levied on
the sale price at each change of ownership of property, goods and
services, including wages.
</P>
<P>
All the parties say their tax plans are better for the country
and beneficial to almost every Australian voter.
</P>
<P>
As Prime Minister John Howard said on August 30 the election
would be fought on economic competence, voters' acceptance of the
three plans is expected to decide who will be the next prime
minister of Australia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS: Updates with Mew Allegation hke090356 --Sacked Malaysian Deputy PM Alleged to Have Homosexual </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Former Deputy
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim had homosexual relationships, sexual
liaisons with women of various races and tried to entice people's
wives, according to an affidavit filed at the High Court here
today.
</P>
<P>
Anwar is also alleged to have received 60 million ringgit
(about 15.789 million U.S. dollars) from S. Nallakaruppan, or
Nalla, during the 1995 general election.
</P>
<P>
Nalla, who is the author of the book "50 Dalil Mengapa Anwar
Tidak Boleh Jadi PM" (50 Reasons Why Anwar Cannot Become PM),
often followed him (Anwar) abroad and acted as middleman in
activities that allowed Anwar to be used by undesirable elements
to threaten national security, the affidavit said.
</P>
<P>
The allegations were contained in the affidavit filed by police
officer Musa Hassan who heads the investigation into the book "50
Dalil Mengapa Anwar Tidak Boleh Jadi PM."
</P>
<P>
Along with affidavits by Attorney-General Mohtar Abdullah,
Prisons Director-General Omar Mohamed Dan and special branch
officer V. Ramasamy, Musa's affidavit was filed to support an
application to set aside Nalla's application for a transfer of his
detention from the Bukit Aman lockup to the Sungai Buloh prison.
</P>
<P>
Nalla is being detained at Bukit Aman under the Internal
Security Act pending his trial for unlawful possession of 125
rounds of Fiocchi 6.35 mm ammunition which police found in Nalla's
house while carrying out investigations into the book.
</P>
<P>
Musa in his affidavit said seven witnesses had given written
statements during the investigations.
</P>
<P>
According to the affidavit, while police were carrying out
their investigations another police report was lodged by a
corporate figure claiming that Anwar tried to entice his wife.
</P>
<P>
Police investigations proved that Nalla too was involved in the
complaint made by the corporate figure.
</P>
<P>
Anwar Ibrahim, who was sacked Wednesday as Malaysia's Deputy
Prime Minister and Finance Minister, said Thursday that there is a
conspiracy at the highest level to ruin him.
</P>
<P>
He told a news conference at his own house here that he was
given a choice by the prime minister to resign or to be removed.
</P>
<P>
"I was not prepared to resign as I was already aware of a pact
or conspiracy at the highest level to ruin me," said Anwar,
claiming that a dirty and disgraceful way had been resorted to in
order to oust him.
</P>
<P>
This is because there was no reasonable truth or basis in
allegations against him to justify his removal, Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he is still the deputy president of the ruling
United Malays National Organization (UMNO) as he was elected to
the post.
</P>
<P>
The UMNO Supreme Council is scheduled to meet Thursday night.
Anwar said, "I will use tonight's forum to defend myself."
</P>
<P>
Anwar also disclosed that he had undergone two DNA tests,
including an independent test outside the country, which proved
that an allegation that he was the father of an illegitimate child
was false.
</P>
<P>
"What I speak (of) is justice. It is tragic that government
institutions have been used by people who plotted against me to
frame up and fabricate charges. If I, as the number two man in the
country (until yesterday), cannot get justice and have become a
victim of these allegations, then I am sorry for this country," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Confirming he was given an ultimatum by the Prime Minister
Wednesday whether to reign or to be removed, Anwar said that he
was not prepared to resign and had repeatedly told the prime
minister that there was a conspiracy at the highest level to
topple him.
</P>
<P>
It included certain cabinet ministers, UMNO Supreme Council
members, corporate figures, people of substantial means and
outsiders, Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
He however said that this action against him did not originate
from UMNO as a political party.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had already expected to be arrested to face
charges under the Official Secret Act (OSA) and possibly the
Internal Security Act (ISA) or other laws.
</P>
<P>
Anwar however said that he would defend himself and his family
members and had initiated the legal process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
