<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Survivors in Swiss Plane Crash Off Canadian Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- There are no survivors from
the crash of the Swissair plane off the coast of Canada's Nova
Scotia province, reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A massive search-and-rescue effort has been under way for
several hours since the wide-bodied jet crashed into the ocean
with 228 passengers and crew about 10:30 p.m. local time Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As dawn broke on the coast, 18 bodies had been recovered from
the sea, according to the CBC Television here.
</P>
<P>
Hospitals in Ottawa, which had been alerted to be prepared for
victims, sent extra staff home early Thursday as hopes for
survivors diminished.
</P>
<P>
"There has been no survivors to date," Chris Power, VC nursing
services at the Queen Elizabeth Hospital of Halifax, said earlier
at a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
The three-engine MD-11 plane, which was carrying 213 passengers
 and 15 crew en route from New York to Geneva, reported smoke in
the cockpit around 10:30 p.m. and asked for emergency landing in
Halifax.
</P>
<P>
Yet shortly after that, the plane disappeared from the radar
screen, lost contact with the air control tower in Moncton, N.B.,
and crashed 11.2 kilometers off the Canadian coast, south of
Halifax.
</P>
<P>
Most of the passengers on board were thought to be Swiss, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
A Hercules aircraft and military aircraft led the search, which
was aided by flotilla of fishing boats.
</P>
<P>
Yet the inky and rough water made it difficult for rescue teams
to navigate through the debris field, which spread a couple of
kilometers across the sea.
</P>
<P>
As dawn broke on the southwest coast of Nova Scotia, a
shoreline search got under way.
</P>
<P>
The weather there was reported to be overcast, with a light
sprinkle of rain.
</P>
<P>
Boeing, the makers of the jet, was sending a team to Nova
Scotia to help in the investigation of the crash.
</P>
<P>
The United States also sent a team of investigators to the
crash site, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
