<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to Boost Peace Efforts in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
arrived at Belfast Thursday morning to begin his two-day visit to
Northern Ireland and the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
He was greeted at the Aldergrove airport by British Prime
Minister Tony Blair after flying in from Moscow where he paid a
two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Upon arriving at the provincial capital, Clinton immediately
went into talks with members of the newly-elected Northern Ireland
assembly, including the assembly's First Minister David Trimble
and his deputy Seamus Mallon.
</P>
<P>
This is Clinton's second visit to Northern Ireland in three
years. His last visit to Britain in 1995 gave a substantial boost
to the peace process in the troubled province.
</P>
<P>
The president will deliver a speech to local politicians and
community leaders and hold a private meeting with Sinn Fein leader
Gerry Adams before visiting Omagh later in the day to meet with
relatives of the bombing victims.
</P>
<P>
The current trip comes at a delicate time. Nearly three weeks
ago, a car bomb in Omagh town center killed 28 people and injured
220, casting a heavy shadow on the peace process in Northern
Ireland since the historic peace agreement was reached in April.
</P>
<P>
Despite the Omagh blast aimed at wrecking the peace process,
this week has witnessed an upbeat turn when the Irish Republican
Army (IRA)'s political wing Sinn Fein announced to let violence be
"a thing of the past, over, done with and gone," and appointed a
senior party leader to represent Sinn Fein in talks with the
independent international decommissioning committee set up to
oversee the disarmament of all paramilitary groups in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
In another development, both the British and Irish parliaments
on Wednesday passed their draconian anti-terrorism bills, which
will make it easier for the two countries to crack down on
terrorism in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has been a pivotal supporter of British and Irish peace
moves that gained new life in July 1997 with a ceasefire by the
anti-British Irish Republican Army. He is expected to use his
political influence this time again to add momentum to the current
peace initiatives.
</P>
<P>
Just as a White House spokesman put it, President Clinton sees
his visit to Omagh as "a way of continuing to support the peace
process and make it clear that those who would use violence to
stop the peace process will not succeed." 
</P>
</TEXT>
