<HEADLINE> First Pan-African Dance Festival Opens in Kigali </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The first pan-African dance
festival has unfolded itself in the Rwandan capital Kigali.
</P>
<P>
The nine-day festival, jointly sponsored by the Rwandan
government and the Organization of Africa Unity, has "African
Dance for Peace" as its central theme, the Rwanda News Agency
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Starting from Tuesday, the festival is aimed at encouraging
the youth to foster the spirit of tolerance and peace, after
decades of conflicts and atrocities that rocked the continent and
which culminated into the 1994 genocide in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Among the objectives of the festival will be the
re-vigorization of political and diplomatic relations between the
states, which go beyond linguistics and ideological barriers.
</P>
<P>
Sources in the Rwandan Ministry of Culture have indicated that
the festival will cost about 544,396 U.S. Dollars. Out of
seventeen delegations invited to attend the festival only a few
responded positively.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from Uganda, Burundi, the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC), and Rwandans living in Belgium, were present at the
opening ceremony. There was no word about countries like Angola,
Zimbabwe, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Zambia, South Africa, and the
Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
But analysts here believe that the on-going conflict in Congo
(K) might have affected the participation when some delegations
might have felt not secure enough in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Others like Zimbabwe, and Angola which have divergent views
over the Congo crisis have seen relations with Rwanda growing
strained.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda wants to be the capital of the African Dance Festival,
as Ouagadougou of Burkina Faso is for the African film, and
Brazzaville of Congo for the African Music. 
</P>
</TEXT>
