<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Police Disperse Striking Workers at Mando Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Some 10,000 South Korean riot
police Thursday morning raided six factories of Mando Machinery
Corp., breaking up striking workers who had occupied and paralyzed
the nation's largest auto parts maker for 18 days.
</P>
<P>
Riot police armed with tear gas and water canons stormed into
the factories at around 6 a.m. Thursday and arrested some labor
leaders and strikers.
</P>
<P>
Police said several striking workers and police were wounded
when strikers in Mando's two plants in Asan in South Chunchong
Province and Munmak in Kangwon Province fought back violently with
stones and pipes.
</P>
<P>
Police dispersed most of the striking workers and hauled away
some 1,600 union workers while they met with little resistance in
the other four factories.
</P>
<P>
However, police, who reportedly failed to arrest top union
leaders, said they will arrest the key organizers of the illegal
strike on charges of obstructing commerce.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that the South Korean government has used
police force to solve a labor dispute, which the government fears
have made foreign investors to suspect its determination to ensure
a flexible labor market.
</P>
<P>
Government officials defended the police raid, saying that it
was inevitable given the strike's negative impact on the nation's
auto industry.
</P>
<P>
The police raid was also seen as a show of the government's
strong determination not to allow illegal strikes after its
intervention in the labor dispute at Hyundai Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Korean Confederation of Trade Unions (KCTU)
denounced the police raids and said it would launch an
anti-government campaign.
</P>
<P>
"We can not tolerate the police raids. We will stage a general
strike and consider pulling out of the tripartite committee of
labor, management and government, " said a spokesman for the
KCTU.
</P>
<P>
Mando's workers have been on strike since August 17 this year,
protesting the corporation's plan to lay off 1,090 of a total of
4,500 workers.
</P>
<P>
Mando, which supplies auto parts to domestic car makers and
exports its products to foreign automakers such as GM and Ford,
went bankrupt last December in the wake of the nation's financial
crisis caused by corporate failures and bad loans of financial
institutions late last year.
</P>
<P>
A slumping domestic auto market has dealt a more serious blow
to the struggling company this year, with its sales plunging 32
percent from a year earlier in the first six months.
</P>
<P>
Mando management said the strike has made the company suffer a
loss of 97.6 billion won (about 72.7 million U.S. dollars) in
production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian CPP, Sihanouk Discuss Ways to Form New Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SIEM REAP, Cambodia, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Second
Prime Minister Hun Sen and three other senior members of the
Cambodian People's Party (CPP) met with King Norodom Sihanouk
Thursday here to discuss ways to form a new government.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen, CPP leader, told reporters after the meeting that they
discussed the convening of the first session of the new National
Assembly (parliament) and formation of a new government.
</P>
<P>
He said, "in order to resolve the current political crisis, the
CPP insists that the King presides over the session and approves
the formation of a new government. The other political parties
should respect the people's will."
</P>
<P>
"Secondly, if the new National Assembly starts to operate but
the new government could not be formed, the current government led
by (First Prime Minister) Ung Hout and I will continue to work as
a caretaker government. We will never agree to form an interim
government."
</P>
<P>
"Thirdly, it would be a worse situation if neither the new
Assembly nor the new government can operate. But the present
government will continue to exist," Hun Sen added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a special meeting of the three main political
parties to be held here on September 5-7, which King Sihanouk will
preside over in a hope to solve the month-long political crisis,
Hun Sen said he and CPP President Chea Sim will attend on behalf
of the CPP.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the Funcinpec Party and Sam Rainsy Party (SRP)
will also send their top leaders to the meeting, which, in his
point of view, will help break the deadlock Cambodia is currently
facing.
</P>
<P>
But it was learned that Funcinpec Party leader Prince Norodom
Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy Party leader Sam Rainsy have not yet had
any plan to take part in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen quoted the King as saying amending of the country's
constitution should be carried out in the new National Assembly
and the power-sharing must be done according to the people's will.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Hun Sen may put forward his idea of getting
Assembly members to amend the constitution so that the CPP could
form a government with only a simple majority rather than
two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
The CPP won the July 26 Assembly election according to the
final official results announced by the National Election
Committee (NEC) on September 1. But it did not win the two-thirds
necessary to form a new government on its own.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Funcinpec and SRP rejected the election results
and insisted they would not join any government headed by Hun Sen,
whom they accuse of staging a coup d'etat to oust Prince Ranariddh
as first premier last year.
</P>
<P>
CPP Honorary Chairman Heng Samrin and Treasurer Chea Soth were
also present at Thursday's meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
