<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Voters Offered 3 Tax Reform Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Eleven million Australian
voters have been offered three different tax reform plans in a
matter of 20 days by competing political parties.
</P>
<P>
The three tax plans were described as risky, lazy and easy,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The first tax reform plan, unveiled by the ruling Australian
Liberal Party and National Party on August 13, was described by
Australia watchers and even some within the two parties as a
courageous but risky one in an election period.
</P>
<P>
The ruling parties introduced their tax reform package,
including a 10-percent goods and services tax (GST), which was
generally welcomed by industrial and business circles and farmers.
</P>
<P>
However, a similar GST tax plan proposed in 1993 cost the
Australian Liberal Party so dearly that the party lost the 1993
federal election because many voters dumped the party as they
feared an introduction would increase the prices of goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 election campaign, Prime Minister John Howard, then
leader of the Liberal Party, made a promise to the voters that he
would "never ever" introduce a GST tax.
</P>
<P>
The "lazy" one was offered by the Australian Labor Party
several days after the release of the ruling parties' tax plan,
which rejects a GST tax, but offers more benefit to middle and
lower income earners.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Party's tax plan was rejected as a lazy one by
Federal Treasurer Peter Costello, who released the ruling parties'
tax package with the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Thursday afternoon, an "easy" tax reform plan was released by
Pauline Hanson, founder of racist One Nation Party, in her
hometown Ipswich in east Australia's Queesland state,
</P>
<P>
Under One Nation Party's plan, a flat two-percent income and
transaction tax is proposed, which Pauline Hanson said would leave
every Australian 17 percent better off.
</P>
<P>
Describing the plan as visionary, Hanson said the easy tax
system was fairer for all and would create jobs by lowering costs.
</P>
<P>
But the plan was immediately ridiculed by Treasurer Peter
Costello as economic madness, while the Australian Society of
Certified Practicing Accountants said it would lead to the
collapse of the Australian economy.
</P>
<P>
Under One Nation's plan, the two-percent tax would be levied on
the sale price at each change of ownership of property, goods and
services, including wages.
</P>
<P>
All the parties said their tax plans are better for the country
and beneficial to almost every Australian voter.
</P>
<P>
As Prime Minister John Howard said on August 30 the election
would be fought on economic competence, voters' acceptance of the
three plans is expected to decide who will be the next prime
minister of Australia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Stock Market Closes Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Share prices gyrated from
positive to negative territory on Singapore Stock Market Thursday
as market was decimated by worries over dramatic changes in
Malaysia's government and its financial policy
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index dropped 15.15 points to end
at 812.70 points.
</P>
<P>
Both the dismissal of Malaysia's Deputy Prime Minister Anwar
Ibrahim and the country's latest move to ban overseas trading of
its currency and stocks had big impact on Singapore since the two
countries are closely linked with their economies intertwined.
</P>
<P>
Bank shares were among the hardest hit on renewed concerns
about Singapore banks exposure to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover edged up to 277.78 million units valued at
225.69 million Singapore dollars (about 128.23 million U.S.
dollars). Decliners outstripped advancers by 301 to 39 with 246
counters unchanged
</P>
<P>
SingTel was the most active stock of the day with a turnover of
17.70 million stocks. It was followed by Renong that had 17.22
million units traded. M Res was next with 15.69 million counters
changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Asean topped the gainers of the day as it rose by 20 cents to
close at 3.00 U.S. dollars. SingTel was up 10 cents to finish at
2.60 Singapore dollars. Both HL Fin and Republic edged up five
cents and they closed at 1.06 and 0.43 Singapore dollars
respectively. RothmansI also inched up five cents and it ended at
6.65 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Genting 200 lost 98 cents to end at 2.00
Singapore dollars. Tasek slid by 59.5 cents to close at 0.805
Singapore dollars. Rothmans M shed 50 cents to finish at 7.50
Singapore dollars. 
</P>
