<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe, Angola Involvement in Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DURBAN, South Africa, September 3 (Xinhua) -- South African
President Nelson Mandela said Thursday it was reasonable that
Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola had deployed troops in Democratic
Congo (DRC) after they received the government's invitation.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in the International Convention
Center here, Mandela said it was reasonable for the Congolese
government headed by President Laurent Kabila to request foreign
countries to offer military support when it was necessary.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mandela said, it was also reasonable for countries
like Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola which sent their troops to
Congo early last month to help the Kabila government quell the
rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's remarks have apparently shown his tendency toward
military involvement in Congo by some member states of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
South Africa is the current chairman of the 14-member SADC.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, who was here to attend the 12th Non-Aligned Movement
summit which opened Wednesday, told reporters Wednesday night
that the military involvement by Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia was
at the invitation of his government.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that as Rwandan and Ugandan troops illegally
entered into Congo, they must be withdrawn immediately. "It is
aggressors who should cease fire," Kabila stressed.
</P>
<P>
Kabila has been accusing Rwanda and Uganda of backing the
Tutsi rebels who launched a revolt against his government on
August 2.
</P>
<P>
However, the charges have been strongly denied by the two
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Mandela told reporters that he met all the leaders of the SADC
countries except Kabila and President Sam Nujoma of Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Kabila was back home late last night because of the tense
situation in his country, while Nujoma had gone for other
engagement. However, both Kabila and Nujoma were represented at
the meeting, said Mandela.
</P>
<P>
The SADC leaders discussed the tense situation in Congo at
working breakfast, Mandela said, but he declined to give details.
</P>
<P>
In the joint press conference, United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who participated in the SADC
mini-summit, said the meeting was "useful" and "constructive".
</P>
<P>
"We are making progress," said Annan. He also declined to
specify the progress.
</P>
<P>
Salim Ahmed Salim, secretary-general of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU), also attended the conference. He said the
OAU would continue its efforts with the SADC countries to make
peace settlement of the Congo conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
