<HEADLINE> Clinton Encourages Chernomyrdin to Tide over Political Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Thursday urged Russian acting Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin
to tackle Russia's political crisis, a White House spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters on board Clinton's Air
Force One plane from Moscow to Belfast that the president held 25
minutes' conversation with Chernomyrdin before he wound up a
two-day visit to Russia, Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
"The president encouraged Chernomyrdin to do everything
possible to try to get beyond this current political crisis so
that the country can get behind a strong economic program,"
McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
"In the end, putting the government together and resolving some
of the political questions that are still lingering is a necessary
predicate to start putting together strong economic policies that
can move the country forward," he quoted Clinton as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The president's observation to Chernomyrdin was that you need
to resolve these political issues about the formation of the
government so you can get on with the urgent task of fixing the
economy," he added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived at Northern Irish capital of Belfast Thursday
morning to show his support to the peace process in Northern
Ireland. He will meet the relatives of the Omagh bombing victims
later in the day and pay a one-day visit to the Irish Republic on
Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
