<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Marginally Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
only marginally higher in subdued trading Thursday in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
It reached a high of 58.73 U.S. cents before closing at 58.36
U.S. cents, just up from Wednesday night's close of 58.27 U.S.
cents, as market participants awaited fresh directions.
</P>
<P>
Guy Reynolds, director of foreign exchange division director of
Macquarie Bank, said the Australian dollar was dragged down to its
low for the day of 58.23 U.S. cents by an Australian
dollar/Japanese yen order from a U.S. hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
Reynolds said the Australian dollar had been very steady for
the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
In a market commentary published Thursday, Stephen Koukoulas,
Citibank chief economist, said the recent recovery in the
Australian dollar from its all-time low of 55.30 U.S. cents to
levels around 58.00 U.S. cents had been supported by a number of
factors such as solid data on Australia economy, a yen pick-up and
a moderate upturn in some commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
In offshore trade Thursday night Reynolds expects the
Australian dollar to trade higher, probably to 59.00 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The local currency was trading at 79.63 Japanese yen from 80.10
yen and 1.0161 German marks from 1.0186 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
