<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overbooking Strands Hundreds of Passengers in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of passengers have
been stranded at the Beirut International Airport since last
Saturday due to overbooking by Lebanon's national carrier Middle
East Airlines (MEA), the Daily Star reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Airport sources estimated that the overbooking stands at 30
percent for some destinations, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
All airlines overbook to avoid having vacant seats on their
planes. When a plane is full, those passengers who show up last at
the airport are the first to lose their seats.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that this happened a lot over the last two
weeks, the high season during which Lebanese expatriates and
foreign tourists return home.
</P>
<P>
The passengers who failed to get the seats complained that MEA
has not offered any accommodation for the passengers. Many of them
are foreign tourists who have nowhere to go.
</P>
<P>
They said that "certain people can get seats on the flight
through connections or by paying MEA officials 100 U.S. dollars or
even more."
</P>
<P>
The chaos at the airport has prompted the intervention of
Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri.
</P>
<P>
He summoned MEA's chairman Mohammed Hout for a meeting about
the airline's booking system.
</P>
<P>
Hout said the accusations were highly exaggerated, adding that
the company offers compensation for passengers and provide hotel
rooms for those who are stranded.
</P>
<P>
MEA, 99 percent of which are owned by the country's central
bank, has a total of 4,500 staff with only 10 aircrafts.
</P>
<P>
It lost 10 million U.S. dollars last year and is expected to
lose the same amount this year, according to Hout. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
