<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall in Tokyo on Hitachi Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices fell in Tokyo Thursday
for the first time in four trading days on news that Japan's major
electrical machinery maker Hitachi Ltd. is expected to suffer a pretax
loss of 100 billion yen (about 725 million dollars) this business
year.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange dropped 115.38 points, or 0.80
percent, from Wednesday's close to end at 14,261.24.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 4.99 points or 0.45 percent to 1,113.77.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to an estimated 375 million
shares from Wednesday's 485.31 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Hitachi's share price plunged moments after the opening bell
following a newspaper report that the flagship company may record an
annual loss for the first time in its 78-year history.
</P>
<P>
The news also triggered a drop in other technology shares,
including NEC, Fujitsu, Toshiba and Rohm.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many banking shares got a lift on indications that the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and opposition parties are
coming closer to passing legislation to rescue ailing big banks by the
use of public funds.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,341 issues listed on the First Section, losers
outnumbered gainers 830 to 289, with 170 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
