<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mbeki Writes to Mugabe to Clear up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki has written to Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe "hopefully to clear any misunderstandings" in South
Africa's handling of the Congo (K) crisis.
</P>
<P>
A copy of the letter, which was also sent to Southern African
Development Community (SADC) leaders, has been leaked exclusively
to The Star, the daily newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki included a copy of a front-page report of The Sunday
Independent newspaper, in which Mugabe was quoted as saying the
South African-led peace plan for the Democratic Republic of the
Congo (DRC) had reached a dead end.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Mugabe also accused Mbeki of being
discourteous by not returning his telephone calls, and not
telling him where and when the meeting of SADC heads of state
over Congo crisis would take place.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe did not attend the summit on August 23 in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki wrote: "I consider the matters raised (in The Sunday
Independent report) of such gravity that I thought it would be
proper that I write to you, hopefully to clear any
misunderstandings which may exist."
</P>
<P>
Mbeki explained that South Africa had originally planned two
meetings -- the first involving Congo, Angola, Zimbabwe, Uganda,
Rwanda and South Africa; the second including SADC's heads of
state.
</P>
<P>
When Mbeki contacted Mugabe over the arrangements of the
meetings, Mugabe said only one meeting should be held because too
short notice had |3n given for a SADC summit, Mbeki wrote.
</P>
<P>
"This would be attended by Congo, Angola, Zimbabwe, Namibia,
Zambia, Uganda, Rwanda, Tanzania, Mozambique and South Africa."
</P>
<P>
However, South African President Nelson Mandela had then
contacted SADC heads of state who said they would be able to
attend the meeting in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
"It therefore became clear that... it would be incorrect to
tell them that the SADC summit should be canceled, in favor of
the meeting you, Mr. President, had proposed."
</P>
<P>
"I then called you to report on this development, having
undertaken to come back to you in any case," Mbeki wrote.
</P>
<P>
"Your office in Harare told me that you had already knocked
off. When I sought to speak to your senior staff, I was told that
they also had knocked off. The only people remaining, I was
informed, were the telephonist and the typist."
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said he subsequently sent the message to Mugabe through
Zimbabwe's High Commission to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
On August 22, Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano told
Mandela that Mugabe would not attend the Pretoria summit as he
insisted there should be only one meeting.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to assure you, Mr. President, that no
discourtesy was ever intended, and no information was ever
deliberately kept away from you," Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki also told Mugabe that reports that South Africa and
Tanzania were involved in training DRC rebels, and that South
Africa was supplying arms to Rwanda and Uganda, were false.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki's letter pointedly goes on: "Part of the tragedy, of
course, is that when the dust has settled over the current Congo
crisis, the inextricable ties among us and the common interest
will still require that all of us cooperate with one another for
the mutual benefit."
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said his government had no desire to impose itself on
anybody.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, and other SADC member states, are pushing for a
diplomatic solution to the Congo conflict, while Zimbabwe,
Namibia and Angola are militarily involved in propping up
Congolese President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Mandela hosted a breakfast meeting of southern African leaders
in Durban Thursday morning on the Congo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was arranged by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
and Salim Ahmed Salim, secretary-general of the Organization of
African Unity.
</P>
<P>
Neither Kabila nor his ally, Namibian President Sam Nujoma,
were there. They left Durban Wednesday night and early Thursday
morning respectively and asked Mugabe to represent them at the
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
