<HEADLINE> Nigeria Approves Pay Rise for Civil Servants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
approved a pay rise package for civil servants, with effect from
last Tuesday, media reports said.
</P>
<P>
With the new package, civil servants at the lowest level will
now receive a monthly salary of about 5,200 Naira (61 U.S.
Dollars), a 500 percent rise from the previous 800 Naira (nine
Dollars), while those at higher levels may earn as much as 30,000
Naira (353 Dollars) a month.
</P>
<P>
The pay rise was conveyed to all ministries and government
bodies in a circular dated August 31, 1998, and signed by Alhaji
Gidado Idris, secretary to the federal government, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The circular, however, said the pay rise was only for civil
servants working for the federal government, while workers of
state governments have to negotiate with their respective
employers for necessary adjustment.
</P>
<P>
The decision to review the salary of civil servants was based
on recommendations by a special committee formed by the Nigerian
government.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the committee submitted its report in
June last year, but the matter was abandoned until General
Abdulsalam Abubakar took over the power three months ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
