<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 09:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Contractors Called to Bid for Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Oil Minister Bijan
Namdar Zanganeh on Thursday called on Iranian contractors to bid
for the country's oil and gas development projects, after foreign
bidders showed less enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar to introduce the country's oil and gas
projects, Zanganeh said that it was a good opportunity for Iranian
contractors to take part in the country's development projects.
</P>
<P>
"If the Iranian contractors bid for the projects, surely they
will win," he said, expressing regret that Iranian contractors
showed little interest in the development projects.
</P>
<P>
At the two-day seminar opened on Wednesday, the National Iran
Oil Company (NIOC) introduced 29 oil and gas projects with a total
cost of about 80 billion U.S. dollars to domestic companies.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was scheduled to be held early in August, but was
postponed due to "lack of enthusiasm" shown by foreign bidders,
according to local media.
</P>
<P>
"The NIOC has decided to give the projects mainly to domestic
companies," local daily Iran news said last month.
</P>
<P>
The projects were also introduced to foreign companies in
London early in July. According to Iranian deputy oil minister
Mehdi Husseini, so far about 72 foreign companies, including
three American, have shown "interest" in the projects.
</P>
<P>
Iran expects to promote the country's oil and gas production
capacity by 1.4 million barrels per day and 70 million cubic
meters per day respectively through the 29 projects on a buyback
basis.
</P>
<P>
Under the buyback mechanism, companies are paid and receive a
profit for developing projects by receiving crude or condensate
from the field. The formula gets round the constitutional
prohibition of foreign ownership or production rights in Iran's
natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Some European and American companies have expressed their
interest in the projects, but they are facing the challenge of the
Iran-Libya Sanctions Act of the U.S., which threatens to impose
sanctions on foreign firms that invest more than 20 million
dollars a year in Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Investment Funds Weather Bearish Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The five newly listed
securities investment funds have weathered a sluggish stock market
recently, reducing their losses in face value to an average of 3
percent while stock prices dropped more than 12 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
It is not easy for the funds to achieve such results since they
have heavy positions and the market has been quite bearish while
moving downward, according to stock analysts.
</P>
<P>
"It is a strong support for the fund managers' rational way of
investment since the stocks the fund managers have selected
outperformed the market," they said.
</P>
<P>
China started launching securities investment funds in April,
with an intention to create new market stabilizers. The five funds
are worth 2 billion yuan (241 million US dollars) each, and have a
term of 15 years.
</P>
<P>
Wise judgement of the market movement also shielded the funds
from losses, analysts said. The Hua'an Fund Management Co. Ltd.,
for instance, was founded on June 22 when the Composite Stock
Index in Shanghai was around 1,400 points. Instead of buying
heavily, the company managers waited until the market moved to a
lower level.
</P>
<P>
The fund managers also invest in a flexible way: they usually
put money into companies with good quality and prospects, but they
also sell stocks when the prices are high and buy again at lower
prices.
</P>
<P>
"Long-term investment in good companies surely yields good
returns, but we also managed to reduce our costs by taking
advantage of the market movement," said a fund manager.
</P>
<P>
Based on the fact that all five new funds have successfully
outperformed the market so far, market analysts have predicted a
bright future for the funds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 09:19 </DATE_TIME>
