<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Scientists Need More Support and Understanding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Lack of understanding and
support from society have kept down the number of women scientists
who have achieved major scientific achievements as compared with
their men colleagues, a female scientist said today.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Hui, deputy head of the Life Science Institute of the
Jilin University in northeast China, made her remarks at the
ongoing Eighth National Congress of Chinese Women.
</P>
<P>
"The number of female scientific workers has increased a lot in
recent years, but the higher the degrees they attain, the greater
the pressures they will face both from the society and their
families," she said, adding that some excellent women, even those
with doctorate degrees, have difficulty finding a spouse.
</P>
<P>
Childbirth is another burden female scientists have to
shoulder, and bearing a child can cost two years out of her career
because of the low socialization level of Chinese family household
chores.
</P>
<P>
She called on the government and society to offer special help
to female scientists, reducing their time away from work to three
months after giving birth, and then providing them with child care
assistance, the standard for many advanced countries.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics shows that China had 9.9 million female
scientists, 37 percent of the scientific sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
