<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sacked Malaysian Deputy PM Says Charges Against Him </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Anwar Ibrahim, who was
sacked Wednesday evening as Malaysia's deputy prime minister and
finance minister, broke his silence and said Thursday all charges
against him are totally fabricated.
</P>
<P>
Four affidavits were filed at the High Court here Thursday
containing various allegations against Anwar, including sexual
misconduct and posing a threat to national security.
</P>
<P>
"It's total fabrication. I'm going to fight it all the way,"
Anwar told reporters from his vehicle as he was leaving the Deputy
Prime Minister's official residence at Jalan Sri Perdana here
Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Anwar accompanied by his wife Wan Azizah Wan Ismail and their
children was leaving for his own house in Bukit Damansara, about 4
kilometers away, where he is expected to hold a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who is Deputy President of the United Malays National
Organization (UMNO), said he would attend the UMNO Supreme Council
meeting scheduled Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was said to have been receiving a stream of visitors the
whole Wednesday night since his dismissal was announced by the
Prime Minister's Department Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Anwar's official residence here is still under police guard and
all roads leading to it have been blocked by the authorities.
</P>
<P>
The situation was calm and visitors including Anwar's
supporters were allowed in after being thoroughly checked.
</P>
</TEXT>
