<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Hold Judges Responsible for Illegal Trial Practices (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to this new system, the decision on the justice of a
court order, judgement or verdict must be made by a judicial
committee of the people's court, and disciplinary and supervisory
bodies within the courts are responsible for gathering evidence
and meting out penalties.
</P>
<P>
Such penalties may be self-criticism and official announcements
of criticism for those whose misdeeds are minor, disciplinary
punishments for those who cause serious consequences, and transfer
to other judiciary bodies for legal proceedings for those who are
suspected of committing or have committed a crime.
</P>
<P>
However, if a wrongful court ruling is made out of
misunderstanding of the law or of the evidence, or verdicts are
changed because of new evidence or alterations in the law, the
court of law and its staff are free from responsibilities, said Li.
</P>
<P>
Li also said that public supervision of the enforcement of this
new method is invited.
</P>
<P>
"The wrongful verdict responsibility system" was first
instituted in China in early 1990, and later extended to most
Chinese courts. Many judges have been disciplined under this rule,
and many have been fired or punished under criminal codes,
according to Li.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Militiamen in Somali Capital Demobilized with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A new hope is present for
the militiamen supporting Mogadishu's faction leaders who
recently claimed the establishment of a joint administration for
the Somali capital.
</P>
<P>
The aspiration of the militiamen started with salary payment
for the first time since the withdrawal of the multi-national
forces -- United Nations Operation for Somalia -- from Somalia
in early 1995.
</P>
<P>
Since the announcement of Mogadishu's administration, the
three faction leaders, Ali Mahdi, Hussein Aidid and Mohamed
Qanyare, have been trying to commit themselves to making a
functioning administration for the capital.
</P>
<P>
According to Colonel Abdi Hassan AwalempTY 1did, chief police
commander for Mogadishu's administration, more than 1,300
militiamen who had been in the camps for 20 days were demobilized
after receiving their first wages Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The police commander who is a military colonel himself said
every militiama will be taking 300,000 Somali Shillings (37.5
U.S. Dollars) for each of the first three months in which they are
being trained for their jobs. He added that each man will be
receiving 100 Dollars as their permanent salary afterwards.
</P>
<P>
Qeybdid, who seems to have fallen out with Osman Ali Atto for
whom he had been the interior secretary, said the money has been
a contribution and donation from Somali businessmen who are
working hard for the stability of Mogadishu and their nation at
large.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters Thursday for the first time since he was
nominated for the post that the businessmen are also paying for
the meals for the 1,300-strong militiamen encamped for
Mogadishu's administration.
</P>
<P>
"Despite pledges, we have received no foreign assistance so
far," said Qeybdid.
</P>
<P>
The Colonel said 800 more militiamen and 900 former policemen
will also be encamped in the next few days for the completion of
the first round of the militia demobilization.
</P>
<P>
Besides, dozens of battle wagons including those mounted with
double barrel anti-aircraft heavy machine-guns were demobilized
in the former Police School in south Mogadishu and the main
former Police Transport Headquarters of north Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
"The second round of the demobilization which will be another
3,000 men will begin in 45 days," said Qeybdid.
</P>
<P>
Fears of inter-clan or factional clashes in Mogadishu seem to
be diminishing despite strong words from Osman Ali Atto, General
Mohamed Sheikh Osman and Hussein Hajji Bod following the
announcement of Mogadishu's administration.
</P>
<P>
More militiamen are likely to turn for Ali Mahdi, Hussein
Aidid and Mohamed Qanyare Afrah as long as they are offering jobs
with payments for them.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, the streets in the capital will be much safer with
the increasing number of demobilized militiamen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
