<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Leaves Russia for Northern Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
concluded his Russia visit Thursday and left here for Belfast,
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
During the visit in Russia, which started Monday, Clinton held
two rounds of talks with his Russian counterpart Boris Yeltsin on
Russia's financial and economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Clinton pledged to back Moscow as long as it stays on the
course of reforms, but stopped short of offering specific
financial or economic assistance.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed a number of joint statements on common
challenges to security at the turn of the century, on exchanges of
information on missile launchings and early warning, and on
principles for reprocessing plutonium from dismantled nuclear
warheads.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also signed agreements on prohibition of
chemical weapons, trade, investment and technological
cooperation, aviation safety and cultural cooperation.
</P>
<P>
After visiting the British province, Clinton will proceed to
Ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
