<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Agro Authority on Measures to Help Flood-Hit Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Ministry of
Agriculture is working on effective measures to help flood-ravaged
areas restore agricultural production in an effort to secure an
autumn harvest.
</P>
<P>
Minister Chen Yaobang said that flooding along the Yangtze and
Songhua rivers and the Nenjiang River Basin since June has
affected the rice crop in the southern part of the country, and
the maize, rice and bean harvest in the northeastern region.
</P>
<P>
China has had 21 million hectares of crop fields affected by
the worst flood disaster since 1954.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged the broad use of electric draining machines
on flood-affected farmlands, and rush repairs of flood-damaged
water conservancy projects.
</P>
<P>
Cash-crop vegetables with short growing period should be
encouraged for autumn planting and the harvest management
intensified, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chen also asked fishing departments at various levels to take
time to organize workers to dredge fish ponds and reduce the
amount of fish lost to the floods.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, attention is also being paid to precautions
for preventing epidemics among farm animals and resuming
production in township enterprises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
