<HEADLINE> US President Arrives to Support N. Ireland's Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
arrived at Belfast Thursday morning for a one-day visit to boost
the peace process in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived from a two-day official visit to Russia and was
met at the Belfast International Airport by British Prime Minister
Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is due to make a speech to politicians and community
leaders in Belfast before visiting Omagh, where a car bomb blast
on August 15 killed 28 people and wrecked the town center.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is a firm supporter of a British-Irish peace drive.
The peace process in the province took a turn in April when the
parties agreed on a historic peace agreement to end 30-year
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president is scheduled to visit the Irish Republic on
Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
