<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Men Paddlers Languish in Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- In 1986, they won Asian
champion; in 1988, they took the world's first Olympic men's
singles champion; in 1990, they were still Asia's number one --
even China found no way to conquer their traditional rivals.
</P>
<P>
But the 1990 Asian Games became the South Korean men paddlers'
last glory. For around eight years, they have never won a single
Olympic or world title. When their Chinese counterparts resumed
dominance, the South Koreans found they are facing a crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The table tennis is just like our economy, it's in a crisis,"
said Lee Sang Kook, who heads the South Korean national team
competing in the Chinese Grand Prix here.
</P>
<P>
"Except Yoo Nam-Kyu and Kim Taek Soo, we can hardly find a
third one in the team," Lee lamented.
</P>
<P>
But the two veterans, pillar of the South Korean team for over
10 years, can overcome all the difficulties but their age en
route to regaining their form as Yoo, the 1988 Olympic champion,
is 30 and Kim, 1992 Olympic bronze medalist, 28.
</P>
<P>
Yoo and Kim, who brought South Korea's table tennis to the
peak that their successors can hardly scale in the coming years,
have seen their confidence shaken with the emergence of young
Chinese stars like Olympic champion Liu Guoliang and 1995 world
champion Kong Linghui.
</P>
<P>
"Kong has made a great improvement since last year," said Kim,
ranked 11th in the world and a losing finalist to Kong at last
week's Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
"His backhand, speed, topspin have all been improved. He has
a better chance if we meet again in the final," Kim said. "China
has a lot of promising young stars, so the gap between us is
getting wider."
</P>
<P>
Coach Lee hoped Kim can regain flair and form to reach the
final again in the Chinese Grand Prix, which will run until
Sunday. On the other side, he said they took the Grand Prix as a
training ground and warm-up chance for the 13th Asian Games
scheduled in Bangkok, Thailand, in December.
</P>
<P>
"Asian Games is the most important thing for all of us. The
government want us to win at least two gold medals in Bangkok or
the team will be greatly changed." said Lee, who took over the
national team last year, meaning that he would be sacked if his
team failed to win two golds at the Asiad.
</P>
<P>
But the coach found he could do little to revive the sport in
a financial crisis-hit nation. "The money they (the government)
give us is getting less and less, how can we win gold medals
without money?" Lee said. "We had more than 10 players in the
national team years ago, but now we can only support six or sev
en."
</P>
<P>
The national coach also has difficulties in finding young
talent across the country.
</P>
<P>
"There are less than 2,000 young people playing table tennis
in the whole country." Lee said.
</P>
<P>
In his team, Lee said the 21-year-old Oh Sang Eun has a lot of
potential but the 16-year-old Yoo Seong Min might be the person
who will shoulder the responsibility for renaissance of the
nation's table tennis.
</P>
<P>
"Oh is very good but too weak mentally," Lee said, "Yoo has
showed his talent in the recent China-Japan-South Korea
friendlies for the youths. He is very talented and only 16. But
it takes time." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
