<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China Strains to Prevent Financial Risks (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- China has been steadily
accelerating financial reforms and regulating the economic order
to guard against financial risks, said Liu Mingkang, vice-governor
of the People's Bank of China (PBOC), in a recent interview with
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"With the deepening of financial reforms, a multi-layer and
multi-type modern financial system has begun to take shape," Liu
said.
</P>
<P>
The financial turmoil which erupted last July in Thailand swept
across southeast Asian countries, seriously damaging the economy
of Republic of Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the Asian financial crisis, the most serious
since the 1950s, resulted from an unscientific financial structure.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has drawn lessons from the crisis and
promoted timely financial reforms.
</P>
<P>
The head office of the PBOC just last year completed the
restructuring after it decided to disband the provincial
subsidiaries step-by-step and establish larger trans-provincial
branches, according to Liu.
</P>
<P>
The state-run financial institutions are also speeding up their
pace of commercialization. For instance, the country pushed its
commercial banks into the market by revoking the ceiling on bank
loans in January.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks have also been given the right to run
themselves in accordance with their asset-to-liability ratio.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China has established the State Security
Regulatory Commission to supervise the securities market, and a
special insurance supervisory organization will also be
established.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo (K) Allied Armies Agree on Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A meeting of army chiefs of
staff of Angola, Zimbabwe, Namibia and Democratic Congo (DRC)
ended Wednesday night with a resolve to safeguard militarily the
stability of the Southern African Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
The meeting also noted that coalition military intervention in
the Congo conflict is aimed at preventing the rebels of ethnic
Tutsis from taking power by armed force.
</P>
<P>
Joao de Matos, chief of the general staff of Angolan army,
told the press after the meeting that the move taken by the
allied armies in the Congolese crisis is "positive" despite some
obstacles at the moment.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the allied troops have made "remarkable
achievements" in the first stage of action, and the victory will
surely belong to them in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
Vitalis Zvinavashe, a Zimbabwean general and commander of the
allied armies, noted that they have controlled the entire
situation although tension remains in certain areas in the east
of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The meeting began here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On August 2, soldiers of the ethnic Tutsi Banyamulunge
community started a rebellion against President Laurent Kabila in
the east of Congo (K). The fighting soon spread to the east and
southwest of the country.
</P>
<P>
Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia have sent troops to help the
Laurent Kabila's government stabilize the situation in the
southwest of the country. 
</P>
