<HEADLINE> Roundup: China Strains to Prevent Financial Risks (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Liu disclosed that the PBOC will introduce a new loan
classification system at the end of this year in line with
international practices.
</P>
<P>
The country also is expected to set up professional financial
assets-management companies to prevent various risks for financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Mi Jianguo, an economist from a research center under the State
Council, said that establishing a sound financial order is an
important part of China's financial reforms. "The current basic
strategy of guarding against financial risks is to avoid
non-performing loans," he said.
</P>
<P>
In late July, the State Council published a directive to deal
with illegal financial institutions and businesses, which was
warmly greeted by insiders.
</P>
<P>
At the national financial working conference held in November
of 1997, China decided to adopt measures to alleviate the negative
impact of the Asian financial turmoil and to guard against
financial risks.
</P>
<P>
And, in the first half of this year, China severely punished a
number of banks and securities firms for breaking regulations,
resulting in the withdrawal of a considerable amount of illegal
capital from the stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
Some experts believe that this move has largely cut down the
"bubbles" in the market, providing a better regulated and
healthier environment in which the market can develop.
</P>
<P>
The PBOC and the State Foreign Exchange Administration have
also started to tackle the issue of existing black markets. Liu
recently warned speculators not to bet against the yuan, "China is
a big player," he said with confidence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
