<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Muslim Population Triples in Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Muslim population in
northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region has tripled since
the autonomous region's founding 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that the Muslim population in this region,
which has the largest number of Hui people in China, has
risen from 580,000 in 1958 to 1.78 million this year.
</P>
<P>
The Muslims now account for 33.8 percent of the region's total
population.
</P>
<P>
Experts with the region's Health Bureau attribute this
population growth to economic development and the improvement of
health conditions.
</P>
<P>
They believe that the special population policy implemented in
the autonomous region also has helped increase the Muslim
population.
</P>
<P>
A Muslim couple there is allowed to have three children, while
a Han couple in a Chinese city is only allowed to have one child.
</P>
<P>
Before the founding of New China in 1949, the ratio of births
to deaths in Ningxia stood at 2 to 1.
</P>
<P>
In the past 40 years, the number of hospitals and clinics has
been tripled, and the death rate for pregnant women and new-born
babies has dropped from 15 per thousand and 200 per thousand, to
0.97 per thousand and 37.9 per thousand.
</P>
<P>
And over the past 40 years, the life expectancy for Muslims in
Ningxia has been extended from 35 years to 69.5 years at present.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 07:46 </DATE_TIME>
