<HEADLINE> Israeli Education Minister Tries to End Teachers' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 3 (Xinhua) -- As the teachers' unions
continued their strike on Thursday, Israeli Education Minister
Yitzhak Levy is expected to find a way out of the current impasse.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after negotiations between teachers' unions and
Finance Ministry broke down Wednesday night, Levy said that he
would go to Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to seek a way to
prevent pupils from being kept home.
</P>
<P>
Levy indicated that he would try to restart negotiations after
his meeting with Netanyahu, asking the teachers' representatives
not to leave Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Angry teachers' representatives blamed the Finance Ministry for
the breakdown of the talks, saying that their unions had shown
responsibility by compromising on many subjects in order to solve
the issue.
</P>
<P>
But a statement issued by the Finances Ministry said that the
Ministry had offered the teachers fair offers to maintain their
real wages, accusing the teachers' organizations of intending to
use pressure and extortion to increase their salaries beyond any
logic.
</P>
<P>
Finance Ministry officials said that the teachers wanted to
increase their salaries by 8 percent, while they agreed only to a
5 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
The teachers' unions launched the strike on Tuesday as the new
school year was scheduled to open, keeping 1.2 million students at
home. 
</P>
