<HEADLINE> Tibet Appeals to More Foreigners (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- With Tibet's opening-up wider to
the outside world, the mysterious highland autonomous region
southwest China is becoming more and more appealing to overseas
visitors.
</P>
<P>
Despite occasional complaints of its incomplete facilities and
services, many foreign visitors are attracted by its beautiful
landscape and unique ethnic features.
</P>
<P>
Guatemalan student Bayron Galindo and his American wife Kay
Reneolayo are now studying the Tibetan language in Lhasa-based
Tibet University.
</P>
<P>
"I hope to be a teacher of a kindergarten or an orphanage in
Lhasa after graduation, because I love children here very much,"
Galindo said.
</P>
<P>
Six years ago Galindo met some Tibetans in Beijing Foreign
Studies University and found that their customs and skin color
were very much like Guatemalans. From then on, he said, he
cherished the dream of visiting Tibet.
</P>
<P>
He made two visits to Tibet before making up his mind to study
there. In March, the couple became overseas students at Tibet
University.
</P>
<P>
Talking about Tibet, Galindo said that he was deeply impressed
by the distinctive ethnic and religious features during his first
visit. But the communication in the region was inconvenient and,
in Lhasa, there was very little grassland or trees.
</P>
<P>
He said the streets in Lhasa have been widened and the city has
a nicer appearance.
</P>
<P>
Johannes Balzer, a German, was one of the first group of
overseas students to attend Tibet University. As soon as he
graduated from the university in 1995, he set up a company in
Lhasa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
