<HEADLINE> No Survivors from SwissAir Plane Crash: Canadian Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A spokeswoman for Queen
Elizabeth hospital of Halifax denied that up to now there have
been any survivors from the crash of the SwissAir jet off the
coast of Nova Scotia, Canada, reports said early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"There has been no survivors to date," Chris Power, VC nursing
services at the Queen Elizabeth hospital of Halifax, near the
crash site, told a news briefing carried live on CBC Television.
</P>
<P>
The alert at the hospital has been called off and things have
returned to normal proceedings, Mrs. Power said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier another local TV station reported that there were some
survivors and that some victims have been rushed to local
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
The plane, which was carrying 215 passengers and 14 crew en
route from New York to Geneva, crashed seven miles off the
Canadian coast, south of Halifax.
</P>
<P>
Canadian ships and aircraft were searching the crash site,
where plane debris was scattered a couple of kilometers across.
</P>
<P>
Some bodies have been picked up from the sea, which was rough
and dark, said the CBC Television.
</P>
<P>
Search is continuing in the crash area, which is about seven
nautical miles off Peggy's Cove on Nova Scotia's South Shore,
early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The MD-11 jet declared an emergency at 10:30 p.m. local time
and attempted an emergency landing at Halifax airport.
</P>
<P>
The crew reported an engine fire and dumped tons of fuel. The
plane crashed moments later.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of ambulances and fire trucks were gathered along the
Canadian coastline. A Hercules aircraft and four military
helicopters were leading the search.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said they heard sputtering sounds before a thunderous
crash.
</P>
<P>
"It wasn't the smooth sound of an airplane," one witness was
quoted as saying. "I heard the crash and a clap of thunder shook
the house."
</P>
<P>
The weather was reported to be overcast, with a light sprinkle
of rain and calm seas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
