<HEADLINE> Zambia's Opposition UNIP Threatens to Boycott </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's United National
Independence Party (UNIP) has threatened to boycott the country's
forthcoming local elections to be held later this year if the
government manipulates the on-going voters' registration.
</P>
<P>
Bweendo Mulengela, secretary for publicity and information of
the country's largest opposition party, told a news briefing
Wednesday in Lusaka that if fraudulent registration practices and
their subsequent demands were not attended to before the polling
date, they would have no option but to boycott "a sham and
stage-managed election".
</P>
<P>
The Post, an independent newspaper, Thursday quoted Mulengela
as saying that there were reports of anomalies in some
registration centers in the capital city of Lusaka and other
districts.
</P>
<P>
His party had uncovered anomalies in the registration of
voters in which some UNIP members were denied chance to obtain
the national registration cards, a situation he said was aimed at
creating artificial apathy.
</P>
<P>
Mulengela elaborated how the UNIP cadres were denied voters'
cards and charged that they were being intimidated and
interrogated by registration officers, who were pretending to be
teachers as required.
</P>
<P>
He also condemned the government's move to sell registration
forms, saying the consequence of this move would make voting a
right to only those who had extra money to spare.
</P>
<P>
UNIP had written formally to both the country's Electoral
Commission and the Department of National Registration to express
its concern over the anomalies, according to Mulengula.
</P>
<P>
UNIP boycotted the 1996 general elections and burnt their
registration cards to protest against the disqualification of its
leader and former president Kenneth Kaunda to run for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
The former ruling party, however, decided last July to
participate in the forthcoming local government elections, the
date of which is to be announced by the head of state.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's registration of voters started on August 24 and runs
up to September 13. The Electoral Commission hoped to capture
3.7 million voters out of a total of 4.3 million eligible voters
this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the turnouts are disappointing since there is
countrywide apathy on the practice. Local reports said fewer
people have been registered in registration centers since the
exercis began. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
