<HEADLINE> NPC Chairman Meets Romanian Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of the
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee, met here
today with a Romanian military delegation led by Minister of State
Victor Babiuc, who also serves as minister of National Defense.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Romanian relations have developed smoothly and the
governments, parliaments and armies of the two countries are
increasing contacts day by day, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Li said he believes the visit of Babiuc would promote
friendship and cooperative ties between the two nations, and
especially the ties between the two armed forces.
</P>
<P>
On the domestic situation, Li said citizens and soldiers are
fighting against floods all over China and they later will face
the difficult tasks of resuming production and rebuilding homes,
which will be China's major post-flood tasks.
</P>
<P>
In general, China's economic situation is good, he said, but some
difficulties have appeared because of the Asian financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Chinese government is taking steps to
overcome the negative impact.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed the Romanian delegation on China's situation in
deepening reforms and strengthening the construction of a
democratic legal system.
</P>
<P>
Turning the topic to international affairs, Li said China is
pursuing an independent foreign policy of peace, and working to
promote the development of multi-polarization and the
establishment of a new order in the global politics and economy.
</P>
<P>
Babiuc praised China as an important role model in safeguarding
world peace, security and stability.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes that the traditional friendship between
Romania and China would continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
Babiuc also expressed sympathy of the Romanian people for flood
victims in China, and admiration to the Chinese People's
Liberation Army for its bravery in the battle against the floods.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
