<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Hold Judges Responsible for Illegal Trial Practices (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- China will enforce an internal
supervisory mechanism in its courts beginning today which will
hold courts of law and their staff members responsible for illegal
trial practices, Li Guoguang, vice-president of the Supreme
People's Court, said here today.
</P>
<P>
"This move is to promote clean and honest courthouses and
ensure justice is served," he said at a press conference on the
issuance of a "trial method on investigating and affixing
responsibilities for illegal trial practices by court staff."
</P>
<P>
Staff members, including judges, shall be deemed responsible
for intentionally breaking the law in court trials, or when
carrying out court verdicts, and responsible for unintentional
legal offenses which result in serious consequences, according to
the procedure.
</P>
<P>
The mechanism is based on a decade-old method called the
"wrongful verdict responsibility system" which exclusively
governed judges. The new system covers all court staff members,
including presidents of people's courts, chief judges and court
secretaries.
</P>
<P>
Illegal practices, as defined in the new method, cover the
application of both substantial and procedural laws, intentional
or unintentional violations of the law, and both ongoing and
past illegal activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Sets Aside Fund for Kenya's Nutrition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF)
has earmarked over 480 million Shillings (8.07 million U.S.
Dollars) to help Kenya improve public health and nutrition in the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF project has been designed to address the high
levels of preventable disease in women and children in the most
disadvantaged areas of this east African country, the Daily
Nation newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The program focuses on chronic malnutrition levels through
the community based approach, building and expanding on the
Bamako Initiative," UNICEF was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The program will improve access to quality services through
support and promotion of community nutrition and care. It will
also support the control of micro nutrient deficiencies, safe
motherhood and reproductive health issues, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The project will aim to reduce the incidence of vaccine
preventable diseases by 50 percent and sustain an expanded
program of immunization (EPI) coverage of 90 percent for infants.
It also aims to eradicate poliomyelitis and reduce child
mortality due to diarrhoeal diseases by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Adequate case management of malaria will be increased by 50
percent, while the Health Ministry's institutional services will
be strengthened from 33 percent to at least 90 percent in all the
districts in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF noted that health conditions all over the country
deteriorated significantly in late 1997 and the first quarter of
this year, due to the floods caused by El Nino.
</P>
<P>
This has resulted in an upsurge in communicable diseases such
as malaria and cholera, inaccessibility of health facilities,
displacement and severe damage to the infrastructure, the UNICEF
4ilented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
