<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Improves Students' Grades: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A survey conducted by AT&AMP;T
last month said the Internet "helps students get better grades."
</P>
<P>
More than half of the 2,416 American respondents to the survey,
whose results were released Wednesday, agreed that "the Internet
has become a necessary tool for success in school."
</P>
<P>
Almost 70 percent of the parents, students and teachers who
participated in the survey said they had seen students' grades
improve through the use of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
"The Internet is to school research in the '90s what the
calculator was to math in the '70s," said Dan Schulman, president
of AT&AMP;T World Net Service, which conducted the on-line survey, in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
"It's a tool that lets students learn more in less time. In
keeping with that belief, we're encouraging kids to use the
Internet in a variety of ways." AT&AMP;T has created several Web
programs to introduce children to the Internet and advise parents
on helping children use the Internet safely.
</P>
<P>
While the survey confirmed the Internet can be an educational
tool, other studies have revealed its "negative impact."
</P>
<P>
Researchers at Carnegie Mellon University, for example, found
that people who spend even just a few hours a week on-line
experience higher levels of depression and loneliness than they
would have if they used the computer network less frequently. The
results of their study, with AT&AMP;T as one of the sponsors, were
released last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six Arrested for Bribery in Railway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Six people have been arrested
for charges of bribery in the case of the Beijing Western Railway
Station, the Chinese capital's new rail gateway.
</P>
<P>
The six expected to be put on trial are manager Su Qingfu of
the Qingdao Power Station Valves Plant, Baoji Material Company's
deputy manager Zhang Yan, materials dealers Tong Yan and Zhao
Zhixiang, surveyor Li Chunbo, and Huabao Real Estate Company's
deputy manager Guo Xueliang.
</P>
<P>
Of the six defendants, one has been bailed out and is waiting
for trial.
</P>
<P>
To sell poor-quality valves to the railway project, Su Qingfu,
the main figure in the case, bought two cars and gave them to the
five other defendants in addition to 300,000 yuan (about 37,500
U.S. dollars) in cash, according to court sources.
</P>
<P>
Su also said he spent more than one million yuan to "entertain"
the five people. His bribery worked and he signed a contract to
sell 20 million yuan (about 2.4 million U.S. dollars) worth of the
famous Qingdao brand valves in the name of the Qingdao Power
Station Valve Plant.
</P>
<P>
But, only one-fourth of the valves were of the Qingdao brand,
and the other valves were a cheap assortment Su reportedly got
from other areas.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the station was commissioned in January of 1996,
almost all the valves began to break down. Paint peeling down from
walls and ceilings and leakage are common. Small fountains drown
the underground consignment warehouse's floor, and the roof of
the multifunction hall on the third floor of the waiting building
is almost completely separated from its walls.
</P>
<P>
The station's waiting building cannot pass the state acceptance
inspection.
</P>
<P>
All investigations about the case have been closed.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Western Railway Station cost the Beijing Municipal
Government five billion yuan (about 580 million U.S. dollars) and
took three years to build. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Detect Lead Content in South Pole Ice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
used an advanced technology to detect lead content in
nearly 100 samples collected from South Pole ice.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time China has obtained accurate data for
South Pole ice lead content, an important index of global
environmental pollution, said Ma Wanyun, an atomic sciences
researcher at Qinghua University in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Ma said the study shows that the lead content of ice and snow
in Antarctica is higher than was previously thought, and the
eastern region of Antarctica has more lead pollution than the
western region.
</P>
<P>
Lead in the ice sheets of the South Pole can indicate current
global air pollution and the influence of human activities at the
South Pole, said Ma.
</P>
<P>
"However, it is very difficult to accurately detect the lead
content there using traditional technology, because 1,000 tons of
ice only contain several milligrams of lead," said Ma.
</P>
<P>
Scientist at the Qinghua lab adapted a technology called
single-atom detection and control to design a laser-excited
fluorescence spectrometer, which can distinguish the weak
information sent out by a single atom despite background
interference.
</P>
<P>
"Another difficulty is to avoid contamination in the
experiment," said Ma. "It took us three years to complete
detection in nearly 100 samples."
</P>
<P>
In addition, single-atom detection technology can also be
used to explore large gold deposits several hundred
meters deep underground, according to Ma.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5-Year Plan for Industrial Zone Drafted in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is drafting a five-year
plan for the development of industrial zones to boost the
country's industrial production.
</P>
<P>
The plan was preliminarily coordinated here Wednesday by the
Myanmar Industrial Development Work Committee, chaired by Minister
of the Second Industry Major-General Hla Myint Swe, official
newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has set up 17 industrial zones across the country in an
effort to promote the development of the industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
These zones include those in Yangon, Mandalay, Bago, Hinthada,
Myaungmya, Myeik, Yenangyaung, Pyay, Mingyan and Meiktila.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the industrial zones is aimed at
manufacturing import substitute goods and promoting export,
ensuring regional development and creating more job opportunities
for local people, according to the country's Industrial
Development Committee, formed with a number of ministers in July
1995 to give greater impetus to the industrialization process.
</P>
<P>
In this respects, Myanmar has called for extensive
participation of the private sector which shared 72 percent of
the production value of the industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Myanmar has also induced foreign investments in
the infrastructural development of the zones with companies from
Japan, Singapore, Malaysia, and Thailand building up three zones
out of five in Yangon.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the country's industrial
sector grew by 5.3 percent in its output value in the 1997-98
fiscal year which ended in March, sharing 9.2 percent of the gross
domestic product (GDP) and standing as the second largest
contributor to the GDP after agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in the sector amounted to 1.43 billion U.S.
dollars in 113 projects at the end of the fiscal year, taking up
the second position after the oil and gas sectors out of a total
of nearly 7-billion-dollar foreign investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
