<HEADLINE> Cambodian CPP Leader Hun Sen Has Audience with King </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SIEM REAP, Cambodia, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Second
Prime Minister Hun Sen, accompanied by a senior Cambodian People's
Party delegation, had an audience with King Norodom Sihanouk
Thursday in Siem Reap to discuss ways to avoid a constitutional
crisis.
</P>
<P>
In the delegation were the party's Honorary Chairman Heng
Samrin, President Chea Sim and Treasurer Chea Soth.
</P>
<P>
The CPP won the most seats in the July 26 National Assembly
election, according to the final official results announced by the
National Election Committee (NEC) on Tuesday. But the party failed
to win two-thirds of the Assembly seats needed to form a new
government by itself.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen is hoping for a revision of the Constitution to allow
his CPP to form a government with a simple majority.
</P>
<P>
The two opposition parties, FUNCINPEC and the Sam Rainsy Party
(SRP), rejected the election results and refused to join a
government headed by Hun Sen, whom they accuse of staging a coup
d'etat to oust then First Prime Minister Prince Ranariddh last
year.
</P>
<P>
The King decided Wednesday to preside over a working session of
the three main political parties in Siem Reap in hope of resolving
a month-long constitutional crisis, which led to 12 days of
opposition-backed demonstrations in Phnom Penh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
