<HEADLINE> Survivors Reported from Swiss Plane Crash Off Canadian Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- There were some survivors from
the crash of the SwissAir jet off the coast of Nova Scotia,
Canada, a Canadian TV station reported early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Some victims of the crash have been rushed to local hospitals,
the CTV reported.
</P>
<P>
The plane, bound for Geneva from New York with 229 passengers
and crewmembers aboard, crashed seven miles off the Canadian coast,
south of Halifax.
</P>
<P>
Canadian ships and aircraft were searching the debris-strewn
crash site, according to David Backer, a volunteer searcher.
</P>
<P>
Early Thursday search was continuing in the crash area, which
is about seven nautical miles off Peggy's Cove on Nova Scotia's
South Shore.
</P>
<P>
The MD 11 jet declared an emergency at 10:30 p.m. local time
and attempted an emergency landing at Halifax airport.
</P>
<P>
The crew reported an engine fire and dumped tons of fuel. The
plane crashed moments later.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of ambulances and fire trucks were gathered along the
Canadian coastline. A Hercules aircraft and four military
helicopters were leading the search.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said they heard sputtering sounds before a thunderous
crash.
</P>
<P>
"It wasn't the smooth sound of an airplane," one witness was
quoted as saying. "I heard the crash and a clap of thunder shook
the house."
</P>
<P>
The weather was reported to be overcast, with a light sprinkle
of rain and calm seas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
