<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rain Causes Cancellation of Night Matches at U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Rain caused the
postponement of four singles matches tonight at the U.S. Open
tennis championships, including those of top seeds Pete Sampras
of the United States and defending champion Martina Hingis of
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Both will play Thursday afternoon. Sampras will continue his
quest for a record-tying 12th Grand Slam title when he battles
unseeded countryman Paul Goldstein. Hingis will take on unseeded
Croatian Iva Majoli, who defeated the Swiss sensation in last y
ear's French Open final.
</P>
<P>
Two singles matches were in progress when the rains came at
about 8 p.m. Officals waited almost 90 minutes before calling off
play for the evening.
</P>
<P>
Seventh seed Alex Corretja of Spain and Italy's Gianluca Pozzi
will resume their first-round match on Thursday, with Pozzi on
top 6-2, 3-6, 5-2.
</P>
<P>
In a suspended women's second round match, American Mary Joe
Fernandez took the first set 6-3 over Alexandra Fusai of France,
but trailed 2-3 in the second set.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Germany's Bernd Karbacher recorded the first major
upset of the tournament as he stunned mistake-prone fourth seed
Petr Korda of the Czech Republic 2-6, 6-3, 6-2, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
Among women, eighth seed and five-time champion Steffi Graf of
Germany stormed into the third round by annihilating countrywoman
Marlene Weingartner 6-0, 6-1 in only 41 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Korda, the reigning Australian Open champion, was plagued by
57 unforced errors and lost his serve seven times as he suffered
his fourth U.S. Open first round loss and 14th overall in the
Grand Slam, including this year's French Open. He knocked off
Sampras in the fourth round last year.
</P>
<P>
Graf never faced a break point and was helped by Weingartner's
27 unforced errors as she won her 16th consecutive U.S. Open
match and 29th in her last 30. She is making her U.S. Open
return after missing last year due to season-ending knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
"I haven't had that many matches like that for a while," Graf
said, "I don't feel great. It feels good if you play well, but if
you don't really get challenged, then it is not so satisfying."
</P>
<P>
Graf will face Croatian teenager Mirjana Lucic in the third
round. Lucic rallied past Japan's Naoko Sawamatsu 4-6, 6-1, 6-1
to reach the third round for the second straight year.
</P>
<P>
In other men's seeded play, second seed Marcelo Rios of
Chile,who has held two brief reigns this year as the world's top
player,got back on the winning track by disposing of Daniel Vacek
of the Czech Republic 6-4, 6-2, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Also 10th seed Spaniard Carlos Moya was leading 6-1, 7-6
(7-4),6-7 (3-7), 4-4 when Argentina's Mariano Puerta retired with
cramps in his right hip flexor. No. 11 Yevgeny Kafelnikov of
Russia stormed past Dutchman Dennis van Scheppingen 6-1, 6-2, 6-4
and No. 13 Tim Henman of Britain downed Australian Scott Draper
6-3, 7-6 (7-4), 7-6 (7-3).
</P>
<P>
Former finalist Michael Chang of the United States crushed
Isaeli qualifier Eyal Erlich 6-1, 6-3, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
For the women, third seed Jana Novotna of the Czech Republic
got past Frenchwoman Amelie Cocheteux 6-2, 7-6 (7-1); two-time
champion Monica Seles of the United States, the sixth seed,
dumped South Africa's Joannette Kruger 6-2, 6-3; and ninth seed
Irina Spirlea of Romania, a semi-finalist last year, downed
Germany's Miriam Schnitzer 6-3, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
In other seeded matches, No. 11 Patty Schnyder of
Switzerland,No. 14 Dominique van Roost of Belgium also sailed
into the next round. No. 16 Ai Sugiyama of Japan was leading
Spain's Gala Leon Garcia 3-2, but was forced to retire with a
left ankle sprain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
