<HEADLINE> Myanmar Deports Three More Foreign Correspondents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yangon, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Three more correspondents from
Canada, Japan and Australia have been deported by the Myanmar
authorities for allegedly declaring false status in their passport
and illegally gathering news.
</P>
<P>
Douglas J Earl, a Canadian reporter for the Thaya Thai
Advertising, Munesuke Yamamoto, a Japanese correspondent of the
Pacific Press Service, and Sophie Louise Barrm, a female
Australian freelance reporter, arrived in the capital of Yangon by
air on August 19, 6 and 14 with tourist visas, claiming themselves
as a company staff, a designer and a teacher respectively.
</P>
<P>
They were deported Tuesday evening after the authorities found
their false status declaration in their passport and illegally
gathering domestic news, the official newspaper New Light of
Myanmar reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The authorities seized from them documents, cassette tapes,
films and video tapes on internal political affairs of the
country.
</P>
<P>
In last month, the Myanmar authorities deported a total of 21
foreigners including three foreign correspondents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
