<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals Down in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals for the first
seven months of this year have reached 202,670, down 1.2 percent
compared with the same period last year, according to Ceylon
Tourist Board (CTB) Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The CTB indicates that tourist arrivals declined for the fifth
consecutive month, falling by 4.3 percent to over 29,500 persons
in July this year.
</P>
<P>
This follows a 3.2 percent and nine percent falls in June and
May respectively.
</P>
<P>
The main reasons of decline in the tourist arrivals may have
been partly deterred by the spate of Tamil rebel attacks in key
cities in Sri Lanka during late last year and early this year, the
CTB said.
</P>
<P>
The tourist industry, one of the top foreign exchange earners,
has been recognized by the government as an essential industry for
the economic and social development of the country.
</P>
<P>
A total of over 366,200 tourists visited Sri Lanka in 1997,
while 302,000 came to the country in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
