<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 06:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> General Strike Hits Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A nationwide general strike
began Thursday morning in Israel, hitting all public sectors of
the country.
</P>
<P>
Organized by Israel Histadrut (National Trade Union), about
30,000 public sector workers joined the strike.
</P>
<P>
The strike was caused by the unsettled wage conflict between
the Histadrut and the government. The Histadrut is asking for an 8
percent wage increase for public sector workers, but the Finance
Ministry only agreed to a 0.75 percent wage increase, which the
ministry said is in addition to the recent cost of living increase
of 0.5 percent and other salary increases, such as seniority
increments.
</P>
<P>
Following discussions on this issue during the last several
days, Histadrut Chairman Amir Peretz and Finance Minister Yaakov
Neeman negotiated Wednesday midnight in a last-ditch attempt to
prevent the strike, but failed.
</P>
<P>
After midnight, Peretz suggested a compromise proposal, asking
only for forming a framework of wage increases and details to be
discussed later, but no agreement was reached with the Finance
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's strike closed down government offices, post offices,
local authorities, regional councils, transportation services,
hospitals, national insurance institutions, port and railway
authorities, telephone and electric corporations and national TV
and radio stations.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry so far stood firm on its position against
any wage increase, saying the government can not afford it. It
said even 1 percent wage increase would need 2 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the Histadrut said the strike is of indefinite duration.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry said the strike would cause great damage
to the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
During the last several days, Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu tried his best to help reach an agreement, but also
failed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
