<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka eager to get Food aid for Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
requested donors to expedite shipment of foodgrain for flood
victims in the wake of the severe flood, The Daily Star newspaper
reported Thursday, quoting official sources.
</P>
<P>
The country's food aid requirement has been estimated to be
around 1.38 million tons in the current fiscal year, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The government's eagerness to get the food aid shipment early
has been already conveyed to donors through a representative of
the United Nations agencies in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
Of the total of about 880 million U.S. dollar-aid requirement,
250 million dollars are required as food aid, according to an
official of the Economic Relations Division (ERD) under the
Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
The World Food Program had already sent messages to its
headquarters seeking early shipment of food aid, the Food Ministry
and the ERD said.
</P>
<P>
Australia has confirmed its readiness to provide 86,000 tons of
wheat this month, a month earlier than scheduled.
</P>
<P>
It would take a few more days for the country's development
partners to come up with specific aid offers, a Food Ministry
official said. "We have urged donors to expedite already committed
aid."
</P>
<P>
The already-committed foodgrain aid includes 140,000, 81,000
and 86,000 tons of wheat from United States, the European Union
and Australia respectively.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, import of foodgrains by traders is likely to
supplement the government drive to meet the food shortage due to
severe floods, officially estimated to be 830,000 tons, the
official said, adding that various other assessments put the
shortfall at two to four million tons during the current fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
Crop loss caused by the nearly two-month-long floods might
stand at three million tons since 60 percent of rice crop had been
seriously affected, an expert said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
