<HEADLINE> SwissAir Plane Crashes Off Nova Scotia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A SwissAir jet carrying 229
passengers and crew members crashed off the coast of Nova Scotia,
Canada, Wednesday night, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Canadian ships and aircraft were searching an area about seven
nautical miles off Peggy's Cove on Nova Scotia's South Shore for
possible survivors early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The MD 11 jet, en route from New York to Geneva, declared an
emergency at 10:30 p.m. local time and attempted an emergency
landing at Halifax airport. But it disappeared moments later.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of ambulances and fire trucks were gathered along the
Canadian coastline. A Hercules aircraft and four military
helicopters were leading the search.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said they heard sputtering sounds before a thunderous
crash.
</P>
<P>
"It wasn't the smooth sound of an airplane," one witness was
quoted as saying. "I heard the crash and a clap of thunder shook
the house."
</P>
<P>
The weather was reported to be overcast, with a light sprinkle
of rain and calm seas. 
</P>
