<HEADLINE> Foreign Aid for Bangladeshi Flood Victims Reaches 84 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh, which is
experiencing an serious flood, has so far received pledges of
about 82 million U.S. dollars in cash and kind from donor
countries and international agencies, press reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Apart from food assistance, the relief goods committed by the
Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs of the United
Nations has so far exceeded 22 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
At least 272,000 tons of foodgrains worth 58 million dollars
have been pledged by Australia, France and the United States.
China, India, Italy, Iceland and South Korea also announced
assistance.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait is the top cash contributor with two million dollars,
followed by the United Nations agencies which jointly announced to
contribute 1.16 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh till now has asked for about 880 million dollars of
assistance in cash and kind, including 112 million dollars in
immediate relief, 461 million dollars for rehabilitation, 1.3
million tons of foodgrains worth 242.5 million dollars and 57,000
tons of corrugated-iron sheets valued at 64 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi missions abroad have been making all efforts to
mobilize relief assistance for the flood victims as well as aid
for the post-flood rehabilitation program.
</P>
<P>
Since early July when the monsoon season began in the country,
45 of its 64 districts have been hit by flood, with more than 20.7
million people affected and the death toll rising to 451, showed
the latest figures issued by the Control Room of the Relief and
Disaster Management Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
