<HEADLINE> Seven-Year Plan Worked Out to Develop Thai Pineapple </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A seven-year, 9.7-billion-baht
(242.5-million-U.S. dollar) plan has been worked out to solve the
problems of Thailand's pineapple industry, the Bangkok Post
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The plan would maintain Thailand as the world's largest
exporter of canned pineapple and canned juice, the newspaper said,
quoting Agriculture Minister Pongpol Adireksarn.
</P>
<P>
Running from next year to 2005, the plan would overcome the
annual problem of an oversupply or scarcity of the fruit, which
caused problems for canneries planning their production, the
minister said during a committee on national pineapple development
policy Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This year, supply is far below demand because of drought, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Pineapple growers and canneries both experienced cost
fluctuation every year.
</P>
<P>
Pongpol said he had asked planners to draw up a proposal to be
put to the government.
</P>
<P>
Of the 9.7 billion baht, five billion baht (125 million
dollars) will be earmarked for growers, 2.5 billion baht (62.5
million dollars) for canneries and the rest for maintaining buffer
stocks that would be used to stabilize the pineapple price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
