<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Release Three Iranian Drivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A joint Pakistani and
Iranian delegation flew to Afghanistan Thursday to receive three
Iranian drivers freed by the Islamic Taliban militia, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
The delegation led by Ayaz Wazir, Director of Afghan Affairs in
Pakistani Foreign Office and Abdullahi, a senior Iranian diplomat
in Pakistan, has gone to Kandahar, Taliban's southern stronghold,
on a special plane Thursday morning and it will come back in the
afternoon, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Taliban's Supreme leader Mohammad Omar announced Wednesday that
"as a good-will gesture", the militia would release three out of
30 Iranian drivers they arrested last month when they overran
Mazar-e-Sharif, headquarters of the rival northern alliance.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban claimed that these Iranian drivers were sending
weapons to the pro-Iranian northern alliance and Iranian
government said they were carrying humanitarian aids to northern
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Iranian government claimed that its 11 diplomats
in the Mazar-e-Sharif, around 300 km north of Kabul, have also
been kidnapped by the Taliban. But the accusation was denied by
the Taliban authorities. 
</P>
