<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Projected GDP Growth Over 5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's economic growth in
terms of Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is expected to be in the
range of 5 to 5.5 percent this year, according to Central Bank
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Bank sources said the projection was slightly lower than
the 5.8 percent achieved during the first quarter of 1998 while
the original target for 1998 was 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The economy had performed satisfactorily up to the first half
of 1998 but external factors such as the recession in Asia and
the Russian crisis were causing difficulties, the sources noted.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, locally, the drop in rubber and coconut output as
well as low growth in some industrial exports had an impact of
slightly lower GDP projection.
</P>
<P>
the sources expressed confidence that interest rates would
stabilize between 12 and 14 percent though it was under some
pressure a few months back.
</P>
<P>
Despite the crisis in South East Asia and its effect on the
world economy, Sri Lanka's exports had succeeded in maintaining an
8 percent growth from a high base in 1997 when exports went up by
13.3 percent. Imports during the first half of 1998 had increased
by 1 percent from 1997. 
</P>
