<HEADLINE> Central Bank Governor Wants Secret Fund to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Central Bank
Governor Chatumongol Sonakul has voiced opposition to the move to
use the 373.8 million U.S. dollar secret fund deposited at the
U.S. Federal Reserve Bank on government spending.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's Nation newspaper quoted the governor as saying the
fund should remain as part of the country's reserves.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Finance Ministry recently stumbled across the fund
under a Thai government account which had been used by the Thai
military to receive U.S. military aid and transfer money for arms
purchase for 16 years.
</P>
<P>
The existence of the account had been known to few outside the
Defense Ministry until U.S. government officials recently
mentioned it as a possible source of downpayment for Thailand's
planned acquisition of F-18 fighter jets, which was later
scrapped.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol said he had instructed the Central Bank to keep the
fund at the U.S. Federal Reserve Bank as part of Thailand's
reserves.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Bhichai Rattakul earlier said he had
asked the Finance Ministry to find a way to use the money as the
government had a shortfall in its revenue collection as a result
of the economic malaise. So far there has been no instruction from
the Finance Ministry to withdraw the money.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol said: "The funds are gaining attention because the
country has faced tight liquidity. The Finance Ministry's stand in
keeping the funds as reserves has helped boost the country's
coffers."
</P>
<P>
He said the Central Bank acknowledged the fund's existence and
had always submitted a monthly statement on the fund to the
Comptroller-General's Department.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Director of the Office of the Auditor-General
Noppado Nimsomboon said the office is seeking to examine the
military's "secret funds" for the past 10 years and check the
income of army-owned television channels 5 and 7 and its more than
200 radio stations countrywide.
</P>
<P>
He said there has been criticism over the misuse of secret
funds and the public demands transparency in spending by all
government agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
