<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economy Grows Despite Negative Impact, Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- China can achieve its
projected economic growth despite the further deterioration of the
Asian financial crisis, a visiting senior Chinese official said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Liu Hong, director-general of China's State Statistical Bureau,
told a press conference that the complex environment in
international economy has had negative impacts on China's foreign
trade, foreign investment and economic development in general.
However, the government policies have enabled China to get along
well with the situation.
</P>
<P>
The policies, announced early this year, are designed to expand
domestic demand and reinforce infrastructure development to offset
the possible drop in export resulted from a strong currency in the
waves of devaluation in other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
China has vowed not to devaluate Renminbi to head off a new
round of devaluation. However, it is predicted that the decrease
in its exports could be hardly avoided.
</P>
<P>
"China's gross domestic product for the first six months of the
year was 3,473.1 billion yuan, representing a relatively high
growth of 7 percent over the same period of 1997 at comparable
prices. This is no easy achievement," said Liu, who has been a
professor of macroeconomic analysis since 1988.
</P>
<P>
The 7 percent growth rate is short of the 8 percent target for
this year. "We are hopeful that we can achieve the goal," Liu
said.
</P>
<P>
"In the remaining months of this year, so long as we succeed in
implementing the policies and measures of the government to
promote domestic demand and turn the unfavorable factors into
favorable ones by boosting the reconstruction in disaster-hit
areas, our overall economic development will accelerate," the
official added.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that major problems still exist in the economic
development including difficulties facing some enterprises in
production and management, the irrational economic structure and
the deterioration in the efficiency of enterprises.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that there are also many favorable factors,
including the encouraging situation in energy, raw materials,
transportation and communications, the low price level and the
great financing potential.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen steady or even accelerated growth in such leading
indicators as investment in fixed assets, bank loans and
production of capital goods," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
By his account, the total investment in fixed assets from
January to July rose by 15.6 percent over the same period last
year, of which the growth in June as compared with June of 1997
was 16.3 percent, and that in July, 22.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The growth in investment, mainly in agriculture, transportation
and communications, has become the main stimulating factor for the
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
July also saw a significant pick up of the growth in money
supply. M2 rose by 15.5 percent as compared with the same period
of 1997, while M1 increased by 10.5 percent and M0 by 10 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
