<HEADLINE> Swissair Jetliner Crashes in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A Swissair jetliner with 227
people, including a crew of 14, on board crashed in the eastern
Canadian province of Nova Scotia Wednesday night, the Canadian
news media reported.
</P>
<P>
The jetliner, Swissair flight 111, was flying from New York to
Geneva, Switzerland. It crashed in the Atlantic Ocean off the
coast of Nova Scotia at 10:30 p.m. EDT (0230 GMT), media reports
quoted a Canadian rescue official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Canadian TV reports said that the plane was a DC-10 and was
preparing for a possible emergency landing at the time of the
crash.
</P>
<P>
The French news agency AFP said that the wreck of the plane has
been found several kilometers offshore.
</P>
<P>
There was no word on survivors.
</P>
<P>
The plane left New York's Kennedy Airport at 8:30 p.m. EDT
(0030 GMT)
</P>
<P>
The plane crashed about seven nautical miles off land.
</P>
<P>
A Hercules, two Labrador helicopters and several coast guard
vessels were on their way to the scene, and as many as 50
ambulances were en route to the area, according to reports.
</P>
</TEXT>
