<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism in Thailand May Be Affected by Economic Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's tourism industry
may become another victim of the recent global economic woes, the
Bangkok Post Thursday quoted Prime Minister's Office Minister
Jurin Laksanavisit as saying.
</P>
<P>
Economic problems in countries and territories like Malaysia,
Hong Kong and Russia will undoubtedly affect Thailand's tourism
industry, Jurin said.
</P>
<P>
However, Jurin, who is in charge of tourism affairs, said that
the Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT) will carry on its plan to
promote the two-year Amazing Thailand campaign in major markets.
</P>
<P>
The TAT plans to continue promotion in high-potential markets
including China, India, Japan, Malaysia and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is one of the few countries in the region to report an
increase in foreign tourist arrivals compared with last year. In
the first half of this year, foreign arrivals rose by 4.8 percent
to about 3.75 million, higher than the TAT targeted 4 percent
growth.
</P>
<P>
Foreign tourists spent 130 billion baht (3.25 billion U.S.
dollars) during the period, an increase of 17.6 percent over the
first half of last year.
</P>
<P>
However, new currency controls imposed by Kuala Lumpur,
including limits on how many ringgit Malaysians can take out of
the country, could hurt the tourism industry in southern border
provinces of Thailand, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
There is also concern about Russia, the fastest-growing new
sources of tourists to Thailand, he said. In the first half of
this year, the number of Russian tourists soared by 48.4 percent
to 30,314.
</P>
<P>
According to Jurin, the TAT is looking for new sources of
tourists.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand would do more to attract Vietnamese people,
who have settled overseas and were returning to Vietnam for family
visit or vacations, to stop over in Thailand for brief holiday.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Asian Games, to be held in Bangkok in December,
will help to attract 800,000 more tourists, many of whom might
stay on to celebrate the Christmas and New Year in Thailand, Jurin
said.
</P>
<P>
Given all the factors, Jurin said he was confident that the TAT
would reach its target for the year of 8.28 million tourists and
300 billion baht (7.5 billion dollars) in revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
