<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup:Thailand Reacts Strongly to Malaysian Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Prime Minister
Chuan Leekpai has voiced optimism over Malaysia's currency control
decision, but government officials and businessmen expressed fears
that the move might hamper border trade and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said on Wednesday that he believed Malaysia would succeed
in tackling its financial woes by its new measures to shore up
currency stability.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, in a last-ditch
effort to save the country's embattled economy, on Tuesday
announced that the government would ban trading of the ringgit
outside the country.
</P>
<P>
Chuan, however, said should Malaysia falter on its currency
control measures, Thailand, as its neighbor, might be adversely
affected.
</P>
<P>
Chuan has instructed the Prime Minister's Office Minister Jurin
Laksanavisit to closely monitor the impact of the Malaysian
decision on Thailand's tourism, according to Thursday's Nation
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister was also cautious about the possibility of
emulating the Malaysian measures on currency control, saying that
conditions in the two countries were different.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Malaysia has comfortable foreign exchange reserve
to back up as it concocted its remedies for the economic ailment.
Thailand is relying on loans from the International Monetary Fund
to shore up its reserves, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Malaysian move to impose foreign exchange
controls has prompted fears from Thai government officials and
businessmen over border trade with Malaysia and the adverse effect
on tourism in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The officials and businessmen said that since the introduction
of the Malaysian currency peg system, Thailand has already
experienced a sharp drop in Malaysian tourist arrivals and the
currency control would further inhibit cross-border trade.
</P>
<P>
Thailand will seek urgent talks with Malaysia to try to divert
the impact of the Malaysian decision on tourism and cross border
trade between the two countries, Foreign Ministry Spokesman Kobsak
Chutiku said.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand will ask whether any flexibility could be
exercised in implementing this decision which will take effect on
October 1.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's southern province, in particular Songkhla, benefit
most from tourism and cross-border trade with Malaysia. Some 80
percent of business in Songkhla depend on Malaysia. About one
million Malaysians visit Thailand each year.
</P>
<P>
The Thai-Malaysian border trade amounts to about 300 billion
baht (about 757 million U.S. dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the currency control measures, Malaysians would
find it difficult to bring ringgit out of the country and
therefore would be discouraged from spending outside.
</P>
<P>
Charn Leelaporn, chief adviser to Songkha Chamber of Commerce,
said he foresaw immediate repercussions for trade and tourism in
Southern Thailand.
</P>
<P>
He said the cross-border business transactions usually rely on
cash and cashier's cheques so the limit on Malaysian currency
movement will have an adverse impact on trade.
</P>
<P>
Businesses in the southern border provinces expect the black
market for foreign exchange to mushroom as businessmen on both
sides of the border try to bypass the artificial control of the
Malaysian currency, Charn added.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-five percent of the trade is cash transactions in baht
and ringgit. In the past, Thai traders were paid in ringgit
directly by their partners or received cash transfers through
banks.
</P>
<P>
"It was a convenient system which is no longer relevant,"
Charn said.
</P>
<P>
"The new Malaysian measures are obstructing the free flow of
border trade. What will happen instead is a cash-only non-banking
trade system," he said, "costs will rise and it will be harder to
monitor data and other information. Soon it will become a black
market transaction."
</P>
<P>
Baht was traded at 10.10 per ringgit (buy) and 10.25 per
ringgit (sell) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Somboon Ponglertnapakan, chairman of the Hat Yai-Songkhla
Hotels Association, said he was alarmed about the plunging hotel
occupancy rate owing to the drop in Malaysian tourists.
</P>
<P>
Somboon revealed that hotel revenues in the southern region
have already declined 30 percent so far this year and that the
cancellations by Malaysian tour groups had risen sharply even
before the currency control announcement.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian tourists would be further discouraged from visiting
southern Thailand, he predicted, saying the southern hotel
industry was hard-hit by the Malaysian economic malaise and that a
number of hotels might have to close if falling occupancy rates
continue.
</P>
<P>
In a longer term, the switch in the Malaysian currency regime
might trigger a fall in Thai exports, said Kumron Kumkaew, a
tourism official in the southern region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Opposition Calls For Talks With Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's main opposition
the United National Party (UNP) has called for talks with the
rebels of Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), according to
the local newspaper The Island Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Party spokesman Karunasena Kodituwakku told the Island that the
government should resume negotiations with the LTTE without delay,
and should not lay down any conditions except for agreeing on a
time frame to conclude negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He said all options available to resolve the North-East crisis
should be probed.
</P>
<P>
There was no need to call off the ongoing military operation in
the North and the East and elsewhere during the talks. Previous
cease-fires had been used by the LTTE to consolidate its position
and resume hostilities resulting in heavy losses among the
government forces, the spokesman pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Kodituwakku added his party did not support the involvement of
a negotiator. However the idea of a mutually acceptable
Facilitator was crucial in bringing the LTTE back to the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting for a separate Tamil state since
1983 and over 55,000 people have been reportedly killed in the
civil war.
</P>
<P>
The present government had held peace talks with the LTTE
during the period from October, 1994 to April, 1995. On April 19,
1995 when the LTTE attacked government troops in the east of the
country, signaling an end to peace talks with the government.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government had expressed willingness to reopen a
dialogue with LTTE, subject to conditions including a substantial
laying down of arms and an arrive at a settlement within a
stipulated time frame. 
</P>
</TEXT>
