<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Reaffirms Position on U.N. Security Council Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini Wednesday reaffirmed Italy's position that the U.N. Security
Council should include the addition of two rotating seats open to
all member states.
</P>
<P>
He said Italy will declare again its position at the
U.N. headquarters in New York during the General Assembly session
scheduled for September 9.
</P>
<P>
While most U.N. member states are in favor of improving
Security Council procedures, transparency and expansion are
recognized as one way to ensure this. But opinions have so far
differed over how it should be done.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this summer, Germany proposed making two industrialized
countries new permanent members of the council, while giving
developing countries nothing more than rotating seats.
</P>
<P>
But Italy is strongly against the German proposal because it
claims it would introduce a distinction between the northern and
southern hemispheres, recreating at the U.N. an inadmissible
dualism between rich and poor countries.
</P>
<P>
Dini said that Italy's involvement in the Security Council
reform has "prevented extremely prejudiced developments not only
in terms of our country but in terms of the effectiveness and
legitimacy of the council itself."
</P>
<P>
Germany and Japan both aspire to permanent seats, which are
currently limited to the United States, Britain, China, France and
Russia and carry a veto right.
</P>
<P>
Dini reconfirmed Italy's opposition to the entry of Germany and
Japan as permanent members of the council and said that a solution
which is truly representative of the new world should be sought.
</P>
<P>
"We must reaffirm our point of view also in light of new facts,
such as the risk of a renewed nuclear arms race, the development
of other countries and continents, and the outlook for Germany --
the heart of Europe -- itself." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Oil Refineries Cut Production Due to Demand Slump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Six oil refineries of Thailand
cut their production by 7 percent in July from the previous month,
and further cutbacks are expected for the rest of the year as the
domestic demand is shrinking.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post reported Thursday that the July cutback of
53,600 barrels was spurred by a 10 percent drop in local oil
product demand.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, exporting surplus output has grown more difficult
due to a market glut.
</P>
<P>
World oil product prices have plummeted to the lowest level in
a decade, the newspaper said, quoting Metta Banthurngsuk, deputy
secretary-general of the National Energy Policy Office (Nepo).
</P>
<P>
The most noteworthy slump in Thailand is demand for diesel oil,
which contracted by 17.4 percent in the first half of this year to
271,750 barrels per day, figures from the Petroleum Authority of
Thailand (PTT) showed.
</P>
<P>
Consumption is likely to drop further through the rest of the
year, and no one can predict when the contraction will end, Metta
said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, refineries have been forced to reduce production
as most are unable to export excess supplies. They also face
foreign-exchange losses as most are funded by offshore loans,
Metta said.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Commercial Registration reported that total
production of all six refineries in July was 709,800 barrels a
day, compared with 763,400 barrels a month ago.
</P>
<P>
The combined production capacity of the six refineries is
825,000 barrels a day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
