<HEADLINE> Colombia Devalues National Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The central bank of
Colombia announced Wednesday it was devaluing the national
currency by nine percent against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's decision was made after the peso came under
increasing pressure, closing at 1,443 to the dollar Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian government had spent 210 million dollars since
last Friday in foreign exchange markets trying to prop up the peso.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Juan Camilo Restrepo said Wednesday that the
currency was devalued because of "the recent evolution of
international financial markets". He said the government would not
allow the peso to depreciate more than 23 percent by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
He also announced measures to pare the burgeoning budget
deficit, including strengthening tax collections and reworking the
government pension system.
</P>
<P>
Global markets have been hit by the economic troubles of Asian
nations and the more recent travails of the Russian
economy. Investors fearful the contagion will spread to other
developing countries have pulled out of financial markets in Latin
America, battering stocks and currencies in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
