<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Calls for More Support for Its Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Italy needs a reformed foreign
ministry with increased resources to better support its evolving
role in the world, Italy's prime minister and foreign minister
agreed on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a keynote speech at the close of an Italian ambassadors
conference, Prime Minister Romano Prodi promised to boost funds
for the ministry, saying "money invested in this direction pays
immediate dividends".
</P>
<P>
In an earlier speech, Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini urged the
government to raise his ministry's share of the state budget to at
least 0.4 percent, the average in other developed countries, from
the present 0.28 percent.
</P>
<P>
Dini also promised that the planned reform of the foreign
ministry would be implemented as soon as possible, ushering in a
phase of "greater initiative, responsibility and flexibility" and
of constant dialogue between Rome and its embassies abroad.
</P>
<P>
The conference, during which ambassadors discussed Italy's
foreign policy and how to further its aims, also served as a
platform for Prodi to outline "the three pillars" of that policy.
</P>
<P>
The three pillars were: an ever greater involvement in the
European Union; a close but free relationship with the United
States; and a strategic involvement in the Mediterranean and the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
On the first of the three, Prodi reaffirmed Italy's support for
the enlargement of the EU and for institutional reforms, including
an overhaul of the Common Agriculture Policy, which Prodi said
would mean sacrifices for Italy.
</P>
<P>
As for Italy's Mediterranean and Middle East policy, Prodi said
it was where the nation had shown "originality" in its foreign
policy by pursuing dialogue with Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said the policy, while sometimes different from that of
the U.S., had never been facile or polemical and had been
developed "honestly and without any craftiness".
</P>
<P>
When talking about the success of the Italy-led mission in
Albania, Prodi said it had lent Italy much credibility. "In the
Mediterranean and the Balkans, we are now considered a strong part
of Europe," Prodi said.
</P>
<P>
Italy's position on the economic crisis in Russia was also
touched on by Dini in his closing speech.
</P>
<P>
"The clear message, which also comes from other countries, is
in the invitation to Russia not to turn back. Confidence in Russia
will depend on its timely and clear decisions on continuing its
policy of reforms and cooperation with the West," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is also the condition for every form of support,
including financial aid," Dini added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
