<HEADLINE> "El Nino," Financial Crisis Blamed for Drop in Peru's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian exports dropped by 26.2
percent during the first seven months of 1998 because of the
weather phenomenon "El Nino" and the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
The value of exports reached 2.984 billion U.S. dollars from
January to July in 1998, compared with 4.044 billion dollars in the
same period in 1997, the Customs Tariffs Department said.
</P>
<P>
The fishery sector was the most affected by "El Nino," with
exports totaling 167 million dollars, 79 percent less than in the
same period of 1997, while mining exports were 1.793 billion
dollars, dropping by 14.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the tariff department, the Asian crisis
contributed to the reduction in prices of mining goods, including
copper, iron, lead and tin exports.
</P>
<P>
However, the sale of gold in the international market has grown
by 13 percent, totaling 321 million dollars from January to July
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the department, the sales of non-traditional
products rose by 2.3 percent in the period. The items with the
greatest success were mechanic-metal and craft goods.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Study Center of the Association of Exporters said
that the trade deficit reached 2.108 billion dollars from January
to July of 1998, 179 percent more than the same period in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
