<HEADLINE> Ningxia Hui Region to Invest in Irrigation Network Improvements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Ningxia Hui Autonomous
Region plans to invest 2.17 billion yuan (about 261.56 million
U.S. dollars) on a gigantic water irrigation improvement project
carrying over into the next century.
</P>
<P>
The project, already ratified by central government
authorities, is designed to expand the areas irrigated by the
Yellow River to some 666,600 hectares from the present 423,300
hectares.
</P>
<P>
An arid inland region in northwest China, Ningxia Hui from
ancient times has relied on diverting the Yellow River, which runs
through it for 397 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Successful water diversion programs have already helped turn
Ningxia into one of China's 12 leading grain-producing areas.
</P>
<P>
The ambitious project, expected to be completed in 5-to-10
years, calls for the building, expanding and transforming of 412
pumping stations and water gates, and the construction of 550
kilometers of irrigation ditches.
</P>
<P>
The project is also expected to help resettle 300,000 people
from Ningxia's poor mountainous areas, and to improve the ecology
in the Yellow River irrigated areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Clinton in Waiting Game with Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
leaves here Thursday in the middle of a waiting game with Russia.
</P>
<P>
As the Russians grapple with a financial crisis and political
chaos, Clinton sets the ground rules of the game: the United
States will only throw in more financial and economic assistance
when it is sure that Russia is sticking to its course of economic
reforms and democratization championed by the West.
</P>
<P>
"America and the international community are, I am convinced,
ready to offer further assistance if Russia stays with the path of
reform," Clinton told a press conference Wednesday at the end of
his summit meeting with Russian leader Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Until then, the Russians will have to wait.
</P>
<P>
As the two presidents talked, Russia's national currency,
dropped over 15 percent against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Late Wednesday, Russia's central bank, which has been forced
to let the ruble freefall, set Thursday's official exchange rate
at 12.8198 to the dollar, a drop of 17.8 percent in a single day.
</P>
<P>
Prices soared. In Moscow's neighborhood grocery stores, some
goods, such as flour, sugar, detergents and toilet paper, are
vanishing from the shelves.
</P>
<P>
Although few people expect the Russian consumer market to
return to the old days of empty shelves and long queues, residents
are hoarding things so as to lessen their vulnerability to a weak
ruble and price hikes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russia is without a fully functioning government to
tackle the dire economic situation.
</P>
<P>
Viktor Chernomyrdin, Yeltsin's nominee for prime minister, was
rejected overwhelmingly by the State Duma, or lower house of
parliament, last Monday.
</P>
<P>
And his chances of succeeding in the second ballot on Friday
are slim.
</P>
<P>
The Duma on Wednesday passed a resolution asking Chernomyrdin
to spare deputies the trouble by simply rejecting the post.
</P>
<P>
"Your voluntary rejection of the position of prime minister
could significantly reduce the tension and lead to a search for a
compromise," the Duma told Chernomyrdin, who was called back to
his old job after five months in political wilderness.
</P>
<P>
Under the Russian constitution, if the nomination is blocked
three times, the president has to select a new candidate or
dissolve the State Duma, which would plunge Russia into further
political upheaval and economic hardship.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, however, seems to have no intention of producing a new
nominee.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he was prepared to dismiss the
opposition-dominated Duma if it refused to confirm Chernomyrdin,
Yeltsin simply ducked the question.
</P>
<P>
"Well, I must say, we will witness quite a few events for us to
be able to achieve all those results. That's all."
</P>
<P>
Clinton, for his part, was trying to help Yeltsin from the
sidelines.
</P>
<P>
When meeting leaders from Russia's various political factions
Wednesday at Spaso House, the U.S. ambassador's residence, he
urged them to "bridge their differences to agree on ... a program
to stabilize the current situation."
</P>
<P>
"But if the basic framework is not in place, as a friend I say
I do not believe that you can defy the rules of the road in
today's global economy anymore than I could defy the laws of
gravity by stepping off the top floor of Spaso House," Clinton
warned.
</P>
<P>
But before the haggling among the political forces dies down,
any reform program has little chance of being followed through
consistently in a volatile Russia, given the severity of the
economic mess.
</P>
<P>
After offering moral support and laying down the rules,
Washington has to go on waiting.
</P>
<P>
"The ball I think is very much in their court. We do not have
any new or additional aid or plan in our pocket," a senior White
House official said, summarizing the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0276 </DOCNO>
