<HEADLINE> Czech Republic Extends Education Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic plans to
spend an additional two billion korunas or 64.5 million
U.S. dollars on education this year, and another 7 billion korunas
or 225 million dollars in 1999, an official from the education
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
He said that by the year 2002 expenditures on public education
would rise to 6 percent of the country's gross domestic product
(GDP), catching up with the level of European countries.
</P>
<P>
Spending on education so far this year was 61.7 billion
korunas, or 1.98 billion dollars, or 4.2 percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
The expenditures have been cut repeatedly in the past. In 1994,
the amount was 5.4 percent of the GDP, 5.3 percent in 1995 and
1996, and 4.7 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
This situation has resulted in negative consequences. Many
school buildings have not been repaired for a long time,
educational equipment is in short supply and some schools have had
to close.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic is one of the central and eastern European
countries where spending on education accounts for only a small
percentage of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
Hungary tops the list of spending by committing 6.7 percent of
its GDP toward education, followed by Slovenia with 6.2 percent,
and Bulgaria ranks third with 5.8 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
