<HEADLINE> Water Control Workers Play Big Role in Fighting Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Water control workers with the
Yangtze River Water Conservation Committee have played a big role
in combating this year's major floods in many areas of Hubei,
Hunan, Jiangxi, Anhui and Jiangsu provinces.
</P>
<P>
According to today's "People's Daily," 3,600 workers of the
committee have worked in shifts to patrol and check the
6,300-kilometer main stream of the Yangtze around the clock since
the flood season began in late June.
</P>
<P>
They have been able to forecast flood crests three days in
advance, with an error rate of zero to 0.07 meters in predicting
water levels.
</P>
<P>
The high volume of information -- telegrams, short-term
rainfall forecasts, reports on water and rainfall, bulletins on
water situations on the Yangtze -- generated by the workers has
been used as an important reference for central flood control
experts in working out detailed plans for combating flooding.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze River Flood Control Headquarters introduced a
24-hour duty system for workers' shifts since early April.
</P>
<P>
Based on information provided by flood control headquarters on
the possible development of flooding on the section of the Yangtze
in central China's Jingzhou Prefecture in mid-August, China did
not have to use the Jingjiang Flood Diversion Area when the river
rose to alarming levels.
</P>
<P>
This decision saved more 10 than billion yuan of property from
destruction and the cost of relocating more than 500,000 local
residents, according to the newspaper.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anger Sends Tyson to Therapist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Embattled Mike Tyson is
being counseled for anger, the banned heavyweight champion's
chief boxing adviser said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"He has been going for therapy," Shelly Finkel said. The
volatile ex-champion's latest incident came Monday after a
traffic accident in Gaithersburg, near Washington D.C., and
threatens to derail his boxing license application on September
19.
</P>
<P>
"This does not help Tyson," said Luther Mack of the Nevada
Athletic Commission, which already had requested Tyson's medical
records.
</P>
<P>
Tyson allegedly punched one man, who suffered a cut inside his
lip, and kicked another in the groin after the car that Tyson's
wife was driving was rear-ended, police spokesman Derek Baliles
said. No charges have been filed.
</P>
<P>
In 18 days, the Nevada athletic commission will decide the
fighter's immediate boxing fate, Commissioners say the issue of
self-control and Tyson's tempestuous nature, which suddenly
erupted when he twice bit Evander Holyfield in 1997, will be
paramount in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The commission already has asked Tyson's boxing adviser Finkel
for Tyson's medical records, which include a diagnosis of
"intermittent explosive disorder."
</P>
<P>
Tyson's latest brush with aggression could be used against him
during the hearing in Las Vegas. Tuesday, commission chairman
Elias Ghanem wondered:"Was it his temper? that provoked the
confrontation with the motorists."
</P>
<P>
In March a woman accused Tyson of throwing coffee in her face
at a Washington, D.C., restaurant, and witnesses said he loudly
cursed her.
</P>
<P>
In July, He blurted out an obscenity to his attorney during a
license hearing in New Jersey, stunning observers.
</P>
<P>
"I will tell you anything that has happened in his life since
June 28, 1997, is open to discussion," commissioner James Nave
said, "I certainly think the commission will look into Tyson's
self-control issues."
</P>
<P>
"I think the commission will do the right thing and ask the
hard questions," commissioner Luther Mack said, "You have to look
at the last year -- the restaurant incident, the New Jersey
incident and now this. We just hope Mr. Tyson comes before us
and tried to explain why these things occurred. No one hates
Mike." 
</P>
</TEXT>
