<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Zhu Rongji has called on governments in
flood-stricken areas to make every effort to help flood victims
survive the coming winter.
</P>
<P>
Zhu conducted a fact-finding tour in disaster areas in
northeast China from August 28-September 2. He said efforts must
concentrate on the construction of housing prior to the arrival of
winter.
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin said yesterday that the common task
ahead for China and the United States is to make continuous
efforts to assure healthy and stable Sino-U.S. relations into the
coming 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remark while meeting with a U.S.-China Society
delegation led by Dr. Henry Kissinger and Cyrus Vance, both former
U.S. secretaries of state.
</P>
<P>
-- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), met
yesterday with a Lions Clubs International (LCI) delegation led by
Kajit Habanananda, LCI's president.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Contacts between the Chinese and Israeli armies have been on
the rise as relations between the two countries grow, President
Jiang Zemin told visiting Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, also chairman of the Central Military Commission, said
he hopes to further promote friendly cooperative ties between the
two armies.
</P>
<P>
-- The seventh meeting of chairman and vice-chairmen of the
Ninth National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) yesterday adopted a seven-point
resolution to support reconstruction efforts in flood-ravaged
regions.
</P>
<P>
The resolution calls for a five percent cut in this year's
administrative expenditure for CPPCC National Committee
departments.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The black hand of corruption has rocked Beijing's Western
Railway Station. Six people responsible for the station's valve
breakdown problems will be put on trial for bribery, an official
of the Beijing Fengtai District Procuratorate said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- Contracts were signed yesterday allowing 20 commercial banks
and insurance companies to underwrite the State Development Bank's
5 billion yuan (US$602.41 million) debenture.
</P>
<P>
-- Two men conquered the Yangtze River by swimming 2,800
kilometers of it without life jackets.  
</P>
