<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Ethnic Region Benefits from New Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The rapidly developing
aviation industry in northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous
Region is improving transportation between the formerly remote
ethnic region and the country's inland and coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
"The distance between Ningxia and Zhejiang was shortened by
days," said Wang Liangqi, vice-president of the Ningxia-Wenzhou
Industrial and Commercial Association.
</P>
<P>
The opening of Yinchuan Hedong Airport to traffic in August
saved time for Wang on his return to east China's Zhejiang
Province, but for Ningxia it was a historical accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
Shen Yuankang, deputy director of the Civil Aviation
Administration of China (CAAC), said that operation of Hedong
Airport for a total investment of 538 million yuan is a symbol
that all of the capitals of China's provinces now have modern
airports.
</P>
<P>
As China's only Hui autonomous region, Ningxia has 1.7 million
Hui people. Until the operation of the new Yinchuan Hedong
Airport, the only airport in Ningxia had been used for 60 years
and was one of the shabbiest in China's provincial capitals.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that, in the first five months, the new airport
handled 64,000 passengers, 600 tons of freight, up 9.2 percent and
11.7 percent, respectively, over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2010, the airport should be able to handle 600,000
passengers and 1,500 tons of goods annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
