<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Falling Copper Prices Drive Chilean Mining Exports Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Chile's mining exports are
expected to drop to 7.1 billion U.S. dollars this year, a fall of
1.3 billion U.S. dollars from last year, according to the latest
appraisals of the National Mining Association (SONAMI).
</P>
<P>
The reason for the drop is blamed on the fall in copper prices.
</P>
<P>
The current annual price of copper is 76.8 U.S. dollars per
pound. But in August, the price fell to 73.5 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The situation has caused the Chilean mining sector to reduce
its exports by an average of 50 percent since 1997. This year,
exports have fallen by 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 20 months, there have been announcements of
temporary and permanent closures of more than 60 mines as well as
small and medium size plants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
