<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jews' Shanghai Story Revived on Screen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- "Shanghai's Ark," a
documentary released recently on Shanghai's Oriental TV, depicts
the odyssey of 25,000 Jewish refugees which ended in Shanghai 60
years ago.
</P>
<P>
This 50-minute film explores abundant historical anecdotes,
including interviews with 22 former Jewish refugees, among them
the former U.S. Minister of Finance, Michael Blumenthal, and the
first violin of the Vienna Philharmonic, Heinz Grunberg.
</P>
<P>
And it will be distributed internationally in both English and
Chinese languages.
</P>
<P>
As a renowned Chinese artist based in the United States,
director Yi-Fei Chen held his personal art exhibition eight years
ago in New York, where he came across a Jewish lady who said hello
to him in fluent Shanghai dialect.
</P>
<P>
She recalled her secure life in Shanghai during those turbulent
days in the 1930s and 1940s, which marked the start of Chen's
project to unveil on screen this little-known phase in war-time
history.
</P>
<P>
"I don't care if this movie makes a profit or not -- what
matters is that I want to emphasize the everlasting brotherhood of
Chinese and humankind," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
In World War II, in order to escape the Nazis, more than 20,000
Jewish refugees fled to Shanghai. They lived there in their own
community maintaining Jewish customs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
