<HEADLINE> Spain to Strengthen Reform to Reduce Crisis Effects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Spain's Second Deputy Prime
Minister and Minister of Economy Rodrigo Rato Figaredo said
Wednesday that Spain should strengthen reforms to enhance
competitiveness in order to cope with the effects of the economic
crises in Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Rato said at Santa Cruz De Tenerife in the Canary Islands that
the crisis would slow economic growth around the world. Spain
would have to adjust manufacturing costs and incomes and maintain
low inflation through control of the national deficit to increase
Spain's ability to compete.
</P>
<P>
Because of the growth in domestic demand and investment, the
Spanish government believed that it was not necessary to change
its 1998 and 1999 macroeconomic plans, Rato said.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1999 macroeconomic plan, economic growth will
be 3.9 percent and inflation rate will be 2.1 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
