<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Gov't Lifts Subsidies on Commodities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
lifted subsidies on wheat flour, sugar and soybeans,
simultaneously liberalizing their importation and scrapping
applicable import duties to reduce its burden in meeting people's
needs for the commodities.
</P>
<P>
The move is also meant to accelerate implementation of its
market-oriented economic policy, Minister of Industry and Trade
Rahardi Ramelan said on Wednesday when announcing the new policy.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no more subsidy and monopoly. We will leave it
to the market mechanism," the Jakarta Post daily Thursday quoted
the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Rahardi said other costs imposed for basic commodities will be
also lifted as a part of the government's efforts to curb
inflation. The inflation rate from January to August this year has
reached 69.12 percent, and it was predicted to hit 80 percent at
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
General importers were completely free to import the
commodities and they would be exempt from import duties, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government was confident the measures
would be able to stabilize prices at affordable levels for most
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
