<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Grants Individuals Right to Purchase Factory Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 3 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang
Province recently issued a policy permitting individuals to
purchase shares from state-owned companies owned by the provincial
government.
</P>
<P>
The move was part of Zhejiang's new initiative for the reform
of state firms.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 percent of a company's stocks should be held by
staffers, according to the new policy. Managers and senior
staffers are also encouraged to purchase more shares.
</P>
<P>
However, public utilities and government monopolies such as
power plants, banks, telecommunications departments and tobacco
companies are temporarily exempted from the new policy.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang Provincial Governor Chai Songyue acknowledged that
establishing an appropriate structure for shareholding is crucial
for restructuring state companies.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics through the end of 1997 show the provincial
government owned 907 companies with a total net capital of at 39
billion yuan (4.7 billion US dollars) and debt ratio of 68
percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
