<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Criminals Not Duly Punished in Nicaragua: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Most Nicaraguans believe that
criminals and other offenders are let off lightly by the justice
system, according to a survey by the consulting firm Gallup.
</P>
<P>
The survey, made from August 9 to 18, indicated that 68 percent
of respondents believed that criminals were treated very softly
and 26 percent thought otherwise.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, 33 percent of the 1,250 respondents
reckoned that the government was acting to eradicate crime, 30
percent thought there had been no change to eliminate crime and 31
percent believed that crime was on the rise.
</P>
<P>
In regard to drug-trafficking, 36 percent thought the
authorities were trying to fight it, 28 percent believed the
problem was getting worse and 28 percent thought the situation was
the same.
</P>
<P>
According to results of a separate study made by another
institution, Nicaraguans thought their main problem was the lack
of jobs.
</P>
<P>
Seven out of every 10 people interviewed considered that the
lack of employment should be the main concern of the government.
They also listed some of the factors affecting the Nicaraguan
society: the high cost of living, corruption, violence and crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
