<HEADLINE> Expedition to World's Highest River Canceled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Organizers from the Government
of the Tibet Autonomous Region announced today that bad weather
has forced the cancellation of an expedition to the Yarlung Zangbo
River, the highest river in the world.
</P>
<P>
The expedition was scheduled for this month, but heavy rains,
storms, landslides and flooding on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau have
caused extreme difficulties for the planned expedition, according
to the organizers.
</P>
<P>
"There are problems in logistics, support, rescue, equipment
and funding," they explained.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the safety of the scientists and reporters, the
government canceled the expedition, which featured plans of flying
across the world's biggest valley on the Yarlung Zangbo and
collecting data about its ecology, natural resources and disasters.
</P>
<P>
The Yarlung Zangbo Valley attracts adventurers from all over
the world. A number of teams have tried to raft the river, but all
failed.
</P>
<P>
Organizers said they might launch another expedition to the
river if conditions are better next year.
</P>
<P>
However, some members indicated that they would ignore the
government's decision and continue the expedition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
