<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Foreign Reserves Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's net foreign
exchange reserves stood at 13.5853 billion U.S. dollars on August
28, a drop by 612.4 million dollars from the fourth week of July
1998, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Muhammad Yunus Yosfiah said here Wednesday
evening that the gross foreign exchange reserves stood at 19.9709
billion, up by 443.5 million U.S. dollars from 19.5274 billion
dollars in the fourth week of July.
</P>
<P>
State revenues in the first three months of this year stood at
32.7554 trillion rupiah (about 3 billion U.S. dollars), accounting
for 12.4 percent of the target quoted in the state budget, said
the minister after a limited cabinet meeting on economy, finance
and industry.
</P>
<P>
Until August 15, state revenues reached 75.8816 trillion rupiah
(about 7 billion U.S. dollars), accounting for 88.8 percent of the
target, while routine and development spending amounted to 59.2436
trillion rupiah (about 5 billion U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
