<HEADLINE> Summer Record for Guangdong Grain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Despite alternating periods of
drought and flood, Guangdong's 1998 summer grain yield is setting
a record, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based English newspaper quoted an official from the
Provincial Bureau of Agriculture as saying that summer grain
yields in this southern Chinese province are more than 9.1 million
tons, up 52,800 tons compared with the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Guangdong has enjoyed five successive years
of increasing summer grain yields from 1994-98.
</P>
<P>
The official attributed Guangdong's sustained growth in grain
yield to an expansion of investments in agricultural production
and to improvements made in agricultural production since the
beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong grew grain on 1.5 million hectares this year, an
increase of 3,000 hectares compared with the previous year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of July, the province reported more than 2.2 million
hectares of sown croplands, up 15,600 hectares compared with
1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
