<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers VP Jerry West Agrees to 5-Year Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Los Angeles Lakers vice
president Jerry West, considering retirement just five months
ago,reportedly has agreed to terms on a new five-year contract
that will pay him 3.5 million U.S. dollars a season.
</P>
<P>
Citing the pressure of trying to build a championship team,
West spoke of taking some time off at a news conference on April
19. He was responding to numerous reports that he would retire
this summer due to his strained relationship with top executives
and coach.
</P>
<P>
Over the last two years, West added O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and
Robert Horry to a young strong team that included guards Eddie
Jones and Nick Van Exel, both of whom blossomed into All-Stars.
</P>
<P>
The Lakers won 61 games this season and were among the
favorites to represent the Western Conference in the NBA Finals,
but they were swept in the conference finals by the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
A new deal would also be instrumental in O'Neal and Bryant
remaining with the team. O'Neal can opt out of his seven-year
deal following next season and Bryant will be a free agent next
summer.
</P>
<P>
As a player, he was an All-Star in each of his 14 years. As a
coach, he had a 145-91 record from 1976-1979 and served as a
special consultant for three years before being elevated to
general manager in 1982.
</P>
<P>
West sitll ranks as the Lakers' all-time leading scorer with
25,192 points. He was elected into the Basketball Hall of Fame in
1979 and was named to the list of the NBA's 50 Greatest Players
in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
