<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Population Continues Rapid Growth: UN Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The chance of a world
population explosion could occur in the near future, the United
Nations warned in its annual world population report released on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The global population may reach 6 billion in mid-1999 and it is
expected to increase at more than 80 million a year in at least
two decades to come, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said the world population is characterized by the
simultaneous rapid growth of the young and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
"Past high fertility means more young people than ever before
-- over one billion between the ages of 15 and 24 -- are entering
their child-bearing years. At the same time the numbers and
proportion of people over 65 are increasing at an unprecedented
rate," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The number of people over the age of 65 is now 578 million
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The report said the growth of the younger population is fueling
the development potential of many countries, while the increase in
the number of elderly is pushing the age for retirement up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
