<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-ferrous Metal Sector Suffers Loss from Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The unprecedented floods that
swept the Yangtze River basin and Northeast China for over two
months have caused great losses in the non-ferrous metal sector,
although these losses have had little impact on the overall
production and markets up until now, according to today's "China
Daily."
</P>
<P>
Preliminary statistics from the State Bureau of Non-ferrous
Metals Industry predict that the total flood-imposed losses will
account for one percent of the sector's total output this year.
</P>
<P>
The floods have affected 31 companies, resulting in temporary
production shutdowns. Direct losses are nearly 60.24 million US
dollars and indirect damages are expected to be more that 24
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The floods aggravated the current poor business climate which
has affected non-ferrous metals companies since 1996.
</P>
<P>
Industrial experts said that the floods can also serve as an
opportunity to upgrade the outmoded technologies and equipments
used by these companies touched by the floods.
</P>
<P>
To promote capital flow into the industry, groups of large
enterprises will be established.
</P>
<P>
As an effective way to slash the production costs, the State
Bureau of the Non-ferrous Metals Industry intends to cut 15,000 to
20,000 employees by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
The task ahead is extremely difficult for the 285 enterprises
involved in the sector because they cannot offer any re-employment
capital since more than half are not registering any profits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
