<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museum Promotes Appreciation for Nature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Museum of Natural
History is now offering visitors a glimpse of a tropical rain
forest environment.
</P>
<P>
The museum, located in a northern temperate zone, recently
opened its highly popular tropical botanical garden.
</P>
<P>
One primary school student visited the exhibit in the
sweltering August heat and said he felt as if he were visiting a
real tropical rain forest.
</P>
<P>
The 6,000-sq.-m. garden, or the so-called "Green Home",
attracts over 5,000 people daily, with visitors pouring in even on
the hottest days.
</P>
<P>
The museum has installed hallway air conditioners for the
comfort of the many visitors.
</P>
<P>
"The color green symbolizes life, but random forestation has
substantially diminished the earth's green coverage, said Curator Li
Jianjun, adding the "exhibition exhorts people to protect plants
and cherish life."
</P>
<P>
The museum spent over 1.6 million yuan (about 200,000 US
dollars) for exhibits and multi-media equipments. Visitors have
the opportunity to stroll through a tropical forest featuring
scenery much like that found in Xishuangbanna in southwestern
China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
Numerous primary and secondary schools have contacted the
museum for information concerning, with students groups charged
less than half of the normal 15 yuan admission fee.
</P>
<P>
"We must assume responsibility for promoting environmental
protection," said Li.
</P>
<P>
He noted that museum organized very few plant exhibitions over
the past decade, with businessmen often renting exhibition halls
for furniture show and sales.
</P>
<P>
"Beijing people adore plants and animals. We realized that we
should take full advantage of our expertise by organizing
exhibitions," said Li.
</P>
<P>
"People throughout the world must care for the earth, and
museums must make their due contributions," said Li.
</P>
<P>
He said the Green Home Exhibition will be around for a long
time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
