<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young Italian Women Rank Third in Jobless Rating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Italian women were third in
the 1997 jobless rankings issued by the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the OECD, almost 40 percent of young Italian women
between the ages of 15 and 24 are out of work, a figure that is
only beaten by Spain and Greece. The proportion of women who stay
in school or a university was not reported.
</P>
<P>
While the trend in Spain has been improving for three years,
and in Greece it turned around in 1996, things have been getting
steadily worse for young female Italian job-seekers.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, only 35.4 percent of young women between 15 and 24
were out of work, but the figure rose to 39.9 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The comparable figures for young Italian males were 23.4
percent in 1990 and 28.7 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The OECD average was 11.2 percent in 1990 and 12.9 percent for
males, and 12.1 percent and 14 percent for females.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland, Italy's neighbor, has the lowest unemployment rate
for young females, just 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other countries with very low jobless rates for young women
were Japan with 6.3 percent, South Korea 6.6 percent, Mexico 8.4
percent and Germany 9.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Rules out Foreign Exchange Control Option </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
dismissed rumors on Wednesday that Indonesia would follow Malaysia
and impose foreign exchange controls.
</P>
<P>
"We will stick to the free foreign exchange system for the time
being, but we will continue to study new developments,"
Coordinating Minister for Economy, Finance and Industry Ginandjar
Kartasasmita said here Wednesday evening after a cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia on Tuesday imposed currency controls in attempts to
fend off speculators by setting a fixed exchange rate for the
ringgit by year-end and allowing the currency to be traded only
within the country.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian drastic policy has prompted speculation that
Indonesia will soon announce a similar measure, a dealer said. But
economists warned the government not to copy Malaysia's move as it
would only further damage investor confidence in the crisis
economy.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has been the hardest hit by the currency woes with
the rupiah losing almost 80 percent of its value against the U.S.
dollar at one stage.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia made world headlines early this year when it said it
was considering the adoption of a currency board system, in which
the rupiah is pegged at a fixed rate to the U.S. dollar. The
government, however, decided not to adopt the system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
