<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Portugal's Illiteracy Rate Highest in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Portugal's illiteracy rate is
the highest in Europe, with 13 percent of women and eight percent
of men being unable to read or write properly, said a report of
the United Nations released here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Spain follow with an illiteracy rate of five percent
of women and two percent of men.
</P>
<P>
However, illiteracy rates are much lower in eastern European
countries whose per capita incomes are comparatively low.
</P>
<P>
In Romania, only three percent of women and one percent of men
are illiterate, while in Poland, illiteracy has been eliminated,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Water-Absorbent Material Developed for Environmental Uses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A new water-absorbent polymer
has been developed by a group of scientists from Beijing
University for such environmental uses as planting trees in the
country's rapidly expanding desert land.
</P>
<P>
The new material -- a super high-speed, high-absorbent polymer
-- was developed by a research team headed by Professor Li Fumian
from the Chemistry Department at Beijing University. The material
passed a formal assessment for industrial production Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The material has proven able to absorb water 1,000 times its
own weight in less than 30 seconds and then slowly release the
water," said Zhang Zhongyue, a senior engineer with the Beijing
Academy of Chemical Industry.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Yiming, a research fellow from the Chinese
Academy of Agricultural Sciences, the new material's excellent
water absorption and preservation capabilities will allow it to be
effectively and widely used in a number of environmental fields
such as combating desertification, soil conservation, flood
control and afforestation.
</P>
<P>
"In deserts, the main problem for afforestation is that water
evaporates very rapidly," he said. "This material can help to
solve the problem and thus help to change deserts into oases."
</P>
<P>
The new material can also raise the survival rate of newly
planted trees from the current average level of around 30 percent
to more than 80 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
As one of the countries facing the world's most severe soil
erosion and desertification situation, China is now losing 2,460
square kilometers per year of its land area because of
desertification.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, 3.6 million square kilometers,
or 38 percent of the country's total land area, is undergoing soil
erosion and 27.3 percent of its total land area has become
desert. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agitators Present During May Riots, Admit Indonesian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian government
officials admitted that there were agitators present during the
May riots in Jakarta and other cities which left 1,200 people
dead, an investigating team member was quoted by national
newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Fact-Finding Team investigating the riots on
Wednesday questioned Armed Forces Intelligence Agency (BIA) chief
Maj. Gen. Zacky Anwar Makarim to collect more inputs which the
team needed before drawing its conclusions on the bloody riots.
</P>
<P>
Zacky was the fourth government official questioned by the
investigation team. Last week, the team questioned former Jakarta
military commander Maj. Gen. Sjafrie, Jakarta Governor Sutiyoso
and former city police chief Maj. Gen. Hamami Nata.
</P>
<P>
The government established the team in July which includes
representatives from the Armed Forces, government agencies, the
National Commission on Human Rights and non-governmental
organizations to investigate reports that the riots were
masterminded.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing is that all four officials admitted
that there were agitators present during the riots," Bambang W.
Soeharto, a member of the team, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Based on the information gathered from the four officials so
far, Bambang said the conclusion could be drawn that all four of
them were "quite aware of and alert to the happenings" on those
days.
</P>
<P>
"From the BIA chief we received the input that the ABRI (the
Armed Forces) was not involved in any action to orchestrate the
unrest, organize or incite the masses to commit destructive acts,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Zacky nevertheless admitted there were a number of agitators
behind the riots.
</P>
<P>
Bambang added that Zacky said he had done his utmost to monitor
rising tension in the country from as far back as April 9.
</P>
<P>
"The intelligence agency had detected signs (of trouble) and
warned all units to be on the alert back in April," Zacky was
quoted by Bambang as saying.
</P>
<P>
Zacky said that his organization predicted that "something"
would happen on May 20, the day Moslem leader Amien Rais planned
to stage a march involving one million people to demand former
president Soeharto's resignation. However, Amien canceled the
rally for fear of clashes between marchers and the security
forces.
</P>
<P>
When pressed further by the reporters as to why the military
were non-existent during the riots, despite Zacky claims that all
units had been placed on the alert, Bambang said: "Zacky revealed
that the troops were tired and depressed... they had been almost
constantly on the alert since the election (last year) and the
general session of the People's Consultative Assembly (in March)."
</P>
<P>
Bambang said the meetings so far held were not sufficient and
added that the team plans to question other officials to establish
if the riots were masterminded or not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0316 </DOCNO>
