<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fourth Seed Korda Beaten in U.S. Open First Round </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Fourth seed Petr Korda of
the Czech Republic was upset by Germany's Bernd Karbacher 1-3 in
the first round competition at the 14 million U.S. Open tennis
championships in New York today.
</P>
<P>
Karbacher recorded the first major upset when he stunned
mistake-prone Korda 2-6, 6-3, 6-2, 6-1. Korda the reigning
Australian Open champion who uspet Pete Sampras of the United
States in the fourth round last year, was plagued by 57 unforced
errors and lost his serve seven times as he suffered his fourth
U.S. Open first-round loss and 14th overall in a Grand Slam
including this year's French Open.
</P>
<P>
Eliminated in the first round of the U.S.Open for the first
time since 1993, Korda said that mental fatigue was the main
reason for his early departure.
</P>
<P>
"I had one bad game, and from that moment everything went
downhill," said Korda. "I'm a little bit tired because I really
depend on my family, and the last six months I saw them only four
months. It is too much for me and it really is probably one of
the keys why I am tired."
</P>
<P>
Currently ranked 155th in the world, the 30-year-old Karbacher
earned his first victory over Korda in three meetings. He
reached the U.S. Open quarter-finals in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Among the women's matches wound up today, eighth seed and
five-time champion Steffi Graf of Germany stormed into the third
round by beating countrywoman Marlene Weigartner 6-0, 6-1 in only
41 minutes.
</P>
<P>
In other men's seeded play, second seed Marcelo Rios of
Chile,who has held two brief reigns this year as the world's top
player,got back on the winning track by ousting Daniel Vacek of
the Czech Republic 6-4, 6-2, 6-3 in his first outing here.
</P>
<P>
No. 11 Yevgeny Kafelnikov of Russia downed Dutchman Dennis van
Scheppingen 6-1, 6-2, 6-4, while No. 13 Tim Henman of Britain
defeated Australian Scott Draper 6-3, 7-6 (7-4), 7-6 (7-3).
</P>
<P>
Former finalist Michael Chang of the United States, unseeded
this year after being seeded second last year, crushed Israeli
qualifier Eyal Erlich 6-1, 6-3, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
In the women's second round actions, third seed Jana Novotna
of the Czech Republic got past Frenchwoman Amelie Cocheteux 6-2,
7-6(7-1); Two-time champion Monica Seles of the United States
dumped South Africa's Joannette Kruger 6-2, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Sampras and Martina Hingis of Switzerland are battling in the
second round matches tonight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
