<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Call for New National Flag Raised in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Jenny Shipley is supporting a call for debate on a new national
flag, a Wellington-based newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion quoted Mrs. Shipley as saying Wednesday that New
Zealand should consider whether its flag reflects its confident,
modern identity as it heads into the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The basis of the current national flag of New Zealand is the
Union Jack in the upper left quarter, and on a blue ground to the
right the Southern Cross is represented by four five-pointed stars
with white borders.
</P>
<P>
Newly-appointed Minister of Cultural Affairs Marie Hasler, who
raised the call for a new New Zealand flag, said that the current
national flag "too much reflects our former colonial status.
Rather, it has become, over time, almost meaningless."
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Shipley said that she supports Hasler's call for debate on
the merits of New Zealand's flag. "The debate should be wider than
just the national flag," she added.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is a wonderful idea to look at the symbols of New
Zealand and ask if it is time to reflect on who we are as we turn
the corner into the next century," the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
A change might reflect New Zealand's increasing confidence in
its culturally rich, multi-ethnic identity, she added.
</P>
<P>
"For some years I have believed our flag no longer catches the
essence of contemporary New Zealand," the paper quoted Ms Hasler
as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, Ms Hasler favors the silver fern on a
black ground, but believed that New Zealanders should debate which
design its flag should bear.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
