<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Magazine Sales Reduced in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The recessionary economy of
New Zealand is taking its toll on magazine sales, with several
suffering falls in the first half of the year, according to
figures recently released by New Zealand's Audit Bureau of
Circulation.
</P>
<P>
The biggest selling women's magazine, Woman's Day, took a big
hit with sales dropping by more than 17,800 to 171,571 for the six
months to June 30 from 189,398 in the previous six months. But it
still held its number one position.
</P>
<P>
Over the same time, New Zealand Woman's Weekly, the second
top-seller, also suffered a fall of 3,333 to 127,373 from 130,706.
But New Idea gained ground, adding 3,748 sales to take its total
sales to 58,268 from 54,520.
</P>
<P>
Another to take a dip was the New Zealand Listener, with sales
at 90,967 for the first half of this year down more than 5,500
from 96,490 in the half-year to December 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Leading the paid-for monthly magazines is the Sky TV magazine,
SkyWatch, with 225,600 sales in the first half of this year, down
on the 283,000 recorded in the previous six months. Reader's
Digest, with 135,556 sales in the half-year, was down slightly on
the 136,966 in the previous six months.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Gardener dropped more than 6,500 sales to 70,550
from 77,077. North and South fell slightly to 35,707 from 36,350.
Auckland's Metro magazine dipped by 1,800 to 20,269.
</P>
<P>
Monthly paid-for magazines with rising sales included women's
magazine Next, with sales up nearly 2,000 to 59,369 for the
half-year, and NZ House and Garden, rising by 224 copies to
48,923. 
</P>
</TEXT>
