<HEADLINE> Adams: I Did not Intend to Hurt Hoddle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Tony Adams, who criticized
England manager Glenn Hoddle in his new book, said on Wednesday
that he did not mean to hurt him.
</P>
<P>
The Arsenal defender criticised Hoddle for making crucial
mistakes during the World Cup in the serialisation of his
forthcoming book "Addicted" in The Sun newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Adams, who will marshall England's defence in their European
championship qualifier against Sweden in Stockholm on
Saturday,said: "I did not want to hurt Glenn Hoddle because I've
got tremendous respect for him.
</P>
<P>
"Take the football away and he's still a great guy. Our
relationship is healthier than it's ever been at the moment."
</P>
<P>
Adams, sitting alongside Hoddle at a press conference near
their training base at Bisham Abbey, added: "The book was
something I needed to do to get things off my chest.
</P>
<P>
"There were also a lot of positives about Glenn Hoddle in the
book -- but people have jumped on the negatives."
</P>
<P>
Adams, the only player in the current squad who played in the
same England team as Hoddle in the 1980s, claims in his book that
Hoddle was wrong to pick Alan Shearer as captain ahead of him,
encouraged Paul Gascoigne to drink before his World Cup axing and
treated senior players like children.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Hoddle insisted his relationship with Adams had not
been damaged by the comments in his book.
</P>
<P>
"It is all about opinions and I have got no problem with
that," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There has never been a problem with me and Tony and as far as
I am concerned there never will be." 
</P>
</TEXT>
