<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Media Partners: No Loser in Super League (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Media Partners, the company
behind a proposed European Super League, said on Wednesday that
there would be no losers in his plan to revolutionise the sport
of soccer in the region.
</P>
<P>
Rodolfo Hecht, a 38-year-old Italian leading the Milan-based
company, spent the day in London giving details of how the new
league will not only satisfy the continent's big clubs but also
pour unprecedented riches into the game.
</P>
<P>
"There is absolutely nothing harmful for European football in
our proposal -- far from it," local reports quoted Hecht as
saying. "It is a proposal with no losers.
</P>
<P>
"The league is built on a merit concept with 100 percent
ownership in the hands of the clubs, on a similar model to the
English premier league.
</P>
<P>
"It is totally transparent and the benefits are so impressive
-- to all levels of the game -- that football could not be
insensitive to it."
</P>
<P>
Hecht said that competing Super League clubs would receive
about three times as much as they currently get from the
Champions' League and promised huge investment at grass roots
level.
</P>
<P>
After further consultations with the clubs this week, Media
Partners have come up with a revised plan for how the league
would work.
</P>
<P>
It would feature 18 "founder member" clubs, two more than
announced in the original plans.
</P>
<P>
They would be selected on their performance over 10 years and
would be guaranteed a place for three seasons. A further 18(also
up from 16) would be invited to play based on their performance
during the previous season.
</P>
<P>
The 36 teams would be divided into three groups of 12, each
club playing the others once. The top five in each group plus
the sixth placed team with the best record would advance to a
knockout last 16 and on to a one-off final.
</P>
<P>
A secondary competition, the Pro Cup, would involve 96 clubs
from all 51 UEFA countries in a knockout competition. Clubs would
qualify on the basis of domestic league and cup performances.
</P>
<P>
Sixty four clubs would play in an initial round with the 32
winners advancing to play a pre-selected 32 and then straight
knockout.
</P>
<P>
Hecht said the new competitions would be played in midweek to
complement, not replace, the current domestic ones.
</P>
<P>
"We want to keep alive the dream of clubs like Wimbledon,who
can not only dream of making it to the Super League but also of
winning it," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This plan makes the dream financially sustainable because the
money will go to all levels of the game and not just to the
already rich."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Media Partners: No Loser in Super League (2-last) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For that to happen the new league must have the approval of
world and European governing bodies FIFA and UEFA, a scenario
that looks unlikely at the moment.
</P>
<P>
"We want their approval and are seeking to get it," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have offered them (UEFA) a regulatory role and really do
not understand why they feel they have to own the competition,"he
added, before warning that if approval was not forthcoming then
he would be happy to follow the alternative route.
</P>
<P>
UEFA have already said they want no part of it and are
planning their own new competition, likely to be based on a
further expansion of the Champions' League.
</P>
<P>
FIFA has threatened to ban Super League clubs from playing in
domestic leagues and ban their players from representing their
countries but Hecht is confident such steps would be illegal
under European Community law.
</P>
<P>
He also said UEFA's current monopoly on selling TV rights
through its own marketing arm would be unlikely to stand up to EC
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
"Not a penny has been pledged nor have there been any
negotiations with anyone regarding TV rights.
</P>
<P>
"It would have been far easier for us to have sold everything
in advance to a multi-media giant -- and we had several
approaches -- but that would have delivered the future of the
game to them.
</P>
<P>
"Our plan keeps control with the clubs and the fans and we can
go to the EC and get the exemption we would need as a result of
those benefits."
</P>
<P>
Hecht said Media Partners were able to resist the pressure to
sell the product in advance because of a three billion
U.S.dollars guarantee given by merchant bankers JP Morgan.
</P>
<P>
"They obviously hope they will not have to spend that money
once we have sold the TV rights but it means we can be able to
present to concept to the clubs and offer them control."
</P>
<P>
Hecht, who pioneered digital TV pay-per-view coverage in
Italian soccer, said that that technology would play an important
part of the deal but promised that there would still be plenty to
see without payment.
</P>
<P>
"The semi-finals and final of the league and the entire Pro
Cup will be available free and there will be highlights of the
other games available 30 minutes after they finish," he said.
</P>
<P>
He is meeting the chairmen of the 20 English premier league
clubs on Thursday when he will outline the latest developments.
</P>
<P>
The plan is still for the new league to begin in the 2000/2001
season but Hecht promised there was still ample time for
changes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Province Plans Multi-Billion Yuan Water Conservancy Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, September 3 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province
plans to invest more than 6.4 billion yuan (773 million US
dollars) to construct several major water conservancy projects
over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Fujian, a province which features both coastal and mountainous
terrain, is exposed to floods, tidal waves and mudflows, Heavy
flooding since June this year had devastated many parts of the
province and local water conservancy projects have played a major
role in minimizing losses.
</P>
<P>
Provincial authorities plan to launch the new projects to
further enhance the province's flood control capabilities.
</P>
<P>
The list of projects includes the construction of levees
stretching 1,014 km along the banks of six major rivers. Said
project will be carried out at a cost of 3.6 billion yuan (435
million US dollars). Other projects include a 1,000-km sea wall
enforcement program expected to cost 690 million yuan, a 160
million yuan project to reinforce 220 flood gates and channels,
and 10 medium to large reservoirs which carry and estimated cost
of 1.77 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The massive program will also the establishment of a flood
control command system, a flood warning network, a multipurpose
river channel protection project and a project to strengthen
administrative management over water conservancy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
