<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide Internet Child Pornography Ring Uncovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States and 11
other countries have started a battle against child pornography
through Internet and on Wednesday arrested almost four dozens of
suspected members of a ring committing such crime worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The ring, Wonderland Club, was allegedly traded pictures of
children as young as 18 months old over the Internet. It has
exchanged thousands of pornographic images of children via
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
A database of more than 100,000 pornographic photos of children
were uncovered after five months of investigations by the British
National Crime Squad, the Associated Press said.
</P>
<P>
"People try to smuggle in smut just like they try to smuggle
dope across the border and we're ready to pounce on them," said
Dick Weart, a special agent for the U.S. Customs Service, which
carried out 32 raids in 22 U.S. states with the help of state and
local police.
</P>
<P>
Police confiscated boxes of pornography, various software
materials and hardware that were part and parcel of the ring
during the raids, Weart said.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 arrests worldwide were made Wednesday, and U.S.
Customs predicted there would be more as officials evaluated the
evidence collected. Hundreds of people are suspected of being
connected with the pornography ring.
</P>
<P>
"The people who exploit children in this way think they can
hide in cyberspace. They are wrong. We will find them and bring
them to justice," U.S. Customs Commissioner Raymond Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
The raids occurred in Australia, Austria, Belgium, Britain,
Finland, France, Germany, Italy, Norway, Portugal, Sweden and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
To join the child pornography ring, members had to have
multiple images of child pornography, and some had as many as
10,000 pictures, U.S. Customs said. The ring allegedly began in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The investigation, code-named "Cathedral," linked members of
the Wonderland Club through the types of images they allegedly
sent to each other. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980903.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Super League Organisers Reveal More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A total of 132 clubs from all
of UEFA's 51 member countries would take part in a planned
European Super League and associated Pro Cup, according to
proposals announced by the organisers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Media Partners, the Milan-based company behind the Super
League plans, said it had met representatives of Europe's leading
clubs on Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Its president Rodolfo Hecht said he was confident the new
structure would be in place for the 2000/2001 season.
</P>
<P>
Hecht said in a statement that the league would feature
18"founder member" clubs, two more than announced in the original
plans.
</P>
<P>
They would be selected on their performance over 10 years and
would be guaranteed a place for three seasons. A second division
of 18 (also up from 16) would be invited to play based on their
performance during the previous season.
</P>
<P>
The Pro Cup would involve 96 clubs in a knock-out
competition. Clubs would qualify on the basis of domestic league
and cup performances.
</P>
<P>
Hecht said the new competitions would take place midweek so as
not to interfere with domestic leagues.
</P>
<P>
That would seem feasible only if Media Partners operated
within UEFA's authority or if the European Community outlawed
UEFA or FIFA attempts to ban Super League clubs from playing in
domestic leagues or banned their players from representing their
countries.
</P>
<P>
UEFA and FIFA have both come out firmly against the Media
Partners' plans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
