<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Star Shuttlers Advance in Asian Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The JVC Asian Badminton
Championships entered its second day Wednesday with all star
shuttlers entering the third round.
</P>
<P>
After the 99 matches in the two days, the top 16 players or
pairs for men's singles, ladies' singles, men's doubles and
ladies'doubles have emerged, while the top eight pairs for the
mixed doubles were also decided.
</P>
<P>
China's Sun Jun, No. 1 seed for men's singles and the world's
No. 2, moved one step closer to the championship with a
convincing two-game victory over his opponent, Thushara
Edirisinghe of Sri Lanka, in the third round of men's singles.
</P>
<P>
Other seeds all won easily as their rivals were rather weak.
</P>
<P>
However, the game will be harder on Thursday, the third day of
the five-day events, as some 32 matches will be held to decide
the top four players or pairs in each of the five events, namely
men's singles, ladies' singles, men's doubles, ladies' doubles
and mixed doubles.
</P>
<P>
More than 250 players from 24 Asian countries and regions
gather here to vie for the 13,600 U.S. dollar prize money of the
championships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
