<HEADLINE> British Sports Authorities Consider Blood Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- British athletics and cycling
chiefs are considering independently to introduce blood test to
find drug abuse in their sports.
</P>
<P>
Dave Moorcroft, the former 5,000 meters world record holder
who now heads the athletics federation, said on Wednesday: "It is
a hugely complicated issue.
</P>
<P>
"But we must explore the possibility of introducing random and
voluntary blood tests, even if it is only initially in the form
of research."
</P>
<P>
British Cycling Federation president Brian Cookson said he had
been "appalled and dismayed" by the scandals surrounding this
year's Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
Cookson said he intended to call for tougher doping control
measures, including blood tests, at a conference to be staged by
the international cycling body, the UCI, in the Netherlands next
month.
</P>
<P>
Two perfomance-enhancing substances -- Human Growth
Hormone(HGH) and erythropoietin (EPO) -- are now believed to be
in widespread use, mainly because they remain undetectable in
urine tests.
</P>
<P>
EPO, by acting on the oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood,is
believed to have become hugely popular in endurance
sports,including cycling, distance running and swimming.
</P>
<P>
"I'm keen to see blood samples introduced, so that we can test
for a range of drugs, not just EPO and growth hormones,"Cookson
said.
</P>
<P>
"With blood tests you get better, more accurate results than
is possible with urine analysis and you are able to detect the
use of masking agents which many people suspect are in use by
steroid takers." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
