<HEADLINE> Dow Slips and Fails to Continue Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A late selling spree today
cut short the Dow industrial's strive to extend Tuesday's rebound
from August's scary selloff.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average, down 512.61 on Monday and up
288.23 Tuesday, fell 45.06 points to close at 7,782.37. The
average of 30 blue chips had been holding onto gains until the
final minutes of trading.
</P>
<P>
At one point, the Dow was up as much as 125.13 at 7,952.56, or
44 points above where it began the year, at 7,908.25.
</P>
<P>
Some other major indicators rose, however, including the Nasdaq
composite index, which added to Tuesday's record point gain.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by about a 13-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 891.58 million
shares, down from 1,204.93 million shares Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 3.99 at 990.27, the
NYSE composite index was down 1.30 at 494.63, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index was up 13.93 at 602.61.
</P>
<P>
The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index was up 15.41 to
1,590.50.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 5.21 to 353.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street came roaring back Tuesday with the Dow gaining 288
points, the second-biggest daily point gain ever. The market came
on record trading of more than 1.2 billion shares on the New York
Stock Exchange. Trading was heavy today, but volume of 891.6
million was well below Tuesday's pace, when the Dow gained 3.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
Today's decline left the Dow 16.7 percent below its record of
9,337.97 set on July 17.  
</P>
</TEXT>
