<HEADLINE> U.S., DPRK to Resume Talks on Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States and the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) will resume talks in
New York on Thursday, the State Department said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A State Department official said DPRK's negotiators, who called
off planned talks in New York on Tuesday while awaiting
instructions from Pyongyang, had agreed to meet with U.S.
officials on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"So we're going to start talks again tomorrow morning," the
official told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The United States, South Korea, Japan and the European Union
had planned a meeting on Tuesday to discuss how to fund
construction of two nuclear power reactors for the DPRK, but the
meeting was suspended after the DPRK test-fired a new longer-range
missiled over Japanese islands and into the Pacific Ocean on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We were on the verge of doing a burden-sharing agreement but
we felt at this particular time it wasn't the moment to be
moving forward with that particular part of it," the official said.
</P>
<P>
He said the four partners will "come back to it a little
later when the environment is better."
</P>
<P>
The four partners in KEDO (Korean Peninsula Energy
Development Organization) want to see "what comes from these
talks" between the United States and the DPRK, the official
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
