<HEADLINE> Romania: Trade Deficit Is Forecast to Over Three </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 2 (Xinhua) - Analysts here estimate that
1998 will score for Romania the "sad" record of getting to a
foreign trade deficit of 3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The trade balance deficit for the first half of this year
stands at 1335.7 million U.S. dollars, which means 24.4 percent
higher than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The industrial production constantly fell, while Romanian
export companies confined themselves to sell low-processed
products. In the meanwhile, the Romanian companies prove to be
unable to face foreign competition and the domestic market is
envaded with much cheaper import products.
</P>
<P>
"The downgrading of Romania's foreign trade is easy to
forecast," the President of Romania's Association of Export and
Import Companies Mihai Ionescu pointed out, adding that the
"Romanian exports quality has seriously degraded".
</P>
<P>
For instance, said Mihai Ionescu, the imbalance between the
cattle export and the beef and beef products one is worth
mentioning. In 1993, Romania exported about 24 thousand head of
cattle, while in 1997, 100 thousand heads, which marks a four-time
increase. Figures show that Romania's exports of fresh beef, which
is the first processing stage, went down from 6,500 tones to 564
tones, over the same period. Besides, this happened in a field
where Romania did have the necessary equipment to process meat so
to get a better price.
</P>
<P>
The same thing occurred also in metallurgy, where the 1997 iron
and steel bars export rose three times against 1993, while the
wire export reached 133 thousand tones at 1997-end, against 58
thousand tones in 1993. In exchange, the export of metal products
with a higher processing stage fell down. The rolled bars exports
slumped from 37 thousand tones to 18 thousand tones, over
1993-1997. The products in the third stage of processing, such as
cookers, television receivers, cars (with an eight-time drop in
exports over 1993-1997), vans.
</P>
<P>
The petrochemical industry also registered important losses,
as, while coke, oil, caustic soda and soda ash were quite
successfully sold abroad, the toluene (a most refined product)
exports diminished.
</P>
<P>
The export protection lacks almost totally, Mihai Ionescu says.
Until 1997, there had been a 50 percent cut in the tax on profit,
but it was consequently cancelled. Romania has become Europe's only
country not to have export incentives, Mihai Ionescu added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
