<HEADLINE> Swazi King Supports U.N. Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DURBAN, September 2 (Xinhua)--King Mswati III of Swaziland
Wednesday expressed his support for those countries calling for
the reform of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the 12th Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) heads of
state and government conference in Durban, Mswati III said: " We
endorse the African view that the continent should have two
permanent seats on the U.N. Security Council and have voting
powers."
</P>
<P>
The king said that Non-Aligned countries had a right for their
voice to be heard.
</P>
<P>
He also gave his backing for nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the 12th NAM summit, South
African President Nelson Mandela, as the new chairman of the NAM,
also called for the restructuring of the U.N. to ensure that the
restructured organization become reflective and responsive to the
interests of the larger world which the NAM represents. 
</P>
