<HEADLINE> Kabila Insists Rebels Cease Fire First </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Zhao Yi)
</P>
<P>
DURBAN, September 2 (Xinhua) -- President Laurent Kabila of
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) said Wednesday night that
it is rebel forces that should cease fire first.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, who is here to attend the 12th Non-Aligned Movement
summit, told reporters that it is "aggressors" who should start
cease-fire first, apparently referring to the rebel forces in the
DRC and the alleged troops from Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Referring to deployment of troops from Zimbabwe, Angola and
Namibia, Kabila insisted that the troops from the three southern
African countries should not be described as foreign troops.
</P>
<P>
"They are not foreign troops. We invited them," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked when they will leave the DRC, Kabila said: "It all
depends on the situation."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Kabila also made commitment to hold free and fair
elections by June 1999, despite what he termed as the aggression
of neighboring Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The conflict would not deter his adminsitration's efforts to
rebuild the DRC into a great nation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kabila confirmed that he met United Nations Secretary General
Kofi Annan here early in the day, but he declined to give any
details about their talks.
</P>
<P>
The DRC president said that he was due to leave for home
Thursday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
