<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British MPs Endorse Anti-terror Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The British government's
anti-terror bill was passed on Wednesday by the parliament with
317 MPs voting for and 87 voting against.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair, who summoned parliament back from
its summer holiday to pass the new law after a bomb killed 28
people in the Northern Irish town of Omagh last month, said the
bill was "an exceptional measure to mop up these last recalcitrant
renegade groups."
</P>
<P>
The Criminal Justice (Terrorism and Conspiracy) Bill will make
it easier to secure convictions for membership of outlawed groups
and to seize assets used in guerrilla activities.
</P>
<P>
Courts will be able to take into account evidence from a single
senior police officer about membership of such groups and will be
allowed to draw an inference of guilt from the refusal of an
accused person to answer police questions.
</P>
<P>
The bill will also target people living in Britain who plot to
commit serious crimes, including guerrilla attacks, abroad.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Conservative and Liberal Democrat leaders said their
parties would support the bill but backbenchers on all sides
complained loudly that Blair was treating the House of Commons as
a rubber stamp.
</P>
<P>
Senior MPs from all parties complained that they were being
asked to rush through the complex legislation in six hours, with
no time for full debate or amendments. The text of the law was
only published on Tuesday evening and debate will be cut short
under procedures known as a guillotine.
</P>
<P>
The Irish parliament also met on Wednesday to push through a
series draconian measures to make it easier to charge and convict
members of banned guerrilla organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
